{"title_page": "Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports", "text_new": "{{current related||2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Impact of coronavirus}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has caused the most significant disruption to the [[2020 in sports|worldwide sporting calendar]] since [[World War II]]. [[Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Across the world]] and to varying degrees, sports events have been cancelled or postponed.<ref name=\"BBC overview\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: How the virus has impacted sporting events around the world |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/51605235 |website=BBC |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1= |first1= |title=How the coronavirus is affecting sports leagues and events |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-09/coronavirus-latest-news-sports-world |website=Los Angeles Times |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Multiple event competitions==\nThe [[2020 Arctic Winter Games]] were cancelled,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/arctic-winter-games-cancelled-coronavirus-1.5490055 |title = 'Shocked and disappointed': Arctic Winter Games cancelled due to coronavirus concerns &#124; CBC News}}</ref> while the [[2020 ASEAN Para Games]] were postponed.<ref name=philippinencaa>{{cite news |last1=Villar |first1=Joey |title=NCAA succumbs to coronavirus scare, postpones all high school games |url=https://www.philstar.com/sports/2020/02/07/1991189/ncaa-succumbs-coronavirus-scare-postpones-all-high-school-games |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> In the Philippines, the [[NCAA Season 95]] and [[UAAP Season 82]] were both indefinitely suspended.<ref name=philippinencaa/><ref name=pba/> NCAA Season 95 was terminated on 19 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/university/ncaa/255125-season-95-terminated-coronavirus-luzon-lockdown|title=NCAA Season 95 terminated|last=Go|first=Beatrice|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Summer Olympics===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the 2020 Summer Olympics}}\nThe 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic itself has been a concern for the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] which were scheduled to take place in [[Tokyo]] starting at the end of July. Due to the Olympics, the [[Government of Japan|country's government]] has been taking extra precautions to help minimise the outbreak's worst impact.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/abe-brushes-worries-virus-impact-tokyo-olympics-68719487 |title=Abe brushes aside worries of virus impact on Tokyo Olympics |first=A. B. C. |last=News |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/01/tokyo-2020-organisers-fight-false-rumours-olympics-cancelled-over-coronavirus-crisis |title=Tokyo 2020 organisers fight false rumours Olympics cancelled over coronavirus crisis |first=Justin |last=McCurry |date=February 1, 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> However, qualifying events are being canceled or postponed almost daily.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sltrib.com/sports/2020/03/10/coronavirus-already/ |title=Coronavirus already causing Olympic chaos at qualifying events |first=Ellingworth |last=Ellingworth |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Salt Lake Tribune}}</ref> There have been suggestions that the 2020 Olympics be moved to [[London]] in light of the situation. Governor of Tokyo [[Yuriko Koike]] indicated at the end of February 2020 that such a move was not under consideration at the moment.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Keh|first=Andrew|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/sports/olympics/tokyo-coronavirus.html|title=Grappling With Coronavirus, Tokyo Olympic Leaders Have No Good Options|date=2020-02-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|last2=Dooley|first2=Ben|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-02-21/tokyo-governor-2020-olympics-coronavirus|title=Tokyo governor: 'Inappropriate' to suggest moving 2020 Olympics because of coronavirus|date=2020-02-21|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nThe traditional [[Olympic flame]] lighting ceremony in [[Olympia, Greece]], to mark the start of the [[2020 Summer Olympics torch relay]] was held on March 12 without spectators.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-2020-flame/tokyo-2020-torch-lit-behind-closed-doors-in-ancient-olympia-idUSKBN20Z1EO |title=Tokyo 2020 torch lit behind closed doors in ancient Olympia |website=Reuters |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, it was announced that the Summer Olympics would be postponed to 2021, still to be held in Tokyo. Six days later, the Olympics made a reschedule date to twelve months from the original scheduled dates of 24 July to 9 August 2020, to 23 July to 8 August 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/fc044c3fa987a60534a804046215f3de|title=On hold: Tokyo Olympics postponed to 2021|date=2020-03-24|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=IOC_2021_Dates>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-ipc-tokyo-2020-organising-committee-and-tokyo-metropolitan-government-announce-new-dates-for-the-olympic-and-paralympic-games-tokyo-2020 |title=IOC, IPC, Tokyo 2020 Organising Committee and Tokyo Metropolitan Government Announce New Dates for the Olympic and Paralympic Games Tokyo 2020 |date=2020-03-30 |website=olympic.org |access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Gaelic games===\nThe [[Gaelic games]] of [[Gaelic football|football]], [[hurling]], [[camogie]] and [[ladies' Gaelic football|ladies' football]] \u2013 mostly played in [[Ireland]] \u2013 saw all competitions suspended from 12 March 2020. The [[2020 National Hurling League|National Hurling League]], [[2020 National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]], [[2020 National Camogie League|National Camogie League]] and [[2020 Ladies' National Football League|Ladies' National Football League]] were suspended, with competitions not intended to resume until 29 March at the earliest.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaa.ie/news-archive/news/gaa-camogie-association-and-the-lgfa-suspend-all-activity/|title=GAA, Camogie Association, and the LGFA suspend all activity|website=www.gaa.ie}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.balls.ie/gaa/gaa-camogie-association-gaa-suspend-activities-march-29th-427885|title=GAA, Camogie Association And LGFA Suspend All Activity Until March 29th|first=P. J.|last=Browne|website=Balls.ie}}</ref> On 17 March, the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) confirmed that [[2020 Connacht Senior Football Championship|the opening fixture]] of the [[2020 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] \u2013 due to have taken place at [[Gaelic Park]] in [[Riverdale, Bronx|The Bronx]] on 3 May \u2013 had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/gaa/galway-and-new-york-clash-first-major-casualty-of-pandemic-988773.html|title=Galway and New York clash first major casualty of pandemic|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|first=Eoghan|last=Cormican|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NCAA===\nOn March 11, 2020, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) \u2014 the main U.S. sanctioning body for [[College athletics in the United States|college athletics]] \u2014 initially announced that its winter-semester championships and tournaments, including its popular [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men's basketball tournament]] (widely known as \"March Madness\"), would be conducted with \"only essential staff and limited family attendance\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2020/03/11/ncaa-tournament-fans-banned-due-to-coronavirus-concerns/5024027002/ |title=NCAA men's and women's basketball tournaments will not include fans due to coronavirus concerns |first=Tom |last=Schad |newspaper=USA Today |date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> However, the following day, the NCAA announced that all remaining championship events for the 2019\u201320 academic year would be cancelled entirely. This marked the first cancellation in the 81-year history of the NCAA basketball tournament.<ref name=\"NCAA cancellations\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |title=NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships |publisher=NCAA |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===BUCS===\nOn 16 March 2020, [[British Universities and Colleges Sport]], the UK organisation for university sport, announced that all fixtures from 17 March to 1 April would not take place. Some individual events, like the [[orienteering]] and [[windsurfing]] championships were cancelled entirely, while others were postponed indefinitely.<ref name=\"BUCS Cancellations\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bucs.org.uk/update-covid-19-coronavirus.html|title=BUCS Statement regarding CoVid-19|publisher=BUCS|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Alpine skiing ==\nThe [[2019\u201320 FIS Alpine Ski World Cup]] ended two weeks earlier after World Cup races in Sweden, Slovenia, and Italy scheduled for March were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/international-ski-federation/news-multimedia/news/fis-alpine-ski-world-cup-finals-cortina-ita-cancelled |title=FIS Alpine Ski World Cup Finals in Cortina Cancelled |date=6 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/alpine-skiing/alpine-news-multimedia/news-multimedia/news/test2/audi-fis-women-s-world-cup-races-in-are-swe-cancelled |title=Audi FIS Women's World Cup races in Are (SWE) Cancelled |date=11 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/alpine-skiing/alpine-news-multimedia/news-multimedia/news/test2/audi-fis-men-s-world-cup-races-in-kranjska-gora-slo-cancelled |title=Audi FIS Men's World Cup races in Kranjska Gora (SLO) Cancelled |date=12 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> An earlier February World Cup race was moved from China to Austria.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/olympics/skiing/story/_/id/28600579/world-cup-ski-races-canceled-china-move-austria |title=World Cup ski races canceled in China move to Austria |date=30 January 2020 |website=[[ESPN]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=29 March 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Archery==\nThe opening stage of the [[2020 Archery World Cup]], scheduled to be held in [[Guatemala City]], [[Guatemala]] from 20 to 26 April, was postponed. Other events postponed include the [[Pan American Archery Championships]], which were scheduled to be held in [[Monterrey]], [[Mexico]], from 23 to 29 March, and the [[European Para-Archery Championships]], which were scheduled to be held in [[Olbia]], [[Italy]], from 18 to 26 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=International Archery Suspended Until 30 April due to COVID-19 Outbreak |url=https://worldarchery.org/news/178285/international-archery-suspended-until-30-april-due-covid-19-outbreak-1 |website=World Archery |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Association football==\nOn 13 March 2020, FIFA announced that clubs did not have to release players to their national teams during the international windows of March and April 2020, while players also had the option to decline a call-up without any consequences. FIFA also recommended that all international matches during these windows be postponed, though the final decision was left to the competition organisers or member associations for [[Exhibition game#International football|friendly]] matches.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/who-we-are/news/fifa-statement-x8681 |title=FIFA statement |work=[[FIFA]] |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 28 March, [[2020 Belarusian Premier League|Belarusian Premier League]] and [[2019\u201320 Liga Primera de Nicaragua|Liga Primera de Nicaragua]] were the only two top flight national football leagues not suspended.<ref>[http://www.la-razon.com/marcas/futbol-covid-19-nicaragua-bielorrusia_0_3338666136.html En el planeta f\u00fatbol, solo Nicaragua y Bielorrusia contin\u00faan con sus torneos] la-razon.com {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n===Africa===\nOn 17 March 2020, [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] announced that the [[2020 African Nations Championship]] had been postponed to a later date due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cafonline.com/news-center/news/statement-on-total-chan-cameroon-2020|title=Statement on Total CHAN Cameroon 2020|publisher=CAF|date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nIn China, the [[2020 Chinese Super League]] was postponed as a result of the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecfa.cn/lstz/20200130/28537.html |title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u8db3\u534f\u5173\u4e8e2020\u8d5b\u5b63\u56fd\u5185\u8db3\u7403\u8d5b\u4e8b\u5ef6\u671f\u5f00\u59cb\u7684\u516c\u544a |work=Chinese Football Association |date=January 30, 2020 |accessdate=January 30, 2020 |language=zh}}</ref> In Hong Kong, the [[2020 Lunar New Year Cup]] was cancelled on January 23.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chan |first1=Kin-wa |title=Wuhan coronavirus: Lunar New Year Cup cancelled by government just hours after HKFA promotes the event |url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/hong-kong/article/3047415/wuhan-virus-lunar-new-year-cup-go-ahead-hong-kong-despite |website=South China Morning Post |date=January 23, 2020 |accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> Other leagues in Asia were affected, including South Korea's [[2020 K League 1|K League 1]] and Japan's [[2020 J1 League|J1 League]].<ref>{{cite news |title=K-League season postponed as COVID-19 spreads in South Korea |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/24/soccer/k-league-season-postponed-covid-19-spreads-south-korea/#.Xms5EqgzaUk |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Japan Times |agency=Associated Press |date=February 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Orlowitz |first1=Dan |title=Amid COVID-19 outbreak, J. League postpones all matches until March 15 |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/25/soccer/j-league/jleague-cancels-levain-cup-coronavirus/#.Xms5FagzaUk |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Japan Times |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 AFC Champions League|AFC Champions League]] and [[2020 AFC Cup|AFC Cup]] was also impacted, a number of group stage and play-off matches being postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-champions-league/latest/news/afc-competitions-update |title=AFC Competitions update |publisher=Asian Football Confederation |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, 2020, FIFA and AFC announced that [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] matches due to take place in March and June 2020 were postponed to later dates due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-asian-cup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers |publisher=AFC |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Play-off matches between South Korea and China in the [[2020 AFC Women's Olympic Qualifying Tournament]] were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers |publisher=FIFA.com |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn India, the remaining [[2019\u201320 I-League|I-League]] matches were postponed and the [[2020 Indian Super League Final|Indian Super League final]] was played behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-aiff.com/article/aiff-statement-10 |title=AIFF Statement |publisher=All India Football Federation|date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe championships of all [[Central Asian Football Association]] members were suspended.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Europe===\nIn Europe, various knockout matches in the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] were played [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] in February and March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2639297.html |title=Update on UEFA competition matches being played this week |work=UEFA |date=February 26, 2020 |access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2640496.html |title=Update on UEFA competition matches |work=UEFA |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> On March 12, 2020, [[UEFA]] announced that the elite qualification round of the men and women's under-17 and under-19 youth international tournaments had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2640886.html |title=Postponement of Youth tournaments |publisher=UEFA.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The following day, UEFA postponed all fixtures for the following week in the Champions League, Europa League and [[2019\u201320 UEFA Youth League|Youth League]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/about-uefa/news/newsid=2641054.html |title=All of next week's UEFA matches postponed |work=UEFA |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany of the domestic European leagues were impacted in February and March 2020. After various fixtures were rescheduled or played behind closed doors, [[2019\u201320 Serie A|Serie A]] was postponed on March 9, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/51808683 |title=Coronavirus: All sport in Italy to be suspended because of outbreak |date=March 9, 2020 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> On March 12, [[2019\u201320 La Liga|La Liga]] and the [[2019\u201320 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] were suspended for at least two weeks after a [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] basketball player tested positive for the virus, which resulted in Real Madrid's footballers being put in quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |title=Real Madrid players in quarantine and La Liga suspended due to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/12/real-madrid-players-in-quarantine-and-la-liga-suspended-due-to-coronavirus |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The [[2019\u201320 Eredivisie|Eredivisie]] was also suspended,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraaf.nl/sport/246406552/streep-door-eredivisie-en-interlands-van-oranje-in-maart|title=Streep door Eredivisie \u00e9n interlands van Oranje in maart|date=March 12, 2020|website=Telegraaf}}</ref> while [[2019\u201320 Ligue 1|Ligue 1]] and the [[2019\u201320 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] followed suit shortly afterwards.<ref name=\"BBC overview\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lfp.fr/Articles/COMMUNIQU\u00c9S/2020/03/13/communique-de-la-lfp |title=Communiqu\u00e9 de la LFP |publisher=lfp.fr |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/coronavirus-what-games-are-cancelled-postponed-behind-closed-doors-overview-10410 |title=Coronavirus: Bundesliga suspended until 2 April |publisher=Bundesliga |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, the [[2019\u201320 Premier League|Premier League]] match between Manchester City and Arsenal, due to be played the next day, was postponed after a number of Arsenal players made close contact with Olympiacos owner [[Evangelos Marinakis]], who had tested positive for [[coronavirus]], when the two teams had met in the Europa League 13 days earlier.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester City vs. Arsenal postponed after players exposed to Olympiakos owner Evangelos Marinakis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/english-premier-league/story/4071980/arsenal-vs-manchester-city-postponed-after-players-exposed-to-olympiakos-owner-evangelos-marinakis |website=ESPN |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Arsenal manager [[Mikel Arteta]] tested positive for the disease, prompting the team's Premier League match against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] for that weekend to also be postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arsenal boss Mikel Arteta tests positive for coronavirus, match against Brighton postponed |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/arsenal/story/4073648/arsenal-boss-mikel-arteta-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-squad-set-to-self-isolate |website=ESPN |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> As of March 13, there has been at least one recorded case of the disease affecting a player in the aforementioned leagues; Serie A footballers [[Daniele Rugani]] and [[Manolo Gabbiadini]], [[2. Bundesliga]] footballer [[Timo H\u00fcbers]], and Premier League footballer [[Callum Hudson-Odoi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/151101/official-gabbiadini-has-coronavirus |title=Official: Gabbiadini has Coronavirus |publisher=Football Italia |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2020/03/13/chelsea-fc-training-facility-will-undergo-partial-closure-after- |title=CHELSEA FC TRAINING FACILITY WILL UNDERGO PARTIAL CLOSURE AFTER MEN'S TEAM PLAYER TESTED POSITIVE FOR COVID-19 |publisher=Chelsea Football Club |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Rugani tested positive while being [[Asymptomatic carrier|asymptomatic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51844945 |title=Coronavirus: Juventus centre-back Daniele Rugani tests positive for virus |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, English elite football was suspended until early April, including the [[Premier League]], [[English Football League]], [[FA Women's Super League]] and [[FA Women's Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended until 3 April at earliest |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nBy 19 March, the [[2020 Belarusian Premier League|Belarusian Premier League]] was the only active top flight in all 55 UEFA member associations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.as.com/en/2020/03/19/football/1584633269_267045.html |title=Amid global coronavirus pandemic, new Belarus season starts |work=AS |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConcerns were raised regarding [[UEFA Euro 2020]], being held in twelve host cities across Europe, and the potential impact of the coronavirus on players, staff and tournament visitors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Homewood |first=Brian |location=Rome |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy-soccer/uefa-says-monitoring-coronavirus-not-yet-clear-if-any-impact-on-euro-2020-idUSKBN20J1XS |title=UEFA says monitoring coronavirus, not yet clear if any impact on Euro 2020 |agency=Associated Press |date=February 25, 2020 |access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> UEFA president [[Aleksander \u010ceferin]] said the organisation was confident that the situation could be dealt with, while general secretary [[Theodore Theodoridis]] stated that UEFA was maintaining contact with the [[World Health Organization]] and national governments regarding the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last=MacInnes |first=Paul |location=Amsterdam |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/03/uefa-congress-ceferin-coronavirus-dark-scenarios |title=Uefa's Ceferin warns against fixating on 'dark scenarios' over coronavirus threat |work=The Guardian |date=March 3, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> UEFA announced that a [[videoconference]] would be held on March 17 with representatives of its 55 member associations, along with a [[FIFPro]] representative and the boards of the [[European Club Association]] and [[European Leagues]], to discuss the response to the outbreak for domestic and European competitions, including Euro 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/about-uefa/news/newsid=2640887.html |title=UEFA calls meeting of European Football Stakeholders |work=UEFA |date=March 12, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The tournament was moved by 12 months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/mediaservices/mediareleases/newsid=2641071.html |title=UEFA postpones EURO 2020 by 12 months |work=UEFA |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn March 12, 2020, the [[2020 CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF Champions League]] was suspended with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.concacafchampionsleague.com/en/article/concacaf-suspends-scotiabank-concacaf-champions-league-with-immediate-effect |title=Concacaf suspends Scotiabank Concacaf Champions League with immediate effect |publisher=CONCACAF Champions League |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The same day, [[2020 Major League Soccer season|Major League Soccer]] was suspended for 30 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/03/12/major-league-soccer-suspends-season-30-days-impact-coronavirus |title=MLS suspends 2020 season for 30 days due to coronavirus |publisher=mlssoccer.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Women's Soccer League]] (NWSL), whose [[2020 National Women's Soccer League season|season]] was not scheduled to start until April 18, canceled its preseason matches,<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.nwslsoccer.com/news/article/statement-from-nwsl-commissioner-lisa-baird-regarding-the-2020-season |title=Statement from NWSL Commissioner Lisa Baird regarding the 2020 season |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> and also imposed a moratorium on team training that initially ran through March 22.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.nwslsoccer.com/news/article/covid-19-resources-and-updates-for-nwsl-fans |title=COVID-19 resources and updates for NWSL fans |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> On March 19, Major League Soccer's suspension was extended to a target return date of May 10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/03/19/mls-extends-season-suspension-accordance-cdc-guidance-covid-19 |title=MLS extends season suspension in accordance with CDC guidance on COVID-19 |publisher=mlssoccer.com |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe day after MLS was initially postponed, all [[CONCACAF]] competitions scheduled for the next month were suspended. Match week 10 of Mexican [[Liga MX]] was played but as of March 15, league executives have now taken the decision to postpone Liga MX activity until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/article/concacaf-suspends-all-its-competitions-scheduled-to-take-place-over-the-next-30-days |title=CONCACAF Champions League |publisher=CONCACAF |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 Major Arena Soccer League season]] was terminated early, effective March 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maslsoccer.com/news/major-arena-soccer-league-to-end-regular-season-ef|title=MAJOR ARENA SOCCER LEAGUE TO END REGULAR SEASON EFFECTIVE IMMEDIATELY|publisher=Major Arena Soccer League|website=maslsoccer.com|first=Jeff|last=Husted|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[USL Championship]] suspended the [[2020 USL Championship season|2020 season]] on March 12, for at least 30 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uslchampionship.com/news_article/show/1094891|title=USL Championship Temporarily Suspends Play|publisher=uslchampionship.com|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Cricket in the West Indies|West Indies cricket championship]] was suspended due to the pandemic and [[Barbados]] was declared the champion on March 24.<ref>[https://apnews.com/435405d82ed4d043a7998c2a32fc8e87 Barbados declared winners of West Indies championship] AP, 24 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===Oceania===\nOn March 9, 2020, the [[Oceania Football Confederation]] announced that all tournaments were postponed until May 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=OFC tournaments, workshops, training and courses postponed until 6 May |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc-tournaments-workshops-training-and-courses-postponed-until-6-may/ |publisher=OFC |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===South America===\nOn March 12, 2020, FIFA announced that the first two rounds of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|South American qualification for the 2022 World Cup]] due to take place in March 2020 were postponed to later dates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers-in-south-america |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers in South America |publisher=FIFA.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The same day, CONMEBOL announced that the [[2020 Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores]] would be temporarily suspended.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-conmebol-libertadores-queda-suspendida-temporalmente |title=La CONMEBOL Libertadores queda suspendida temporalmente |publisher=CONMEBOL.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15 all top-tier football in Brazil was suspended until April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/eb6fe061d42f1c68f151697dfe25f1d8|title=The Latest: T-Wolves' Towns donating $100K to Mayo Clinic|date=March 15, 2020|website=AP NEWS}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March CONMEBOL announced that the 2020 edition of [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] was postponed to 2021.<ref>{{cite news |title=Euro 2020 and Copa Am\u00e9rica Are Postponed for a Year |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/sports/euro-2020-postponed.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020|last1=Panja |first1=Tariq }}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n\nThe [[2021 World Athletics Indoor Championships|2020 World Athletics Indoor Championships]] were scheduled to be held from 13 to 15 March in [[Nanjing]], [[China]], but were postponed until March 2021.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Athletics to postpone World Athletics Indoor Championships Nanjing 2020 |url=https://www.worldathletics.org/news/press-releases/indoor-championships-nanjing-2020-postponed |website=World Athletics |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 World Athletics Half Marathon Championships]] was scheduled to be held on 29 March in [[Gdynia]], [[Poland]], but was postponed until October 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Half Marathon Championships in Gdynia to be postponed |url=https://www.worldathletics.org/competitions/world-athletics-half-marathon-championships/news/world-half-marathon-championships-gdynia-post |website=World Athletics |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first three events of the [[2020 Diamond League]], scheduled to be held in [[Qatar]] in April, followed by two events in [[China]] in May, were postponed until later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wanda Diamond League suspends early-season events |url=https://www.diamondleague.com/news/single-news/news/detail/News/wanda-diamond-league-suspends-early-season-events/ |website=Diamond League |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Boston Marathon]], originally scheduled for 20 April, was postponed until 14 September.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-marathon/2020/03/15/2020-boston-marathon-monday-september |title=Marathon Monday in September? Here's what we know so far about the 2020 Boston Marathon's new date |work=Boston.com |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 London Marathon]], scheduled to take place on 26 April, was postponed until 4 October.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234 |title=Coronavirus: London Marathon postponed until October |newspaper=BBC Sport |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The 2020 [[Rome Marathon]] was cancelled.<ref name=\"cancellation.1\">{{cite web |author=user |url=https://www.runromethemarathon.com/en/2020/03/05/acea-run-rome-the-marathon-of-29-march-2020-cancelled/ |title=Acea Run Rome The Marathon of 29 March 2020 cancelled \u2013 ACEA RUN ROME THE MARATHON |publisher=Runromethemarathon.com |date= March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Two Oceans Marathon]], scheduled for 8\u201311 April has been cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twooceansmarathon.org.za/2020-two-oceans-marathon-cancelled-amid-covid-19-pandemic/|title=2020 Two Oceans Marathon cancelled amid COVID-19 Pandemic|website=Two Oceans Marathon|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Three Peaks Race]] originally scheduled for April 25 has been postponed to September 26.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.grough.co.uk/magazine/2020/03/12/coronavirus-claims-second-dales-event-as-three-peaks-race-put-back-to-September |title=Coronavirus claims second Dales event as Three Peaks Race put back to September |date=2020-03-12 |accessdate=2020-03-18 |publisher=Grough |first=Bob |last=Smith}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Grandma's Marathon]], scheduled for June 20, was canceled by the organizers more than 50 days before it was to begin. They announced on March 31 that the marathon, the half-marathon and the 5K would all be canceled. <ref>{{cite web |author1=Grandma's Marathon staff |title=COVID-19 Update/Cancellation |url=https://grandmasmarathon.com/covid19/ |website=grandmasmarathon.com |accessdate=31 March 2020 |location=Duluth, Minnesota |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Australian rules football==\nAt the conclusion of its first round of games, the [[2020 AFL season]] was suspended until May 31 at the earliest,<ref name=\"aussierules\">{{cite web|url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/389109/watch-from-4-30pm-aedt-afl-postpones-season|title=WATCH from 4.30pm AEDT: AFL postpones season|publisher=AFL.com.au|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> while the Finals series of the [[2020 AFL Women's season]] was cancelled after its semi-finals were played with no premiership awarded.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Badminton==\nAll scheduled [[Badminton World Federation]] tournaments were suspended until April 12 due to coronavirus concerns.<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Suspends International Badminton |url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/03/14/bwf-suspends-international-badminton/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=14 March 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> The affected tournaments are [[2020 Swiss Open (badminton)|Swiss Open]], [[2020 India Open|India Open]], [[2020 Orl\u00e9ans Masters|Orl\u00e9ans Masters]], [[2020 Malaysia Open|Malaysia Open]], and [[2020 Singapore Open|Singapore Open]]. Previously the body had suspended the [[2020 German Open (badminton)|German Open]]<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Media Statement on Yonex German Open 2020 |url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/02/26/bwf-media-statement-on-yonex-german-open-2020-2/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=2 March 2020 |date=26 February 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> and pushed the [[2020 Lingshui China Masters|Lingshui China Masters]] from February to May 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Statement on Postponement of Lingshui China Masters |url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/02/01/bwf-statement-on-postponement-of-lingshui-china-masters/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=2 February 2020 |date=1 February 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> The [[2020 Thomas & Uber Cup]] had also been postponed to 15\u201323 August.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Baseball==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2021 World Baseball Classic \u2013 Qualification|qualifying round]] of the [[World Baseball Softball Confederation]]-sanctioned [[2021 World Baseball Classic]], scheduled in [[Tucson, Arizona]], United States in March 2020 was postponed on March 12, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harrigan |first1=Thomas |title=World Baseball Classic qualifier games postponed |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/world-baseball-classic-qualifier-games-postponed |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=MLB.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n\n====Japan====\nOn February 26, 2020, [[Nippon Professional Baseball]] announced that spring training would continue without fans in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japanese baseball to play remainder of preseason without spectators due to virus fears |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/26/baseball/japanese-baseball/japanese-baseball-play-remainder-preseason-without-spectators-due-virus-fears/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Japan Times |agency=Kyodo News |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, the league announced that the start of its [[2020 Nippon Professional Baseball season|2020 season]] would be postponed until April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's pro baseball league delays season start over coronavirus |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/6cba442bcfa8-breaking-news-japan-pro-baseball-to-delay-start-of-season-over-virus-source.html |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |agency=Kyodo News |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Coskrey |first1=Jason |title=BayStars, Tigers managers react to NPB's decision to push back start of season |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/?post_type=sports&p=2526679 |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Japan Times |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2020, the [[Japan High School Baseball Federation]] announced that the [[National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament]], scheduled to begin on March 19, would take place without fans in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's Senbatsu spring HS baseball tourney to be held with no spectators due to virus |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200304/p2a/00m/0na/025000c |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Mainichi |date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> However, on March 11, the governing body of [[high school baseball in Japan]] declared that the tournament had been cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Organizers cancel Spring Koshien due to COVID-19 crisis |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/03/11/baseball/cancel-spring-koshien-coronavirus/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Japan Times |agency=Kyodo News |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's Senbatsu spring HS baseball tournament canceled over coronavirus fears |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200311/p2a/00m/0sp/017000c |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=The Manichi |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The cancellation of the 2020 tournament marked the first time the contest had been cancelled since its establishment in 1924. The tournaments were not formally scheduled between 1942 and 1946, due to [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Koshien cancelation stuns players |url=https://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0006415873 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Japan News |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Spring high school baseball tourney cancelled over coronavirus |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/c9ea2971def3-breaking-news-national-invitational-hs-baseball-tournament-cancelled-due-to-virus.html |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |agency=Kyodo News |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nOpening Day of the [[2020 KBO League season]] was originally scheduled for March 28, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baseball league announces 2020 regular season schedule |archiveurl=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20191216000870 |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=The Korea Herald |agency=Yonhap News Agency |archivedate=December 16, 2019 |date=December 16, 2019 |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191216007100315}}</ref> The [[Korea Baseball Organization]] announced in March that all ten exhibition games would be cancelled, and the start of the regular season would be delayed until April.<ref>{{cite news |title=(LEAD) Pro baseball league postpones start of regular season over coronavirus |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200310005251315?input=tw |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |agency=Yonhap News Agency |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest: South Korean baseball season postponed |url=https://wtmj.com/national/2020/03/12/the-latest-south-korean-baseball-season-postponed/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=WTMJ-TV |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn March 12, 2020, [[Major League Baseball]] suspended all spring training activities. [[Opening Day]] of the [[2020 Major League Baseball season]], scheduled for March 26, was postponed, as was the start of the regular season for [[Minor League Baseball]], which was to begin on April 9.<ref>{{cite news |title=MLB suspends spring training, delays Opening Day at least two weeks |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/28892315/sources-mlb-expected-suspend-spring-training |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |website=[[ESPN.com]] |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/mlb-2020-season-delayed |title=Opening Day delayed at least 2 weeks; Spring Training games cancelled |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlso on March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] announced the suspension of its baseball season and cancellation of the [[2020 College World Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.omaha.com/sports/cws/college-baseball-stunned-after-ncaa-decision-to-cancel-college-world/article_ba4b22b5-7cbd-52a7-b0a0-edb0eba8f079.html|title=College baseball stunned after NCAA decision to cancel College World Series, end season in March|newspaper=Omaha World-Herald|last=Bland|first=Evan|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Basketball==\n\n===Africa===\nThe launch of the [[2020 BAL season|inaugural season]] of the [[Basketball Africa League]] set for March 2020 was delayed due to the coronavirus pandemic. No new date has been announced.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Solomon |first1=Salem |title=Basketball Africa League Delays Inaugural Season Because of Coronavirus |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/basketball-africa-league-delays-inaugural-season-because |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |agency=Voice of America |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nThe [[2019\u201320 Chinese Basketball Association season]] was suspended on 1 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Prewitt|first=Alex|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2020/03/13/cba-coronavirus-nba-allerik-freeman|title=While the NBA Pauses, China Is Ready to Play Again. For Better or Worse|date=March 13, 2020|work=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, [[FIBA]] ordered two [[2021 FIBA Asia Cup qualification|qualifying games for the 2021 FIBA Asia Cup]], [[Philippines men's national basketball team|Philippines]] vs [[Thailand national basketball team|Thailand]] in [[Quezon City]], and [[Japan national basketball team|Japan]] vs. [[China men's national basketball team|China]] in [[Chiba (city)|Chiba]] to be postponed to a later date. This brought the postponed games to three, after FIBA earlier ordered the China vs. [[Malaysia national basketball team|Malaysia]] game in [[Foshan]] to be postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/asiacup/2021/qualifiers/news/three-fiba-asia-cup-2021-qualifier-games-postponed|title=Three FIBA Asia Cup 2021 Qualifier games postponed|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Later that week, the [[Guam national basketball team|Guam]] vs. [[Hong Kong basketball team|Hong Kong]] game in [[Hag\u00e5t\u00f1a, Guam|Hag\u00e5t\u00f1a]] was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/asiacup/2021/qualifiers/news/fiba-asia-cup-2021-qualifier-between-guam-and-hong-kong-postponed|title=FIBA Asia Cup 2021 Qualifier game between Guam and Hong Kong postponed|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Korean Basketball League]] canceled its [[2019\u201320 KBL season|2019\u201320 season]] on 24 March, after playing its last game on 29 February. This comes as the [[Women's Korean Basketball League]] canceled its season a week before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200324000415|title=Men's basketball league cancels season due to coronavirus|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=2020-03-24|website=www.koreaherald.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March, FIBA announced the cancellation of the [[2019 FIBA Under-16 Asian Championship]] in [[Beirut]] and the 2019 FIBA Under-16 Asian Championship for Women in [[Canberra]]. It also postponed the [[Basketball at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 3x3 qualification|3x3 Olympic qualification tournament]] in [[Bangalore]], and rescheduled the 2020 [[FIBA Asia 3x3 Cup]]s in [[Changsha]] and the 2020 FIBA 3x3 Under-17 Asian Cup in [[Cyberjaya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/news/changes-made-to-several-fiba-events-due-to-covid-19-virus|title=Changes made to several FIBA events due to COVID-19 virus|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n====ASEAN Basketball League====\nSeveral fixtures of the [[ASEAN Basketball League]] [[2019\u201320 ABL season|2019\u201320 season]] scheduled on February onwards were rescheduled due to the coronavirus pandemic. In early March 2020, four participating teams, [[Alab Pilipinas]], [[Hong Kong Eastern Basketball Team|Hong Kong Eastern]], [[Macau Black Bears]] and [[Formosa Dreamers]] has released statements urging the suspension of the whole season due to logistical issues posed by COVID-19-related travel measures in Southeast Asia, mainland China and Taiwan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alab Pilipinas, three other teams want ABL to suspend season due to COVID-19 |url=https://sports.mb.com.ph/2020/03/12/alab-pilipinas-three-other-teams-want-abl-to-suspend-season-due-to-covid-19/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, 2020, the league's 2019\u201320 season was postponed indefinitely.<ref name=\"pbateams\">{{cite news |last1=Dalupang |first1=Denison Rey |title=PBA: Teams can't hold practices, scrimmages |url=https://sports.inquirer.net/389302/pba-teams-cant-hold-practices-scrimmages |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Philippines====\nThe [[2020 PBA season|2020 season]] of the [[Philippine Basketball Association]] (PBA) and the [[PBA D-League]] was suspended indefinitely on March 10, 2020. The inaugural of the PBA's 3x3 tournament was also likewise delayed.<ref name=pba>{{cite news |title=PBA suspends games indefinitely due to COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/sports/basketball/729223/pba-suspends-games-indefinitely-due-to-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The PBA management also imposed a two-week prohibition on team \"practices, scrimmages and other related activities\" which took effect on March 14, 2020.<ref name=\"pbateams\"/>\n\n=== Europe ===\n[[Jordi Bertomeu]], CEO of the [[Euroleague]], suspended the games from 14 March to 11 April. The Euroleague previously suspended the [[EuroCup Basketball|Eurocup]]. FIBA also suspended the [[Basketball Champions League]] and the [[FIBA Europe Cup]] starting on 14 March. [[Lietuvos krep\u0161inio lyga|Lithuania]], [[Swedish Basketball League|Sweden]], [[Swiss Basketball League|Switzerland]], [[Slovak Basketball League|Slovakia]] and [[Ukrainian Basketball SuperLeague|Ukraine]] canceled outright their respective first division leagues, naming the teams in the top of the standings as champions. Top flight divisions in [[Liga ACB|Spain]], [[LNB Pro A|France]], [[Basketball Bundesliga|Germany]], [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italy]], [[Israeli Basketball Premier League|Israel]], [[Pro Basketball League|Belgium]], [[Korisliiga|Finland]], [[HT Premijer liga|Croatia]], [[Greek Basket League|Greece]], [[Polish Basketball League|Poland]], [[Cyprus Basketball Division A|Cyprus]] and [[National Basketball League (Czech Republic)|Czech Republic]] suspended its games as of 14 March. The [[ABA League|Adriatic League]] and the [[VTB United League]] suspended its competitions until April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28898393/international-basketball-virtually-shut-coronavirus-concerns|title=International basketball virtually shut down|date=2020-03-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The government of Turkey suspended the [[Basketball Super League]] on 19 March, the last major European league to do so.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2020/03/19/turkey-basketball-soccer-suspended-coronavirus|title=Turkey Suspends Soccer, Basketball Seasons|last=West|first=Jenna|website=Sports Illustrated|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn March 11, 2020, the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) [[Suspension of the 2019\u201320 NBA season|suspended its season]] after [[Utah Jazz]] player [[Rudy Gobert]] tested positive for coronavirus prior to tip-off for a scheduled game against the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref name=\"nba-suspension-of-season\">{{cite web |title=NBA to suspend season following Wednesday's games |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2020/03/11/nba-suspend-season-following-wednesdays-games |website=NBA.com |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Commissioner [[Adam Silver]] stated the next day that this suspension \"will be most likely at least 30 days, and we don't know enough to be more specific than that\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, all [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] conferences in [[NCAA]] [[college basketball]] cancelled their respective tournaments in-progress. The [[Ivy League]] had already called off its tournament prior to the decision, while some conferences, as well as the NCAA for its [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men's]] and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women's]] tournaments, had previously announced that they would conduct their games behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/12/coronavirus-ncaa-conference-tournaments-cancellations.html |title=Big Ten, SEC, ACC scrap conference tournaments, adding to wave of coronavirus-related sports cancellations |last=Eudaily |first=Chris |date=March 12, 2020 |publisher=CNBC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/pac-12-mens-basketball-tournament-canceled-over-coronavirus-pandemic |title=Pac-12 cancels all sports competitions 'until further notice' because of coronavirus |date=March 12, 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28891602/big-ten-sec-american-cancel-conference-tournaments |title=Conference tournaments shut down over virus |date=March 12, 2020 |publisher=ESPN|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The NCAA subsequently cancelled its tournaments outright.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/march-madness-ncaa-tournament-canceled-coronavirus |title=No shining moments: NCAA basketball tournaments are canceled for the first time |date=March 13, 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/coronavirus-updates-ncaa-cancels-championship-competition-for-all-winter-and-spring-sports/ |title=Coronavirus updates: NCAA cancels championship competition for all winter and spring sports |website=CBSSports.com|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Baloncesto Superior Nacional]] of Puerto Rico suspended its season on 14 March.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe [[National Basketball League of Canada]] suspended the remainder of the [[2019\u201320 NBL Canada season|2019-20 season]] on March 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nblcanada.ca/sports/mbkb/2019-20/releases/20200312nqi4na|title=NBLC Suspends Remainder of 2019-20 Season Until Further Notice|website=National Basketball League of Canada|language=en|date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Oceania ===\nIn Australia's [[National Basketball League (Australia)|National Basketball League]], the [[Sydney Kings]] announced 17 March that they would pull out of the [[2020 NBL Finals]] after three games, due to \"a critical mass of relevant and actual concerns related to player welfare and the club's social responsibility\". The NBL had been considering playing Game 4 of the series on 18 March instead of 20 March as originally scheduled to accelerate its completion.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/basketball/nbl/perth-wildcats-disappointed-with-sydney-kings-nbl-grand-final-decision/news-story/2426c7f70f33f5a06e963a4c971365c4|title=NBL Grand Final 2020: Perth Wildcats 'disappointed' with Sydney Kings' NBL Grand Final decision|date=2020-03-17|website=Fox Sports|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/basketball/nbl/breaking-nbl-season-called-off-midfinals-due-to-coronavirus-crisis/news-story/7f707f71310056816e01d8d99e7748cf|title=NBL Grand Final 2020: NBL season called off mid-finals due to coronavirus crisis, Sydney Kings vs Perth Wildcats|date=2020-03-17|website=Fox Sports|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> The decision effectively [[Forfeit (sport)|forfeited]] the series to the [[Perth Wildcats]]\u2014who were leading the best-of-five series 2-1 after Game 3, and were officially announced as NBL champions on 18 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thewest.com.au/sport/perth-wildcats/nbl-grand-final-title-win-the-last-piece-of-the-puzzle-for-stoked-perth-wildcats-ng-b881494184z|title=Title win the last piece of the puzzle for stoked Cats|date=2020-03-19|website=The West Australian|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The series was played behind closed doors beginning with Game 2, and the NBL stated that it would be suspended immediately if any player was diagnosed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/basketball/nbl-grand-final-series-to-be-completed-behind-closed-doors-20200313-p549xx.html|title=NBL grand final series to be completed behind closed doors|last=Ward|first=Roy|date=2020-03-13|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Biathlon ==\nThe [[2019\u201320 Biathlon World Cup]] ended a week and a day earlier than previously scheduled. The World Cup final in Norway was cancelled as was the last day of the penultimate World Cup in Finland.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.biathlonworld.com/news/detail/ibu-statement-on-world-cup-in-oslo |title=Update: IBU Statement on World Cup in Oslo, Kontiolahti and Junior OECH |date=13 March 2020 |website=Biathlon World |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bodybuilding==\nSeveral competitive events in international [[Bodybuilding|competitive bodybuilding]] on the amateur and [[Professional bodybuilding|professional]] levels have seen limitations, postponements, or even cancellations due to concerns about the spread of COVID-19.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nDue to these concerns the 2020 [[Arnold Sports Festival]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]] cancelled its Fitness Expo and, under orders from the state government, held the bodybuilding and physique competitions, including the Arnold Classic, without spectators with exceptions for parents and guardians of minors participating in the competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arnoldsportsfestival.com/visitor-info/media/update-March-3/ |title=UPDATED EVENTS SCHEDULE |work=Arnold Sports Festival |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Similar Arnold Sports Festivals planned to be held in Africa, Australia, and South America were postponed for later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arnoldsportsfestival.com/ |title= ARNOLD SPORTS FESTIVALS IN AUSTRALIA, SOUTH AMERICA & AFRICA HAVE BEEN POSTPONED. NEW DATES TBD |work=Arnolds Sports Festival |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2020, Jim Manion, president of the [[IFBB Professional League]] and the [[National Physique Committee]] announced that competitions planned through to May 10, 2020 in the United States would be postponed for later in the year or cancelled until the 2021 season.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ifbbpro.com/npc-news/npc-ifbb-professional-league-president-jim-manion-addresses-coronavirus-concerns-for-contests-in-the-united-states/ |title= NPC & IFBB Professional League President Jim Manion Addresses Coronavirus Concerns For Contests In The United States |work=IFBB Professional League \u2013 NPC News Online |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bowls==\nThe [[2020 World Outdoor Bowls Championship]] scheduled to be held on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] from 23 May to 7 June 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bowls.com.au/events-page/international-events/world-bowls-championships/|title=2020 World Bowls Championship|publisher=Bowls Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bowlsmalaysia.com/world-events-calendar/|title=WORLD EVENTS CALENDAR|publisher=Bowls Malaysia}}</ref> has been postponed until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bowls.com.au/2020-world-bowls-championships-to-be-postponed-indefinitely/|title=2020 World Bowls Championships to be postponed indefinitely|date=2020-03-17|website=Bowls Australia|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==Castells==\n\nIn response to the shutdown of extracurricular activities for children in [[Catalonia]], the Coordinadora de Colles Castelleres de Catalunya (CCCC), the governing body for [[castell]]s (Catalan human towers), issued a statement on March 10, 2020, recommending the suspension of all castells practices and performances.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mu\u00f1oz |first1=Silvia |title=Primers assajos i diades castelleres suspeses en prevenci\u00f3 pel coronavirus |url=https://www.elmoncasteller.cat/primers-assajos-i-diades-castelleres-suspeses-en-prevencio-pel-coronavirus/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=M\u00f3n Casteller |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|lockdown imposed throughout Spain]] shut down all castells activities throughout Catalonia as of March 15.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prats |first1=David |title=Segon cap de setmana de confinament casteller |url=http://revistacastells.cat/2020/03/segon-cap-de-setmana-de-confinament-casteller/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Revista Castells |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> As of March 25, 2020, there was no word about the potential impact of the pandemic on the biennial [[:ca:XXVIII Concurs de castells de Tarragona|Tarragona Castells Contest]], scheduled for October 3 and 4, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prats |first1=David |title=Madrid, una ciutat en hores baixes |url=http://revistacastells.cat/2020/03/madrid-una-ciutat-en-hores-baixes/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Revista Castells |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Chess ==\nThe [[44th Chess Olympiad]] scheduled to take place in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]] from 5\u201317 August 2020 was postponed and rescheduled for the summer of 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fide.com/news/460 |title=Statement by the FIDE Council regarding the Chess Olympiad |date=24 March 2020 |website=fide.com |publisher=FIDE |access-date=24 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"postponed\">{{cite web |url=https://www.chess.com/news/view/fide-postpones-chess-olympiad-to-2021 |title=FIDE Postpones Chess Olympiad To 2021 |author=Peter Doggers |date=24 March 2020 |publisher=[[Chess.com]] |access-date=24 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe FIDE [[Candidates Tournament 2020]], held in [[Yekaterinburg]], [[Russia]], was suspended at the mid-point of the tournament on 26 March. FIDE decided to postpone the second half of the tournament after Russia announced it would be interrupting air traffic with other countries starting on 27 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.chessbase.com/post/breaking-news-fide-stops-the-candidates-tournament |title=Breaking News: FIDE stops the Candidates Tournament! |date=2020-03-26 |website=Chess News |language=en |access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Cricket==\nThe coronavirus pandemic impacted on several international cricket fixtures and tournaments. The [[2020 ACA Africa T20 Cup Finals]] was scheduled to take place in Kenya in March 2020, before it was postponed in line with the Kenyan government's 30-day ban on international gatherings.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africacricket.com/read_more_news.php?id=145 |title=ACA T20 Africa Cup Kenya 2020 postponed |work=Africa Cricket Association |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.busybuddiesng.com/ncf-closes-lagos-camp-as-coronavirus-forces-postponement-of-africa-cricket-championship/ |title=NCF closes Lagos camp as coronavirus forces postponement of Africa Cricket Championship |work=Busy Buddies |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref> A women's [[2020 Thailand Women's Quadrangular Series|quadrangular series]] was scheduled to take place in Thailand in April 2020,<ref name=\"CV1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cricketireland.ie/news/article/quadrangular-tournament-ahead-for-ireland-women |title=Quadrangular tournament ahead for Ireland Women |work=Cricket Ireland |accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref> but was cancelled a month before it was due to start.<ref name=\"CV2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kncb.nl/en/news/womens-quadrangular-series-in-thailand-called-off/ |title=Women's Quadrangular Series in Thailand called off |work=Royal Dutch Cricket Association |accessdate=March 2, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Malaysia Cricket World Cup Challenge League A]], scheduled to take place in March 2020, was postponed,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/1636508 |title=Men's Cricket World Cup Challenge League A postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref> along with two T20I matches [[Mujib 100 T20 Cup Bangladesh 2020|between a World XI and Asia XI side]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28882792/world-xi-v-asia-xi-matches-postponed-amid-coronavirus-fears |title=World XI v Asia XI matches postponed amid coronavirus fears |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2020, English teams [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] and [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] both cancelled their pre-season warm-up tours to the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/51835256 |title=Worcestershire & Surrey cancel pre-season trips to United Arab Emirates over coronavirus fear |newspaper=BBC Sport |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The following day, Australia Women's [[Australia women's cricket team in South Africa in 2019\u201320|tour to South Africa]] in March 2020 became the first major international series not to go ahead as planned due to coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1219220.html |title=Australia Women won't tour South Africa as scheduled because of coronavirus |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, 2020, the [[2020 United States Tri-Nation Series]] was postponed due to the pandemic and travel restrictions to the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/1645150 |title=Series six of Men's CWC League 2 in USA postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usacricket.org/media-release/mens-cricket-world-cup-league-2-in-usa-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |title=Men's Cricket World Cup League 2 in USA Postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=USA Cricket |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 12, the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]] announced that all remaining matches of the [[Pakistan Super League]]'s ongoing [[2020 Pakistan Super League|fifth season]] being played in [[Karachi]] (where the majority of cases in Pakistan had been concentrated) would be closed to spectators.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2174849/1-coronavirus-fears-psl-matches-karachi-played-empty-stadium/ |title=Covid-19: PSL matches in Karachi to be played in empty stadium |work=The Express Tribune |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/psl-matches-in-karachi-to-be-held-closed-door-without-crowd-coronavirus-outbreak-pandemic-1654922-2020-03-12 |title=Coronavirus pandemic: Pakistan Super League matches in Karachi to be played in front of empty stands |work=India Today |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Everest Premier League]] was also postponed on 12 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everest Premier League 2020 postponed due to coronavirus threat |url=https://www.emergingcricket.com/events/everest-premier-league/everest-premier-league-2020-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-threat/ |website=Emerging Cricket |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI) announced that the start of [[2020 Indian Premier League]] will be postponed from March 29 to April 15.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's official: IPL 2020 postponed to April 15 due to coronavirus |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/top-stories/its-official-ipl-2020-postponed-to-mid-april-due-to-coronavirus/articleshow/74609776.cms |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Times of India}}</ref> Later that day, it cancelled the [[South African cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|ODI matches between India and South Africa on March 15 and 18]], which were originally announced to be played without spectators.<ref>{{cite news |title=India-South Africa series called off due to COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/cricket/coronavirus-india-south-africa-series-called-off-due-to-covid-19-threat/article31061061.ece |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Hindu}}</ref> On the same day, the two-match Test series between [[English cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2019\u201320|Sri Lanka and England]], scheduled to be played in March 2020, was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28896266/england-tour-sri-lanka-cancelled-amid-covid-19-spread |title=England tour of Sri Lanka cancelled amid COVID-19 spread |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The remaining seven matches of the [[2020 Road Safety World Series]] were rescheduled to a later date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldseriest20.com/news/in-the-interest-of-public-safety-security-and-support-to-the-government-road-safety-world-series-rescheduled |title=In the interest of public safety & security and support to the Government, Road Safety World Series rescheduled, new dates to be announced later |date=March 13, 2020 |website=Road Safety World Series |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> It was earlier decided that the remaining seven matches of the tournament would be played behind the closed doors in [[DY Patil Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldseriest20.com/news/unacademy-road-safety-world-series-to-be-played-behind-closed-doors-in-dy-patil-stadium |title=Unacademy Road Safety World Series to be played behind closed doors in DY Patil Stadium |date=March 12, 2020 |website=Road Safety World Series |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2020, the [[New Zealand cricket team in Australia in 2019\u201320|remaining two One Day International (ODI) matches]] of the [[Chappell-Hadlee Trophy]] along with the three-match [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) series [[Australian cricket team in New Zealand in 2019\u201320|between Australia and New Zealand]] were cancelled due to new border restrictions imposed by the New Zealand government.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://es.pn/2U7Ngt5 |title=Australia v NZ cancelled amid travel restrictions |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> The first ODI match of the series had been played on 13 March behind closed doors in Sydney.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1645137 |title=COVID-19 outbreak: Chappell-Hadlee series to be held behind closed doors |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The following day, [[Cricket Australia]] confirmed that the final round of matches in the [[2019\u201320 Sheffield Shield season]] had been cancelled, with [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]] being named as the winners of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28913589/new-south-wales-named-sheffield-shield-winners-final-cancelled |title=New South Wales named Sheffield Shield winners as final cancelled |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[New Zealand Cricket]] cancelled the final two rounds of matches in the [[2019\u201320 Plunket Shield season]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28909068/plunket-shield-cancelled-due-coronavirus-measures,-wellington-named-champions |title=Plunket Shield cancelled due to coronavirus measures, Wellington named champions |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> with [[Wellington cricket team|Wellington]] being named the winners of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120318144/coronavirus-plunket-shield-cancelled-wellington-firebirds-declared-champions |title=Coronavirus: Plunket Shield cancelled, Wellington Firebirds declared champions |work=Stuff |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2020, the remaining play-offs in the [[2020 Pakistan Super League]] were postponed due to a huge spike in the number of coronavirus cases around the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geosuper.tv/latest/4433-pcb-decides-to-call-off-psl-2020-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-report|title=PCB 'postpones' PSL 2020 amid coronavirus outbreak|website=www.geosuper.tv}}</ref> The [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]] tour of Pakistan for a single [[One Day International|ODI]] and a [[Test cricket|Test]] match was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1645763|title=Bangladesh's Karachi leg of Pakistan tour postponed|work=[[International Cricket Council]]|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Curling==\nThe [[2019\u201320 curling season|curling season]] typically ends in May but was cut short by the pandemic, effectively ending in early March. The [[World Curling Federation]] cancelled the last five championships scheduled for the 2019\u201320 curling season, most importantly the [[2020 World Women's Curling Championship]], [[2020 World Men's Curling Championship]], and [[2020 World Mixed Doubles Curling Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2019-2020 season ends with event cancellations |url=https://worldcurling.org/2020/03/2019-2020-season-ends/ |website=World Curling Federation |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cycling==\n===Road cycling===\nThe [[2020 UAE Tour]] was scheduled to run until February 29, but was abandoned following stage five after two support staff tested positive for coronavirus. Of the following nineteen [[2020 UCI World Tour]] races scheduled to take place up to 31 May, only [[2020 Omloop Het Nieuwsblad|Omloop Het Nieuwsblad]] and [[2020 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]], which also had the final day of racing removed, took place at the intended time, some with the stated hope of taking place at a later date.  The postponed races in this block include the [[2020 Giro d'Italia]] and four of the five annual [[Cycling monument|monuments]], and many lower category races were also cancelled or postponed. Also races of the [[2020 UCI Women's World Tour]] were cancelled or postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uci.org/news/2020/novel-coronavirus-important-information|title=Novel coronavirus: important information|website=UCI|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Farrand|first=Stephen|title=RCS Sport cancels Strade Bianche in light of coronavirus measures|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/rcs-sport-cancels-strade-bianche-in-light-of-coronavirus-measures/|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=5 March 2020|date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Frattini|first=Kirsten|title=Coronavirus: Women's WorldTour Trofeo Alfredo Binda postponed until June 2|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/coronavirus-womens-worldtour-trofeo-alfredo-binda-postponed-until-june-2/|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=5 March 2020|date=5 March 2020|quote=They are still awaiting the authorisation of the new date from the UCI.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/coronavirus-womens-worldtour-ronde-van-drenthe-cancelled/|title=Coronavirus: Women's WorldTour Ronde van Drenthe cancelled|first=Lukas|last=Kn\u00f6fler|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=12 March 2020|date=12 March 2020|quote=Sadly, this means that our races will not go ahead [...] We hope to be back next year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Geen koers tot en met drie april, Ronde van Vlaanderen maakt nog een waterkansje maar houdt rekening met annulering|language=Dutch|trans-title=No race until April 3, Tour of Flanders still has a remote chance but takes cancellation into account|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200312_04887671|work=[[Het Nieuwsblad]]|publisher=[[Mediahuis]]|accessdate=12 March 2020|date=12 March 2020|quote=We besluiten bij deze om onze wedstrijd Driedaagse Brugge De Panne ook uit te stellen naar een later tijdstip. We hopen dat we een plaatsje krijgen op de kalender in het najaar. [We hereby decide to postpone our match Three Days Bruges De Panne to a later date. We hope that we will have a place on the calendar in the autumn].}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://sporza.be/nl/2020/03/12/alle-sportactiviteiten-in-belgie-tot-en-met-3-april-worden-gean~1584050395120/|title=Alle sportactiviteiten in Belgi\u00eb tot en met 3 april worden geannuleerd|language=Dutch|trans-title=All sports activities in Belgium until April 3 will be canceled|work=[[Sporza]]|publisher=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie]]|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=12 March 2020|quote=In het wielrennen worden Nokere Koerse (18 maart), de Bredene Koksijde Classic (20 maart), de Driedaagse Brugge-De Panne (25 maart), de E3 Harelbeke (27 maart), Gent-Wevelgem (29 maart) en Dwars door Vlaanderen (1 april) geschrapt. [In cycling Nokere Koerse (March 18), the Bredene Koksijde Classic (March 20), the Driedaagse Brugge-De Panne (March 25), the E3 Harelbeke (March 27), Ghent-Wevelgem (March 29) and Dwars door Vlaanderen (April 1) are scrapped.]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://womenstour.co.uk/womens-tour-2020-postponed|title=Women's Tour 2020 postponed|first=Nick|last=Bull|work=[[The Women's Tour]]|publisher=SweetSpot Group|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/paris-roubaix-fleche-wallonne-and-liege-bastogne-liege-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/|title=Paris-Roubaix, Fl\u00e8che Wallonne and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge postponed due to coronavirus pandemic|first=Barry|last=Ryan|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|quote=As part of the fight against the spread of Coronavirus (COVID19), Amaury Sport Organisation, with the agreement of the Union Cycliste Internationale (UCI), has decided to not organise Paris-Roubaix (12th April), the Fl\u00e8che Wallonne and the Fl\u00e8che Wallonne Women (22nd April) and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge Women (26th April) races on their scheduled dates.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/tour-of-flanders-cancelled-over-coronavirus-concerns/|title=Tour of Flanders cancelled over coronavirus concerns|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|quote=Organisers of the Tour of Flanders made the long-anticipated decision to cancel their April 5 race, saying they will work with the UCI and representatives of the teams and riders to look at the potential for scheduling a new date later this year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.velonews.com/2020/03/news/rolling-report-impact-of-coronavirus-on-pro-racing_505843|title=Rolling report: Impact of coronavirus on pro racing|work=[[VeloNews]]|publisher=Pocket Outdoor Media, LLC|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|quote=March 18, 5:15 a.m. (MT): Amstel Gold race postponed}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, [[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]] requested to suspend all UCI-sanctioned events in affected territories until April 3, and the qualification for the Tokyo 2020 Olympic Games and Paralympic Games to stop retroactively as of March 3.<ref name=\"uci20200315\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uci.org/inside-uci/press-releases/the-uci-takes-strong-measures-faced-with-the-development-of-the-coronavirus |title=The UCI takes strong measures faced with the development of the coronavirus |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=Union Cycliste Internationale |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> On March 18, the suspension of events were extended at least until the end of April.<ref name=\"uci20200318\">{{cite web |url=\nhttps://www.uci.org/inside-uci/press-releases/the-uci-and-its-partners-unite-to-face-the-consequences-of-the-coronavirus-for-road-cycling |title=The UCI and its partners unite to face the consequences of the coronavirus for road cycling |date=18 March 2020 |publisher=Union Cycliste Internationale |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===BMX===\nRace days of the 2020 [[UCI BMX Supercross World Cup]] were cancelled including 2 to 3 May in Papendal, the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myprivacy.dpgmedia.net/?siteKey=Oom2kBLTny5zJUeO&callbackUrl=https%3a%2f%2fwww.gelderlander.nl%2fprivacy-gate%2faccept%3fredirectUri%3d%252fsport-arnhem%252fwereldbeker-bmx-papendal-ook-van-de-agenda-geld-terug-voor-deelnemers-en-fans%257ea71539c9%252f%253freferrer%253dhttps%253a%252f%252fwww.google.nl%252f|title=Privacy settings|website=myprivacy.dpgmedia.net|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[UCI BMX World Championships]], scheduled to take place in [[Houston]], United States on 26\u201331 May, are postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2328063|title=Ook wereldkampioenschappen BMX uitgesteld wegens coronavirus|website=nos.nl|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nThe annual [[Cape Epic]] endurance race scheduled from 15 to 22 March was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cape-epic.com/riders/the-2020-race/official-statement-2020-absa-cape-epic-cancellation|title=The Official Statement regarding the cancellation of the 2020 Absa Cape Epic {{!}} Absa Cape Epic|website=cape-epic.com|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Darts==\nThe [[Professional Darts Corporation]]'s [[PDC European Tour|European Tour]] was impacted by the coronavirus; with the [[2020 European Darts Grand Prix]], the [[2020 European Darts Open]] and the [[2020 German Darts Grand Prix]] all being postponed following restrictions on gatherings implemented by federal governments in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] and [[Bavaria]], respectively. The two [[2020 Premier League Darts]] rounds to be held in [[Rotterdam]] at the end of March were postponed to September following restrictions on gatherings in the Netherlands; and the round to be held in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] a week earlier was subsequently postponed to October; meaning the Newcastle date would serve as the Premier League's play-off round. The next five rounds, in [[Belfast]], [[Sheffield]], [[Manchester]], [[Berlin]] and [[Birmingham]] were also postponed to later dates. All ProTour events from March 16 to the end of April were postponed. The [[2020 Nordic Darts Masters]] was postponed from June to October. The PDC's North American affiliate, the Championship Darts Corporation, cancelled the first weekend of its season in [[Ontario]], and the New Zealand affiliate DartPlayers tour was ended for 2019/20 following the cancellation of events in [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus \u2013 Latest re PDC events |url=https://www.pdc.tv/Coronavirus |publisher=[[Professional Darts Corporation]] |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Esports==\n=== Leagues and tournaments ===\nImpact of the pandemic on [[esports]] have primarily affected events and leagues that host competitions in-person at venues with spectators, which have led to cancellations, postponements, and competitions being held behind closed doors\u2014either in the traditional sense, or with competition being conducted entirely [[Multiplayer video game|over the internet]] (although [[Latency (engineering)|latency]] between players can be a factor).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21167652/coronavirus-esports-impact-league-of-legends-pubg-csgo-iem-katowice|title=The coronavirus' human impact on esports|last=Garst|first=Aron|date=2020-03-06|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video-games/esports/2020/03/17/esports-streamers-coronavirus-sports-canceled/|title=While the sports world falls silent, esports and streamers fill the void|last=Smith|first=Noah|date=2020-03-17|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Overwatch League]] cancelled homestand events (matches held on-location at home venues akin to traditional sports leagues, as opposed to a centralized studio) in Asia at the onset of the pandemic, and subsequently cancelled all homestands through to April following its spread in North America in mid-March. The league planned a shift to online play, and competition of the [[2020 Overwatch League season|2020 season]] to resume March 21. The mid-season tournament was also removed from the schedule, and its all-star festivities were moved to the off-season due to not all players having played an equal number of games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28885048/coronavirus-leads-overwatch-league-suspend-play-march-april|title=Coronavirus leads OWL to cancel events for March, April|date=2020-03-11|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\"/> Due to [[stay-at-home orders]] imposed by the state of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in California|California]] (where [[Blizzard Entertainment|Blizzard]]'s headquarters and several other teams are located), the resumption of play was postponed (although exhibition matches showcasing the game's newly-unveiled character Echo were still held). Play resumed on March 28, with teams realigned into three regional conferences. Due to various factors, including several teams suspending their operations (including the [[New York Excelsior]], in compliance with a [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|local]] stay-at-home order, and the [[London Spitfire]] and [[Vancouver Titans]] re-locating their staff to South Korea), six of the 16 matches scheduled for the weekend were dropped from the schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28928919/overwatch-league-postpones-first-weekend-online-matches|title=Overwatch League postpones first weekend of online matches|date=2020-03-20|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video-games/esports/2020/03/27/overwatch-league-schedule-coronavirus-online/|title=Overwatch League teams face a reset after pandemic spoils its grand plans|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=Launcher (Washington Post)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/multiple-overwatch-league-matches-canceled-on-march-28-and-29|title=Multiple Overwatch League matches canceled on March 28 and 29|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=Dot eSports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n[[Riot Games]] announced that the [[League of Legends Championship Series]] would temporarily suspend its season and switch to online play. In addition, the Spring Finals event in Frisco, Texas was called off and moved back to Riot's Los Angeles studio. [[Electronic Arts]] has suspended all competitive gaming that cannot be produced remotely.<ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28852881/how-coronavirus-affecting-esports-gaming-events|title=How coronavirus is affecting esports and gaming events|last=|first=|date=2020-03-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/14/21179779/league-of-legends-lcs-spring-finals-canceled-moved-ea-sports-fifa-global-series-apex-legends|title=League of Legends, EA suspend all esports due to coronavirus|last=Good|first=Owen S.|date=2020-03-14|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Crossover with traditional sports ===\nSportcal suggested that the esports industry had an opportunity to attract mainstream sports fans as a \"viable alternative\" to traditional sporting events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://advanced-television.com/2020/03/18/analyst-coronavirus-a-significant-opportunity-for-esports/|title=Analyst: \"Coronavirus a significant opportunity for eSports\"|last=|first=|date=|website=advanced-television.com|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>  Roundhill Investments CEO Will Hershey predicted that games that are straightforward for casual viewers to understand (such as [[sports game]]s) could see particular interest among this new audience.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWith the suspension of nearly all sporting events, some professional athletes began to increase their involvement in video game streaming as a means to engage with fans.<ref name=\":2\" /> Some teams have taken advantage of sports games in a similar manner, such as the [[Phoenix Suns]] holding ''[[NBA 2K20]]'' streams with guest players, between the teams the Suns were scheduled to play that night if the season had continued.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28900417/luka-doncic-50-leads-mavs-suns-twitch|title=Luka's 50 lead Mavericks past Suns -- on Twitch|date=2020-03-14|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28964373/bridges-leads-suns-victory-first-nba-2k-game-broadcast-radio|title=Bridges leads Suns to victory in first NBA 2K game broadcast on radio|date=2020-03-28|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> This culminated with a game actually being commentated by the team's radio broadcasters on team flagship [[KMVP-FM]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nEsports organisations have also invited professional athletes to compete in specific competitions (often alongside, or in competition with professional players); [[FaZe Clan]] organized a charity ''[[Call of Duty: Warzone]]'' pro-am entitled \"Fight 2 Fund\" in support of coronavirus-related charities, where professional players were partnered with celebrity participants (such as [[Ben Simmons]], [[Chad Johnson]], and [[JuJu Smith-Schuster]]),<ref name=\":2\" /> and several [[sim racing]] competitions similarly invited professional race drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/cars/2020/03/esports-fills-the-gap-as-coronavirus-cancels-in-person-sporting-events/|title=F1 drivers and other pros switch to esports in the age of the coronavirus|last=Gitlin|first=Jonathan M.|date=2020-03-16|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/22/21184192/sim-racing-coronavirus-f1-nascar-iracing-veloce-esports-max-verstappen-lando-norris|title=Pro drivers are competing with gamers after F1 and NASCAR canceled races|last=O'Kane|first=Sean|date=2020-03-22|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> In turn, both the [[IndyCar Series]] and [[NASCAR]] announced partnerships with sim racing platform [[iRacing]] to hold online invitational events featuring series regulars, with the latter employing television broadcasts by NASCAR television partner [[Fox NASCAR|Fox Sports]] (styled after and still featuring personalities associated with their traditional broadcasts, such as lead commentator [[Mike Joy]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2020/03/22/nascar-iracing-pro-invitational-series-fox-sports-1-high-marks/2894874001/|title=FS1 broadcast of NASCAR iRacing comes extremely close to the real thing|last=Gardner|first=Steve|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"espn.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/story/_/id/28919500/with-nascar-season-postponed-drivers-compete-esports-series|title=NASCAR greats set to compete in esports series|date=2020-03-18|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"espn.com\" />\n\n==Field hockey==\nMany field hockey leagues in Europe have been suspended, including in Spain,<ref>{{cite web |title=Comunicado Oficial RFEH |url=https://www.rfeh.es/comunicado-oficial-rfeh-7/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=es}}</ref> England,<ref>{{cite web |title=England Hockey suspends national hockey activity |url=https://www.englandhockey.co.uk/news.asp?itemid=49019&itemTitle=England+Hockey+suspends+national+hockey+activity&section=22 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> Germany,<ref>{{cite web |title=Feldhockey-Bundesligen: Spielverkehr bis Ende April ausgesetzt |url=https://web.hockey.de/news/lgtz22.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=de}}</ref> and the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web |title=Geen competitie en hockeyactiviteiten tot 1 april |url=https://www.knhb.nl/nieuws/geen-competitie-en-hockeyactiviteiten-tot-1-april |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 Euro Hockey League]] Final 8 and [[2020 Euro Hockey League Women]] seasons were suspended on 12 March.<ref name=\"EHL\">{{cite web |title=EHL Final8 Put on Hold |url=https://ehlhockey.tv/2020/03/12/ehl-final8-put-on-hold/ |website=ehlhockey.tv |publisher=[[Euro Hockey League]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Men's EuroHockey Club Trophy I]], [[2020 Men's EuroHockey Club Trophy II]], [[2020 Boys' EuroHockey Youth Championships]] and [[2020 Girls' EuroHockey Youth Championships]] were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=EHF cancels all EuroHockey Club Trophy and Challenge events, 2020 |url=https://eurohockey.org/2020/03/24/ehf-cancels-all-eurohockey-club-trophy-and-challenge-events-2020/ |website=eurohockey.org |publisher=[[European Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=EuroHockey U18 Championships boys and girls 2020 are cancelled |url=https://eurohockey.org/2020/03/31/eurohockey-u18-championships-boys-and-girls-2020-are-cancelled/ |website=eurohockey.org |publisher=[[European Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Asia, the [[2020 Men's Hockey Junior Asia Cup]], [[2020 Women's Asian Champions Trophy]], and [[2020 Women's Hockey Junior Asia Cup]] were postponed.<ref name=\"AHF2020\">{{cite web |title=Announcement: Postponement of the Bangabandhu Al-Arafah Islami Bank Junior Asia Cup Dhaka 2020 & the Women's Asian Champions Trophy Donghae 2020 |url=http://www.asiahockey.org/news/announcement-postponement-of-the-bangabandhu-al-arafah-islami-bank-junior-asia-cup-dhaka-2020-the-womens-asian-champions-trophy-donghae-2020/ |website=asiahockey.org |publisher=[[Asian Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Junior Asia Cup Gifu Kakamigahara 2020 \u2013 Formal Announcement of Postponement |url=http://www.asiahockey.org/news/womens-junior-asia-cup-gifu-kakamigahara-2020-formal-announcement-of-postponement/ |website=asiahockey.org}}</ref> The [[2020 Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] has been postponed to 24 September.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Azlan Shah Cup Hockey Tournament Postponed |url=https://sports.ndtv.com/hockey/coronavirus-azlan-shah-cup-hockey-tournament-postponed-2188516 |website=ndtv.com |publisher=[[NDTV]]}}</ref>\n\n==Futsal==\nThe [[2020 AFC Futsal Championship]] in [[Ashgabat]] had been postponed following consultation with all relevant stakeholders. On 9 March 2020, FIFA and AFC announced that the tournament were postponed to 5\u201316 August 2020.\n\n==Golf==\nMany elite golf tournaments, both professional and amateur, have either been postponed or cancelled in response to the pandemic, including the [[Men's major golf championships|major championships]]. On March 13, it was announced that the [[2020 Masters Tournament|Masters Tournament]] (scheduled for April 9\u201312) had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Masters Tournament Postponed |url=https://www.masters.com/en_US/news/articles/2020-03-13/2020_masters_tournament_postponed.html |publisher=Masters.com |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=Augusta National announces Masters will be postponed |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28897249/augusta-national-announces-masters-postponed-played |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 PGA Championship]] (scheduled for May 11\u201317) was postponed the following week.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/sports/golf/pga-championship-postponed.html|title=P.G.A. Championship Is Postponed|newspaper=The New York Times|last=Pennington|first=Bill|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> It is also widely expected that the [[2020 U.S. Open (golf)|2020 U.S. Open]] (scheduled for June 18\u201321) will also be postponed, but there has been no official announcement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/26/us-open-wont-be-played-in-june-but-will-stay-at-winged-foot/|title=US Open won't be played in June, but will stay at Winged Foot|newspaper=New York Post|last=Cannizzaro|first=Mark|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The [[R&A]] continue to plan for the [[2020 Open Championship]] to proceed as scheduled, but are investigating options should that not be possible.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theopen.com/latest/2020/03/covid19statement |title=Statement from the R&A on the COVID-19 pandemic |website=TheOpen.com |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> The ladies majors have been similarly affected, with the [[LPGA Tour]] postponing the [[ANA Inspiration]] until September.<ref name=lpga/>\n\nOn March 12, 2020, midway through the first round of the [[2020 Players Championship]], the [[PGA Tour]] announced that the remainder of the tournament and the next three events, the [[Valspar Championship]], [[WGC Match Play]], and the [[Valero Texas Open]], would continue without fan attendance. Subsequently, after completion of the days play, the tour decided to cancel the remainder of tournament and the three following events.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=Players Championship, other events won't have fans in attendance |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28890609/players-starts-autograph-ban-place |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=PGA Tour cancels Players Championship after first round |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28894497/pga-tour-cancels-players-championship-first-round |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 17, the tour announced the cancellation of all scheduled tournaments through May 10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pgatour.com/company/2020/03/17/pga-tour-news-tournament-cancellations-rbc-heritage-zurich-classic-new-orleans-wells-fargo-championship-att-byron-nelson-pga-championship.html |title=PGA Tour statement regarding additional tournament cancellations |publisher=PGA Tour |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The [[European Tour]] have also cancelled or postponed many tournaments, mostly those scheduled from mid-March through to the end of May,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/news/articles/detail/update-on-european-tour-events/ |title=Update on European Tour events |website=European Tour |date=March 27, 2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> including the [[Irish Open (golf)|Irish Open]], a [[Rolex Series]] event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/golf/52092416 |title=Irish Open: Mount Juliet European Tour event postponed because of coronavirus |website=BBC Sport |date=March 30, 2020 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther leading professional tours have announced similar measures, as have the bodies responsible for organising leading amateur events. The LPGA Tour have postponed four tournaments including the ANA Inspiration,<ref name=lpga>{{cite news |title=LPGA to reschedule 3 events, including first major, the ANA Inspiration |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28893923/lpga-reschedule-3-events-including-first-major-ana-inspiration |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> and the [[Japan LPGA Tour]] cancelled five tournaments scheduled from March into April.<ref name=sched>{{cite web |url=https://www.lpga.or.jp/tournament/jlpgatour/2020 |title=2020\u5e74\u5ea6 JLPGA\u30c4\u30a2\u30fc\u30b9\u30b1\u30b8\u30e5\u30fc\u30eb |trans-title=2020 JLPGA Tour Schedule |publisher=JLPGA |language=ja}}</ref>\n\n==Greyhound racing==\nThe [[2020 English Greyhound Derby]] was postponed on 16 March with no replacement dates set at present.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/derby-postponed-statement/|title=DERBY POSTPONED \u2013 ARC STATEMENT|website=Greyhound Star}}</ref> The [[Arena Racing Company]] tracks announced a behind closed doors policy from 24 March <ref>{{cite web|url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/arc-meetings-staged-behind-closed-doors/|title=ALL ARC MEETINGS TO BE STAGED BEHIND CLOSED DOORS|website=Greyhound Star}}</ref> and [[Greyhound racing in Ireland|racing in Ireland]] continues with a behind closed doors policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.igb.ie/talking-dogs/covid-19-update-racing-behind-closed-doors/|title=COVID 19 UPDATE: RACING BEHIND CLOSED DOORS|publisher=Irish Greyhound Board}}</ref>\n\n==Gridiron football==\n===CFL===\nOn March 12, the [[Canadian Football League]] announced the cancellation or modification of several pre-season events in response to the pandemic. Several scouting combines across Canada and the United States were cancelled, while other events such as rules committee meetings will now be held remotely. The League continues to plan to hold both its International and National Drafts in April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cfl.ca/2020/03/12/statement-cfl-coronavirus-situation/ |title=A statement from the CFL on the Coronavirus situation |website=cfl.ca|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL===\nThe [[National Football League]] has been in its off-season since [[Super Bowl LIV|February 2, 2020]], but the [[2020 NFL Draft]] is scheduled to be held in [[Las Vegas]] from April 23\u201325, 2020. On March 12, various NFL teams began to suspend travel by their coaches and [[Scout (sport)|player scout]]s, while the league itself had advised its non-critical staff to work from home. On March 13, 2020, the NFL announced that it had temporarily prohibited draft-eligible players from travelling to meet team personnel, and vice versa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/nfl-coronavirus-updates-league-prohibits-pre-draft-visits-mulls-draft-changes-xfl-player-tests-positive/ |title=NFL coronavirus updates: League prohibits pre-draft visits, mulls draft changes, XFL player tests positive |website=CBSSports.com |language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the NFL announced that it had cancelled public festivities associated with the draft; the draft itself will still be held, but the league stated that it was exploring \"innovative options for how the process will be conducted\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Belson|first=Ken|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/sports/football/nfl-draft-coronavirus.html|title=How the N.F.L. Draft Process Works From Home|date=2020-03-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001106351/article/nfl-draft-to-proceed-april-2325-sans-public-events-in-las-vegas|title=NFL draft to proceed April 23\u201325 sans public events in Las Vegas|website=NFL.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nLabor negotiations with the [[National Football League Players Association]] continued through the pandemic, resulting in ratification of a new, ten-year [[collective bargaining agreement]] in March 2020.\n\n===XFL===\nOn March 12, the [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] announced the suspension of the 2020 season, with all players to be paid their base pay and benefits for the full 2020 regular season; the season was officially cancelled on March 20, with half of its ten-week regular season schedule played.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/xfl-officially-cancels-inaugural-season-reveals-when-players-can-sign-with-nfl-or-cfl-teams/|title=XFL officially cancels inaugural season, reveals when players can sign with NFL or CFL teams|last=Dajani|first=Jordan|date=20 March 2020|publisher=[[CBSSports.com]]|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> The XFL, which is the revival of [[XFL (2001)|a league]] that played only one season in 2001, stated that they were committed to playing a full season in 2021 and future years.\n\n==Gymnastics==\nMultiple international artistic gymnastics competitions, many of which were [[Gymnastics at the 2020 Summer Olympics|Olympic]] qualifying events, were either canceled or postponed.  On March 13, after already having completed qualifications, the [[2020 FIG Artistic Gymnastics World Cup series|Baku World Cup]] canceled its event finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gymnastics.sport/site/news/displaynews.php?idNews=2836|title=Finals of Baku World Cup cancelled|work=[[International Gymnastics Federation]]|date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>  The Stuttgart, Birmingham, and Tokyo World Cups (scheduled to take place between March 21 \u2013 April 5) were all canceled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gymnastics.sport/site/news/displaynews.php?idNews=2827|title=Impact of the COVID-19 outbreak on the upcoming FIG events|work=[[International Gymnastics Federation]]|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.british-gymnastics.org/news-and-events/news/latest-news/9015-british-gymnastics-national-events-announcement-including-fig-world-cup|title=British Gymnastics national events announcement, including FIG World Cup|work=[[British Gymnastics]]|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=tokyowc>{{cite tweet|number=1239945252183703553|user=FIG_media|date=March 17, 2020|title=Japan Gymnastics Association has decided to cancel the #Tokyo All-Around World Cup that was scheduled on 4-5 April 2020}}</ref>  The [[European Women's Artistic Gymnastics Championships]] (scheduled to take place April 30 \u2013 May 3) and the [[European Men's Artistic Gymnastics Championships]] (scheduled to take place May 27\u201331) were both canceled.<ref name=euros2020>{{cite web|url=https://www.ueg.org/news/covid-19-update-event-cancellations|title=COVID-19 update - event cancellations|work=[[European Union of Gymnastics]]|date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>  The [[Pacific Rim Championships]] (scheduled to take place April 17\u201319) was postponed until 2021.<ref name=pacrim>{{cite web|url=https://www.gymnasticsnz.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/2020-Pacific-Rim-postponement-announcement-final-17Mar20.pdf|title=2020 Pacific Rim Championships Postponed|date=March 17, 2020|work=Gymnastics New Zealand}}</ref>\n\n==Handball==\nThe 25\u201329 March, [[2020 European Women's Handball Championship qualification]] matches in Rotterdam, the Netherlands were cancelled.<ref name=\"nu.nl\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nu.nl/sport-overig/6033687/deze-sportevenementen-zijn-afgelast-vanwege-het-coronavirus.html|title=Deze sportevenementen zijn afgelast vanwege het coronavirus|date=February 27, 2020|website=NU|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Horse racing==\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, most horse racing events remained scheduled as normal, but with restricted attendance at racecourses. This included Hong Kong, France,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/sports/hippisme/coronavirus-les-courses-hippiques-et-les-turfistes-s-adaptent-10-03-2020-8276982.php|title=Coronavirus : Les courses hippiques et les turfistes s'adaptent|first1=Par St\u00e9phan FlourentLe 10 mars 2020|last1=\u00e0 19h56|first2=Modifi\u00e9 Le 10 Mars 2020|last2=\u00c0 19h57|date=March 10, 2020|website=leparisien.fr}}</ref> Japan,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/238823/coronavirus-forces-bettors-online-in-japan |title=Coronavirus Forces Bettors Online in Japan |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |first=Naohiro |last=Goda |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> United Arab Emirates,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/horse-racing/the-35-million-dubai-world-cup-show-must-go-on-1.70362919|title=The $35 million Dubai World Cup show must go on|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> United States, Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racenet.com.au/news/all-star-mile-slated-to-go-ahead-yet-fans-banned-from-australian-grand-prix-20200313|title=LATEST BREAKING NEWS \u2013 All-Star Mile to go ahead but crowd lockout|website=www.racenet.com.au}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/latest/dundalk-to-race-behind-closed-doors-as-ireland-launches-coronavirus-restrictions/427842|title=Racing in Ireland to go ahead behind closed doors until March 29 &#124; Horse Racing News &#124; Racing Post|website=www.racingpost.com}}</ref> United Kingdom, Germany, New Zealand, and Singapore.\n\nThe [[Macau Jockey Club]] suspended racing events from 31 January to 15 February and resumed racing from 22 February. The [[Korea Racing Authority]] suspended horse racing from 8 March. [[Sunland Park Racetrack & Casino|Sunland Park Racetrack]] in the United States canceled its race meeting from 16 March, which included the [[Sunland Derby]], part of the [[2020 Road to the Kentucky Derby]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239094/maryland-new-mexico-close-tracks-simulcast-facilities |title=Maryland, New Mexico Close Tracks, Simulcast Facilities |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Many tracks in North America followed suit over the following weeks, although some remained open depending on state-by-state decisions. In Britain, although the [[Cheltenham Festival]] proceeded as normal in mid-March,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Oliphant |first1=Vickiie |title=Cheltenham coronavirus advice: How to avoid COVID-19 \u2013 Festival guidelines in FULL |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/horseracing/1252795/Cheltenham-coronavirus-advice-guidelines-in-full-cheltenham-festival-races |website=Express.co.uk |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=en |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> the [[Grand National]] meeting at Aintree in April was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/grand-national-meeting-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/428688|title=Grand National cancelled as Aintree card lost to spiralling coronavirus crisis &#124; Horse Racing News &#124; Racing Post|website=www.racingpost.com}}</ref> By mid-March [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] had become the only major horse racing country in Europe where the sport continued, albeit strictly regulated and behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/18/talking-horses-racing-industry-left-to-contemplate-cost-of-suspension|title=Ireland goes it alone as racing continues behind closed doors|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Greg|last=Wood|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Ireland finally closed down racing on 25 March until at least 19 April.<ref name=IrelandCancelled />\n\n[[Churchill Downs]] announced that the [[2020 Kentucky Derby]], normally the first leg of the [[Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing|American Triple Crown]], would be delayed to September 5;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239121/the-146th-kentucky-derby-moved-to-sept-5 |title=The 146th Kentucky Derby Moved to Sept. 5 |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first1=Eric |last1=Mitchell |first2=Byron |last2=King |title=Owners, Trainers React to Kentucky Derby Postponement |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239123/owners-trainers-react-to-kentucky-derby-postponement |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |date=17 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> this also cascaded to the [[Preakness Stakes]], with the [[Maryland Jockey Club]] also delaying their second leg race to a date to be determined, likely in September as well.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-latest-will-the-preakness-be-postponed-jockey-club-discussing/|title=Coronavirus Latest: Preakness To Be Postponed, Likely To September|date=17 March 2020|publisher=[[WJZ-TV]]|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> The [[New York Racing Association]] has not announced plans to reschedule the third leg, the [[Belmont Stakes]].\n\nOn 22 March, it was announced that the [[Dubai World Cup]], due to celebrate its 25th anniversary running on 28 March, had been cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Dubai World Cup night is called off at Meydan |url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/2020-dubai-world-cup-night-is-called-off-at-meydan-1.1584882198359 |website=Gulf News |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome horsemans are limited from travelling to other racecouses or horse racing facilities. Hong Kong-based jockey [[Keith Yeung]] felt unwell on 22 March night, but his test for COVID-19 PCR was negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/racing/article/3076478/hong-kong-jockey-keith-yeungs-covid-19-test-comes-back-negative|title=Hong Kong jockey Keith Yeung's Covid-19 test comes back negative|website=South China Morning Post|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, it was announced that American-based jockey [[Javier Castellano]] had tested positive.<ref>{{cite web |last1=King |first1=Byron |title=Jockey Castellano Tests Positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239301/jockey-castellano-tests-positive-for-covid-19 |website=BloodHorse.com |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n;Cancelled race meetings<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Updates/Announcements |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/section/covid-19-updates-announcements |website=www.bloodhorse.com |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Macau Jockey Club]] \u2013 31 January to 15 February, 28 March to 11 April<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mjc.mo/race_en/info/news_detail.php?newsid=32256|title=Macau Jockey Club - Company News|website=Macau Jockey Club|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Korea Racing Authority]] \u2013 from 8 March\n*Selangor Turf Club, Malaysia \u2013 from 14 March\n*[[Sunland Park Racetrack & Casino|Sunland Park Racetrack]], New Mexico \u2013 March meeting\n*[[Keeneland]], Kentucky \u2013 April meeting. [[Kentucky Downs]] and [[Ellis Parks]] closed down in mid-March, while [[Turfway Park]] curtailed its meeting from 29 March to 26 March. Churchill Downs deferred the Kentucky Derby and Kentucky Oaks, normally scheduled for early May, to September\n* [[Woodbine Racetrack]], Toronto \u2013 harness racing from March 14 for at least two weeks. Status of Thoroughbred meeting, scheduled to begin in April, is to be determined\n* [[Aqueduct Racetrack]], New York \u2013 indefinitely from 19 March after a backstretch worker tested positive\n* [[Laurel Park (race track)|Laurel Park]], Maryland \u2013 indefinitely from 20 March\n* [[Fair Grounds Race Course|Fair Grounds]], Louisiana \u2013 cancelled last week of its winter meeting, 22 March to 29 March\n* [[Santa Anita Park]], California - indefinitely from 27 March\n*All United Kingdom racecourses \u2013 18 March to 30 April (excluding [[Downpatrick Racecourse|Downpatrick]] and [[Down Royal Racecourse|Down Royal]] in Northern Ireland, which come under Irish racing rules)\n*All Ireland racecourses \u2013 25 March to 19 April<ref name=IrelandCancelled>{{cite web |title=Racing off in Ireland from Wednesday after all sporting events are cancelled |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/racing-off-after-all-sporting-events-are-cancelled-in-ireland/429939 |website=Racing Post |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*All German racecourses \u2013 17 March to 18 April<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.turf-times.de/tt-artikel/wegen-des-coronavirus-renn-stopp-bis-zum-18-april-deutschland|title=Wegen des Coronavirus: Renn-Stopp bis zum 18. April in Deutschland! &#124; Turf-Times Deutschland|website=www.turf-times.de|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n*All French racecourses [[France Galop]] and [[LeTrot]] \u2013 17 March to 15 April\n*All United Arab Emirates race meetings \u2013 Including [[Dubai World Cup Night]] and four April meetings.\n*All New Zealand racecourses - From 24 March\n*All South African racecourses - 27 March to 16 April<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingpost.co.za/2020/03/sa-horseracing/|title=Newsflash: It's Official - No SA Racing|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Remaining racing meetings\n*[[Hong Kong Jockey Club]] - no meeting canceled and rescheduled.\n*[[Macau Jockey Club]] \u2013 resumed racing from 22 February to 21 March\n*[[Japan Racing Association]] and [[National Association of Racing]] - no meeting canceled and rescheduled under coronavirus.\n*[[Singapore Turf Club]] - Weekly one meeting from April.\n*[[Solvalla]], Sweden\n*Most Australian racecourses - Some County and Picnic meetings are canceled. \n*Some American racecources, including [[Gulfstream Park]] in Florida and [[Oaklawn Park]] in Arkansas\n\n==Ice hockey==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship|IIHF Women's World Championship]], [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division IV|IIHF World Championship Division IV]] and [[2020 Women's Ice Hockey World Championships|Women's Ice Hockey World Championships]] were all cancelled by the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] due to the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://iihf.com/en/events/2020/ww/news/18296/women%E2%80%99s-worlds-cancelled |title=Women's Worlds cancelled |date=March 7, 2020 |work=iihf.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iihf.com/en/news/18277/iihf-cancels-march-tournaments |title=IIHF cancels March tournaments |date=March 2, 2020 |work=iihf.com}}</ref> The federation also cancelled the [[2020 IIHF World U18 Championships|2020 event]] of one of its two official junior world championship tournaments, the [[IIHF World U18 Championship]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=IIHF cancels U18 Worlds |url=https://www.iihf.com/en/events/2020/wm18/news/18313/iihf-cancels-u18-world-chhmpionship |location=[[Plymouth Charter Township, Michigan]] & [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]], [[United States]] |publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]] |first=Adam |last=Steiss |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 21, IIHF publicly announced that the senior men's world championships had also been cancelled.<ref>{{cite press release | title=2020 IIHF Ice Hockey World Championship cancelled | url=https://www.iihf.com/en/events/2020/wm/news/18344/2020-iihf-ice-hockey-world-championship-cancelled | location=[[Switzerland]] | publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]] | website=iihf.com | first=Adam | last=Steiss | date=March 21, 2020 | access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Cancelled tournaments:'''\n\n* [[2020 IIHF World U18 Championships]]\n*[[2020 IIHF World Championship]]s\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division I]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division II]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division III]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division IV]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship Division I]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship Division II]] Group A\n\n===Europe===\n\nAs a result of the German government's ban on large events, the [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] announced on March 10 that it would cancel the remainder of its season, marking the first time in the league's history a champion would not be crowned. The top four teams at the time of the cancellation \u2014 [[EHC Red Bull M\u00fcnchen]], [[Adler Mannheim]], [[Straubing Tigers]], and [[Eisbaren Berlin]] \u2014 would advance to the [[Champions Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite press release | title=German League cancels season, won't crown champion as a result of coronavirus outbreak | url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/german-league-cancels-season-wont-crown-champion-as-a-result-of-coronavirus-outbreak | first=Jared | last=Clinton | publisher=[[The Hockey News]] | website=thehockeynews.com | date=March 10, 2020 | access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Swedish Ice Hockey Association]] suspended all remaining hockey, the playoffs and qualification rounds, in the Swedish elite leagues on March 15; no awarding of the [[Le Mat Trophy]] for the 2019/20 season nor transference of teams from the leagues' qualification plays for the 2020/21 season will happen as a result.<ref>{{cite news | title=Hockeys\u00e4songen 2019/20 st\u00e4lls in | url=https://www.hockeyallsvenskan.se/artikel/2ittak7t7-1el1/hockeysasongen-2019-20-stalls-in | publisher=[[HockeyAllsvenskan]] | language=Swedish | website=hockeyallsvenskan.se |date=March 10, 2020 | access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Cancelled or ended leagues:'''\n\n* [[2019\u201320 Czech Extraliga season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 Slovak Extraliga season]]\n* [[2019-20 Austrian Hockey League season]]\n* [[2019-20 DEL season]]\n* [[2019-20 SHL season]]\n* [[2019-20 EIHL season]]\n\n===North America===\nIn early March 2020, the [[National Hockey League]] suspended media access to the locker rooms, saying that only official personnel would be allowed in after the games to limit person-to-person contact. On March 12, the NHL, [[American Hockey League]], the leagues of the [[Canadian Hockey League]] ([[Ontario Hockey League]], [[Quebec Major Junior Hockey League]], and [[Western Hockey League]]), the [[United States Hockey League|USHL]], and [[ECHL]] announced that their [[2019\u201320 NHL season|2019\u201320 seasons]] would be indefinitely suspended.<ref>{{cite web |title=NHL pauses regular season because of coronavirus |url=https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gaydos |first1=Ryan |title=NHL suspends 2019\u201320 season over coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.foxnews.com/sports/nhl-suspends-season-over-coronavirus-outbreak |website=Fox News |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaplan |first1=Emily |title=NHL suspending play immediately due to virus |url=https://www.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/28891430/sources-nhl-suspending-play-immediately-due-virus |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wearegreenbay.com/community/health/coronavirus/green-bay-gamblers-season-suspended-due-to-covid-19/|title=Green Bay Gamblers season suspended due to COVID-19|last=Rose|first=Joshua|date=12 March 202|work=[[WFRV-TV|WeAreGreenBay.com]]|publisher=[[Nexstar Media Group]]|accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe ECHL announced on March 14 that the remainder of the season would be scrapped.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/28904194/prudent-decision |title=ECHL cancels season amid concerns over virus |date=2020-03-15 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The leagues of the CHL announced on March 18 that they would scrap the remainder of their regular seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/qmjhl-becomes-first-chl-league-to-cancel-remainder-of-regular-season|title=CHL leagues cancel remainder of regular season campaigns; playoff status still undetermined|last=EllisMarch 18|first=Steven|last2=2020|date=2020-03-18|website=The Hockey News|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> On March 23, the CHL confirmed that all playoffs and the [[2020 Memorial Cup]] were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprovince.com/sports/hockey/junior-hockey/covid-19-forces-cancellation-of-chl-playoffs-and-2020-memorial-cup|title=COVID-19 forces cancellation of CHL playoffs and 2020 Memorial Cup|date=2020-03-23|website=The Province|language=en-CA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n[[Hockey Canada]], the governing body for amateur hockey in the country, cancelled the remainder of its season on March 13. This included national championships such as the [[Telus Cup]] and [[Esso Cup]], as well as all regional and provincial playoffs.  It also included the [[Canadian Junior Hockey League]] playoffs and the [[2020 Centennial Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/news/2020-news-hockey-canada-ends-season|title=Hockey Canada statement in response to coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=2020-03-12|publisher=Hockey Canada}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/hockey-canada-ends-season-cancels-championships-1.4851343|title=Hockey Canada ends season, cancels championships|last=Hunt|first=Stephen|date=2020-03-12|website=Calgary|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Lacrosse==\nThe [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL) temporarily suspended the [[2020 NLL season|2020 season]] on March 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nll.com/news/nll-statement-on-game-play-march-12-2020/|title=NLL STATEMENT ON GAME PLAY (MARCH 12, 2020)|publisher=National Lacrosse League|website=nll.com|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts==\nDue to [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], [[ONE Championship]]  will host all events closed door at least until May 29, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mmaweekly.com/one-championship-closes-door-on-all-events-until-at-least-may-29-because-of-coronavirus |title=ONE Championship closes door on all events until at least May 29 because of coronavirus {{!}} MMAWeekly.com|date=March 12, 2020|language=en-US|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bellator MMA in 2020#Bellator 241|Bellator MMA 241]] was scheduled to be a closed-door event,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mma/news/coronavirus-updates-bellator-241-fight-card-to-be-held-without-fans-in-attendance-in-connecticut/ |title=Coronavirus updates: Bellator 241 fight card to be held without fans in attendance in Connecticut |website=CBSSports.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> but was cancelled the day of the fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmaweekly.com/bellator-makes-last-minute-decision-to-cancel-fridays-bellator-241-coronavirus-covid-19|title=Bellator makes last-minute decision to cancel Friday's Bellator 241|publisher=MMA Weekly|website=mmaweekly.com|first=Ken|last=Pishna|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Konfrontacja Sztuk Walki]] (KSW) cancelled KSW 53 in [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]], Poland for March 21, 2020 event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fightsports.tv/ksw-cancels-upcoming-event-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |title=KSW Cancels Upcoming Event Due To Coronavirus Outbreak |date=March 11, 2020 |website=FIGHT SPORTS |language=en-US|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) hosted its event [[UFC Fight Night: Lee vs. Oliveira]] [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] in [[Bras\u00edlia]], Brazil.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-Brasilia-to-be-Held-in-Empty-Arena-Following-Governors-Order-Media-Day-Cancelled-171435 |title=UFC Brasilia to be held in empty arena following Governor's order, Media Day cancelled |website=Sherdog.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[UFC Fight Night: Overeem vs. Harris]], [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]], and [[UFC Fight Night: Woodley vs. Edwards]] were postponed to future dates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/ufc-postpones-three-events-coronavirus-pandemic|title=UFC postpones three events amid growing coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-16|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Motorsport==\n===Australian Supercars===\nThe [[Supercars Championship]] had planned to hold an event, the [[Melbourne 400]] supporting the Australian Grand Prix. The event was cancelled the same time the Grand Prix was also cancelled. The Championship is currently seeking to hold a replacement event later in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/13/supercars-confirms-albert-park-cancellation-seeking-replacement-event/|title=Supercars confirms Albert Park cancellation, seeking replacement event|date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The Supercars' [[Tasmania Super400]] at [[Symmons Plains Raceway]] (originally scheduled for 4\u20135 April), the [[Auckland Super400]] at Hampton Downs (25\u201326 April), and the [[Perth SuperNight]] at [[Wanneroo Raceway]] (16\u201317 May) rounds were also postponed beyond June.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chapman|first=Simon|url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/18/breaking-supercars-postpones-tasmania-auckland-and-perth/|title=Supercars postpones Tasmania, Auckland and Perth|publisher=[[Speedcafe]]|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> The Supercars' support series like the [[Boost Mobile Super Trucks]] were also affected, though the trucks intend to commit to their support schedule once new dates are finalised.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nguyen|first=Justin|url=https://www.thecheckeredflag.co.uk/2020/03/tasmania-auckland-perth-races-postponed-sst-to-follow-reschedules/|title=Tasmania, Auckland, Perth races postponed, SST to follow reschedules|publisher=The Checkered Flag|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSupercars formed the All Stars Eseries to allow its drivers to compete against each other.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bartolomaeus|first=Stefan|url=https://www.supercars.com/news/championship/what-you-need-to-know-supercars-goes-virtual/|title=What you need to know: Supercars goes virtual|publisher=[[Supercars Championship]]|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters===\nThe [[2020 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters]] series postponed the start of its championship until July 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/dtm/news/148790/dtm-issues-revised-2020-calendar-set-for-july-start|title=The DTM has issued a revised 2020 calendar set to start in July|first=Rachit|last=Thukral|website=Autosport.com|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Formula One===\nThe early [[2020 Formula One World Championship|Formula One season]] was disrupted by the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"CHN postponed\">{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.chinese-grand-prix-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak.3g2y5Ngyrk1MbNxQB9hj4s.html |title=2020 F1 Chinese Grand Prix postponed due to novel coronavirus outbreak |date=February 12, 2020 |website=Formula1.com |publisher=Formula One World Championship Limited|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212184109/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.chinese-grand-prix-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak.3g2y5Ngyrk1MbNxQB9hj4s.html|archive-date=February 12, 2020|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> Prior to the start of the season, [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] and [[Scuderia AlphaTauri|AlphaTauri]] expressed concern about the spread of the virus and its effect on the championship. Both teams are based in Italy, which has suffered [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|one of the worst outbreaks of the virus]] outside China,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148478/ferrari-wants-assurances-over-coronavirus-from-f1 |title=Ferrari wants assurances over coronavirus from F1 before travel |last=Noble |first=Jonathan |date=February 28, 2020 |website=[[Autosport|Autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229014941/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148478/ferrari-wants-assurances-over-coronavirus-from-f1|archive-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148508/tost-unfair-if-australia-goes-ahead-without-all-teams |title=Tost: Unfair if Australia goes ahead without all F1 teams |last=Noble |first=Jonathan |date=March 2, 2020 |website=[[Autosport|Autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303042841/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148508/tost-unfair-if-australia-goes-ahead-without-all-teams|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> and so both Ferrari and AlphaTauri were therefore concerned over the ability of their staff to leave a quarantine zone that was established in northern Italy. [[Ross Brawn]], the managing director of the sport, announced that Grands Prix would not go ahead if a team were blocked from entering a host nation, but that events could go ahead if a team voluntarily chose not to enter a host nation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51727401 |title=Coronavirus: F1 will not hold race in country preventing teams entering |last=Benson |first=Andrew |date=March 4, 2020 |website=[[BBC Sport]] |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305134810/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51727401|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> The [[Australian Grand Prix|Australian]] and [[Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Grands Prix]] were cancelled.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51849163 |title=Coronavirus: Australian Grand Prix called off |date=March 13, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 13, 2020 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"NEDMONESP\"/> The cancellation of the Monaco Grand Prix meant that 2020 would mark the first time since {{F1|1954}} that the race has not been held. The [[Azerbaijan Grand Prix|Azerbaijan]], [[Bahrain Grand Prix|Bahrain]], [[Chinese Grand Prix|Chinese]], [[Dutch Grand Prix|Dutch]], [[Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish]] and [[Vietnam Grand Prix|Vietnam Grands Prix]] were postponed.<ref name=\"NEDMONESP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.dutch-spanish-and-monaco-grands-prix-postponed.5CggooJeHoDchKkFehkrkY.html|title=Dutch, Spanish and Monaco Grands Prix postponed|website=formula1.com|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"spectators\">{{cite web |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/08/no-spectators-for-bahrain-grand-prix/ |title=No spectators for Bahrain Grand Prix |last=Chapman |first=Simon |date=March 8, 2020 |website=Speedcafe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-13/f1-grand-prix-in-china-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-fears/11960614 |title=Coronavirus fears force the postponement of the F1 Grand Prix in China in April |work=abc.net.au |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=13 February 2020 |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> The summer break shut down period\u2014which includes mandatory factory closures as a cost-cutting measure\u2014was also brought forward from August to March and April and was extended to three weeks, allowing for postponed races to be held in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.f1-summer-shutdown-brought-forward-in-response-to-coronavirus-outbreak.5a4PM49x3Rs3WKMmxfUIO8.html|title=F1 summer shutdown brought forward in response to coronavirus outbreak|last=|first=|date=2020-03-18|website=Formula1.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nThe sport had planned to overhaul its technical regulations for the {{F1|2021}} championship in one of the largest changes in its seventy-year history. The pandemic prompted these changes to be postponed until {{F1|2022}}, with teams required to enter their {{F1|2020}} cars in the 2021 championship to minimise the financial stress placed on the teams.<ref name=\"19 chassis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/20/formula-1s-new-regulations-delayed-until-2022/|title=Formula 1's new regulations delayed until 2022|first=Daniel|last=Herrero|work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]]|publisher=[[Speedcafe]]|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRecently,{{when|date=March 2020}} some Formula One drivers have entered a virtual version of the [[Australian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DG1cFm3dsaU|title=Veloce Esports's NotAusGP|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> and the [[Bahrain Grand Prix]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vVLTdi4BtPE|title=Veloce Esports's NotTheBahGP|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QwcRDOjgfkE|title=F1 Bahrain Virtual Grand Prix|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The races are hosted by [[Jean-\u00c9ric Vergne]]'s Veloce Esports and F!. The online races are contested by current and former F1 drivers, like [[Lando Norris]], [[Nicholas Latifi]], [[Stoffel Vandoorne]], [[Esteban Guti\u00e9rrez]], [[Nico H\u00fclkenberg]], [[Johnny Herbert]] and [[Martin Brundle]], as well as celebrities and other sportsmen.\n\n====Formula 2 and Formula 3====\nThe [[Bahrain International Circuit|Bahrain]], [[Circuit Zandvoort|Zandvoort]] and [[Circuit de Barcelona|Barcelona]] rounds of the [[2020 FIA Formula 2 Championship|FIA Formula 2]] and [[2020 FIA Formula 3 Championship|Formula 3 Championships]]\u2014a series of races for junior drivers that run in support of Formula 1 events\u2014were postponed when the Bahrain, Dutch and Spanish Grands Prix were postponed.<ref name=\"BHR postponed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2020/03_March/FIA-Formula-2-and-FIA-Formula-3-Championships-Round-1-in-Bahrain-postponed/ |title=FIA Formula 2 and FIA Formula 3 Championships Round 1 in Bahrain postponed \u2013 Formula 2 |website=fiaformula2.com|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ZANBARMON\">{{cite news|url=https://www.fiaformula2.com/Latest/53FNxDGggZW5n65yl8aFpB/fia-formula-2-and-fia-formula-3-championships-may-races-and-tests-postponed|title=FIA Formula 2 and FIA Formula 3 Championships May races and tests postponed|work=fiaformula2.com|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Circuit de Monaco|Monaco]] Formula 2 round was cancelled when the Monaco Grand Prix was cancelled and the [[Baku City Circuit|Baku]] round postponed when the Azerbaijan Grand Prix was postponed;<ref name=\"ZANBARMON\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fiaformula2.com/Latest/3jBJqgLEiIY3w7fOsUwScE/fia-f2-round-in-baku-postponed-as-coronavirus-outbreak-continues|title=FIA Formula 2 round in Baku postponed as Coronavirus outbreak continues|work=fiaformula2.com|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Formula 3 had not been scheduled to race in Monaco or Azerbaijan.\n\n===Formula E===\nThe [[Formula E]] championship for electric cars initially responded to the pandemic by postponing the [[Rome ePrix|Rome]] and [[Sanya ePrix]]. Planned races in [[Paris ePrix|Paris]], [[Jakarta ePrix|Jakarta]] and [[Seoul ePrix|Seoul]] were also postponed, prompting organisers to postpone the entire season by two months.<ref name=Sanya>{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/formula-e/news/fe-china-sanya-eprix-coronavirus/4679553/amp/ |title=Formula E postpones China race amid virus outbreak |first=Alex |last=Kalinauckas |date=February 2, 2020|access-date=February 2, 2020 |website=motorsport.com}}</ref><ref name=Rome>{{cite news |url=https://www.fiaformulae.com/NEWS/2020/March/rome-eprix-update-march-2020?utm_source=FormulaETwitter&utm_mediumSocialPost&utm_campaign=rome&utm_source=FormulaETwitter&utm_mediumSocialPost&utm_campaign=rome |date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020 |website=fiaformulae.com |title=Statement on the 2020 Rome E-Prix}}</ref><ref name=ParisAndSeoul>{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/formula-e/news/coronavirus-suspend-season-two-months/4740500/ |first1=Charles |last1=Bradley |title=Formula E set to suspend 2019\u201320 season for two months |website=motorsport.com |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===GT World Challenge Europe===\nThe 3 Hours of Monza round of the [[2020 GT World Challenge Europe Endurance Cup]], scheduled for 19 April, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/gt/news/148594/gtwce-opener-in-italy-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus|title=GT World Challenge Europe Monza opener cancelled due to coronavirus|first=Gary|last=Watkins|website=Autosport.com|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===IndyCar===\nThe [[IndyCar Series]] initially announced on March 12 that it would hold the [[Firestone Grand Prix of St. Petersburg|Grand Prix of St. Petersburg]] \u2014 the opening race of the [[2020 IndyCar Series|2020 season]] \u2014 behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://racer.com/2020/03/12/indycar-st-pete-to-run-behind-closed-doors-condensed-schedule/ |title=IndyCar St Pete to run behind closed doors; condensed schedule |date=March 12, 2020 |website=RACER |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the series announced that it would cancel all races through at least the end of April, including St. Petersburg, [[Honda Indy Grand Prix of Alabama|Alabama]], [[Grand Prix of Long Beach|Long Beach]], and [[AutoNation IndyCar Challenge|Austin]]. IndyCar intended to begin the season with the traditional \"Month of May\" races at [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]], including the [[GMR Grand Prix|road course race]], and the 104th running of the [[Indianapolis 500]] on its traditional [[Memorial Day]] weekend scheduling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://racer.com/2020/03/13/indycar-cancels-st-pete-first-four-races/ |title=IndyCar cancels St Pete, first four races |date=March 13, 2020 |website=RACER |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, IndyCar announced that it would tentatively delay the beginning of the season to the end of May (beginning with the [[Detroit Grand Prix (IndyCar)|Detroit Grand Prix]] on May 30 and 31) by postponing the two Indianapolis races to later in the season. The [[GMR Grand Prix]] was moved to [[Independence Day (United States)|July 4]], and the Indianapolis 500 to August 23\u2014marking the first time in history that it has not been held in May. The Grand Prix of St. Petersburg was reinstated as the planned season finale, with a date to be determined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/motor/2020/03/26/indycar-calendar-undergoes-massive-overhaul/2918583001/|title=IndyCar calendar undergoes massive overhaul in response to coronavirus|website=Indianapolis Star|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nIndyCar eventually formed the IndyCar iRacing Challenge, with its drivers racing against one another on the ''[[iRacing]]'' [[racing simulation]] game.<ref>{{cite web|last=Eubanks|first=Michael|url=https://motorsports.nbcsports.com/2020/03/28/indycar-iracing-challenge-drivers-first-virtual-race-at-watkins-glen/|title=What drivers said after IndyCar's iRacing opener at Watkins Glen|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===MotoGP===\nThe [[MotoGP|MotoGP World Championship]] cancelled the opening round of the 2020 championship in [[2020 Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|Qatar]]. The [[Moto2]] and [[Moto3]] support categories raced in the country. Planned events in the United States, Argentina and Thailand were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fim-live.com/en/article/motogp-class-cancelled-at-the-grand-prix-of-qatar/ |title=MOTOGP CLASS CANCELLED AT THE GRAND PRIX OF QATAR |last= |first= |date=March 1, 2020 |website=FIM-live.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NASCAR===\nPrior to the [[2020 Folds of Honor QuikTrip 500]], part of the [[2020 NASCAR Cup Series]], [[NASCAR]] announced that no fans would be permitted to attend the race; this event, along with the [[Dixie Vodka 400]] at [[Homestead-Miami Speedway]], were later postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/12/nascar-statement-atlanta-homestead-race-schedules/ |title=NASCAR statement on Atlanta and Homestead {{!}} NASCAR|date=March 12, 2020|website=Official Site Of NASCAR|language=en-US|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, NASCAR announced that all race events through May 3 were postponed, however they still intend to run all 36 races for the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/16/nascar-schedule-update-statement-race-coronavirus/ |title=NASCAR statement: All race events through May 3 postponed {{!}} NASCAR|date=March 16, 2020|website=NASCAR.com|language=en-US|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNASCAR subsequently began to organize invitational [[eSports]] events on ''iRacing'', featuring current and past NASCAR drivers, officially known as the eNASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series. [[Fox NASCAR|Fox Sports]] also picked up broadcasts of these events to provide filler content for [[Fox Sports 1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autoweek.com/racing/nascar/a31789600/fox-sports-to-air-iracing-event-featuring-full-field-of-nascar-drivers/|title=Fox Sports to air iRacing event featuring full field of NASCAR drivers|last=Weaver|first=Matt|date=2020-03-19|website=Autoweek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n===World Endurance Championship===\nThe [[1000 Miles of Sebring]] race was cancelled.<ref name=\"Sebring\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailysportscar.com/2020/03/12/wec-set-to-cancel-sebring-trip.html |title=WEC Cancels Sebring Race (Updated) |date=March 12, 2020 |work=Marshall Pruett |publisher=Dailysportscar.com |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The [[6 Hours of Spa-Francorchamps]] and the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] were both postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://racer.com/2020/03/16/wec-postpones-spa/|title=WEC postpones Spa|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/motorsport/51946353| title= Coronavirus: Le Mans 24 Hours postponed until September| work=[[BBC Sport]]| date=18 March 2020| accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===World Rally Championship===\nThe 2020 running of [[Rally Argentina]], [[Rally Italia Sardegna]] and [[Rally Portugal]] were postponed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.autosport.com/wrc/news/148648/coronavirus-forces-rally-argentina-to-be-postponed |title=Coronavirus forces WRC Rally Argentina to be postponed |first=Nick |last=Garton |work=[[Autosport|autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]] |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.autosport.com/wrc/news/148778/wrc-season-hit-by-more-postponements|title=WRC 2020 season hit by more rally postponements due to coronavirus|first=Pablo|last=Elizalde|work=[[Autosport|autosport.com]]|publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Rally Mexico]] was shortened to allow competitors time to pack their equipment up and return to their headquarters in Europe before a series of travel bans were implemented.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/15/rally-mexico-shortened-by-a-day-due-to-travel-restrictions/ |title=Rally Mexico shortened by a day due to travel restrictions |first=Daniel |last=Herrero |work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]] |publisher=[[Speedcafe]] |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 World Rally Championship-2|World Rally Championship-2]], [[2020 World Rally Championship-3|World Rally Championship-3]] and [[2020 Junior World Rally Championship|Junior World Rally Championship]] support categories were also affected by the postponements.\n\n===World Rallycross Championship===\nThe opening rounds of the [[2020 FIA World Rallycross Championship]] in [[World RX of Barcelona|Barcelona]] and [[World RX of Portugal|Portugal]] were postponed.<ref name=\"BarcelonaPostponed\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/world-rx/news/world-rallycross-opener-barcelona-coronavirus/4746950/ |title=World RX postpones Barcelona opener over coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |last=Ridge |first=Hal |publisher=motorsport.com |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PortugalPostponed\">{{cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/world-rx/news/portugal-second-round-postponed-coronavirus/4771259/|title=World RX's second round also postponed due to coronavirus|date=20 March 2020|last=Ridge|first=Hal|publisher=motorsport.com|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===World Touring Car Cup===\nThe opening rounds of the [[2020 World Touring Car Cup]] in [[FIA WTCC Race of Hungary|Hungary]] and [[FIA WTCC Race of Germany|Germany]] were cancelled.<ref name=\"hun2020cancellation\">{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/wtcr/wtcr-race-of-hungary-statement_sto7702776/story.shtml |title=WTCR Race of Hungary statement |date=13 March 2020 |work=Eurosport |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/17/nurburgring-24-hours-race-weekend-postponed-september/|title=N\u00fcrburgring 24 Hours race weekend postponed to September|date=17 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fiawtcr.com/update-wtcr-race-of-germany/|title=Update: WTCR Race of Germany|date=17 March 2020|work=FIA WTCR {{!}} World Touring Car Cup|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> The four races that would have been held across the two rounds were rescheduled for other rounds.\n\n===Motorcycle road racing===\nThe 2020 [[Isle of Man TT]] was cancelled on 16 March.<ref>[http://web.archive.org/web/20200316235253/https://www.iomtt.com/news/2020/03/16/tt-2020-cancelled Isle of Mann Government announces cancellation of 2020 TT Races] Isle of Mann TT 16 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[North West 200]] event was postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Statement Re the Postponement of the 2020 fonaCAB and Nicholl Oils North West 200 |url=https://www.northwest200.org/statement-re-the-postponement-of-the-2020-fonacab-and-nicholl-oils-north-west-200/ |website=northwest200.org |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Scottish Six Days Trial]] event was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.obantimes.co.uk/2020/03/16/scottish-six-days-trial-and-pre-65-trial-cancelled-due-to-covid-19-outbreak-2/|title=Scottish Six Days Trial and Pre '65 Trial cancelled due to Covid-19 outbreak|date=16 March 2020|website=The Oban Times|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/highlands/2077336/coronavirus-lochabers-scottish-six-days-trial-event-cancelled/|title=Coronavirus: Lochaber's Scottish Six Days Trial event cancelled|first=Stuart|last=Findlay|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===British national-level championships===\nAll British motorsport, including the [[2020 British Touring Car Championship|British Touring Car Championship]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/17/btcc-postpones-opening-three-rounds-coronavirus-policy-change/|title=BTCC postpones opening three rounds after coronavirus policy change|date=17 March 2020|website=Touring Car Times|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> the [[2020 British GT Championship|British GT Championship]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.britishgt.com/news/590/british-gt-season-opener-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak|title=British GT season opener postponed due to coronavirus outbreak|date=17 March 2020|publisher=britishgt.com|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> and the [[Britcar]] [[2020 Britcar Endurance Championship|Endurance]] and [[2020 Britcar Trophy Championship|Trophy Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britcar-endurance.com/newsRead.php?link=317&page=0|title=Opening Rounds Postponed|website=Britcar Endurance|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> were postoned until July 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/national/news/148772/uk-motorsport-on-hold-until-july-due-to-covid19|title=UK motorsport on hold until July to contain spread of coronavirus|first=Stefan Mackley, Paul|last=Lawrence|website=Autosport.com|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Monster trucks===\n[[Monster Jam]] events in multiple localities were affected. Shows in [[Austin, Texas]], [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], [[Columbia, South Carolina]], [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], [[Columbus, Ohio]], [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], and [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]] were postponed; and a show in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]] was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.monsterjam.com/en-US/event-basic-page|title=Event basic page &#124; Monster Jam|website=www.monsterjam.com|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hot Wheels|Hot Wheels Monster Trucks Live]] postponed a show in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whas11.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/hot-wheels-monster-trucks-postponed/417-fe68c6a7-fba6-46f3-b913-d4ab3ad5cc99|title=Hot Wheels Monster Trucks Live postpones shows this weekend|website=WHAS11|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMonster X Tour postponed it's World Finals event in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://alohastadium.hawaii.gov/main/monster-x-tour/|title=MONSTER X TOUR WORLD FINALS 2020 \u2013 RESCHEDULED JULY 25-26|website=alohastadium.hawaii.gov|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020, [[Monster Jam World Finals XXI|World Finals XXI]], scheduled to take place May 2\u20133, 2020, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|title=Monster Jam World Finals 2020 Cancelled|date=March 27, 2020|url=https://www.monsterjam.com/en-US/2020-worldfinals-cancelled|publisher=[[Monster Jam]]|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Radio-controlled racing===\nDespite taking place in the second half of the year, all 4 blocks (representing Asia ([[Far East Model Car Association|FEMCA]]), North America ([[Remotely Operated Auto Racers|ROAR]]), Europe ([[European Federation of Radio Operated Model Automobiles|EFRA]]) and the rest of the world ([[Fourth Association of Model Auto Racing|FAMAR]])) and the [[International Federation of Model Auto Racing|IFMAR committee]] have agreed to postpone all remaining [[IFMAR World Championships]] ([[2020 IFMAR ISTC World Championship|1:10 Electric Touring Car]] in Heemstede, Netherlands); [[2020 IFMAR 1:8 IC Off-Road World Championship|1:8 IC Off-Road]] in Cianorte, Brasil and [[2020 IFMAR 1:10 IC Touring Car World Championship|1:10 IC Touring Car]] in Brisbane, Australia) to an alternative date, possibly early 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverc.com/news/announcements/22360-All_2020_IFMAR_World_Championships_Postponed/ |title=All 2020 IFMAR World Championships Postponed |publisher=LiveRC.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redrc.net/2020/03/ifmar-call-off-2020-season/ |title=IFMAR call off 2020 season |publisher=Red RC |date= March 28, 2020|accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> This was the first postponement since 2001 when the events of the [[September 11 attacks]] caused the [[IFMAR 1:10 Electric Off-Road World Championship|1:10 Electric Off-Road Worlds]] to be moved to May the following year.\n\n==Poker==\n\nAs of March 18, most casinos and other gaming venues worldwide have been closed indefinitely and many upcoming live [[poker tournament]]s have been either postponed, cancelled or (in jurisdictions where currently permitted) moved to an [[online poker|online platform]]. Tournaments originally scheduled to be played live and now being played online include the 2020 [[Irish Poker Open]].\n\nThe pandemic has resulted in a massive increase in online poker traffic. It is believed to have directed both professional and recreational players who normally prefer live poker to online platforms due the indefinite closure of most casinos and other live gaming venues worldwide, with even many [[Underground poker|unlicensed venues]] shutting down. In addition, the sudden dearth of live entertainment options due to the widespread disruption of the sports and entertainment schedules around the world is believed to have resulted in more than the usual number of casual players turning to online poker as an alternative. Many operators reported traffic of double or more the previous volume, depending on the time of day.\n\n==Professional wrestling==\n===New Japan Pro-Wrestling===\nIn accordance with recommendations from the Japanese Ministry of Health, [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) decided to cancel all scheduled shows from March 1 through March 15.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-cancels-shows-march-1-15-due-coronavirus-outbreak-305026 |title=NJPW CANCELS SHOWS FROM MARCH 1\u201315 DUE TO CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK |first=Joseph |last=Currier |date=February 26, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On March 10, NJPW announced that they were cancelling all shows through March 22, which meant that they either cancelled or postponed the [[New Japan Cup#2020|2020 New Japan Cup]] as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-cancels-remainder-new-japan-cup-tour-due-coronavirus-306136 |title=NJPW CANCELS REMAINDER OF NEW JAPAN CUP TOUR DUE TO CORONAVIRUS |first=Brian |last=Rose |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> The [[World Wonder Ring Stardom|Stardom]] promotion, sister company of NJPW also owned by [[Bushiroad]], also made adjustments to their scheduled, cancelling shows from February 19 to March 14. Their March 8 show in [[Korakuen Hall]] was held without any spectators in attendance, instead streaming live on their [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/stardom-makes-major-schedule-changes-due-coronavirus-outbreak-304441 |title=STARDOM MAKES MAJOR SCHEDULE CHANGES DUE TO CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK |first=Josh |last=Nason |date=February 18, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>\n\n===WWE===\nAmerican promotion [[WWE]] began to move the broadcasts of its weekly programs, including ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]]'' and ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' (which usually broadcast from arenas), and ''[[WWE NXT|NXT]]'' (which is usually filmed at [[Full Sail University]]; the school has suspended group activities through April)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2020/03/13/wwe-moves-smackdown-taping-to-orlandos-wwe-performance-center-at-full-sail-amid-coronavirus-concerns |title=WWE moves 'SmackDown' taping to Orlando's WWE Performance Center at Full Sail amid coronavirus concerns |last=Moyer |first=Matthew |website=Orlando Weekly |language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> to the [[WWE Performance Center]] in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], beginning with ''SmackDown'' on March 13, with no audience and only essential staff in attendance. The first ''SmackDown'' and ''Raw'' broadcasts under this arrangement included fewer live matches than usual episodes, with time filled by encores of matches from recent WWE [[pay-per-view]] events ([[Elimination Chamber (2020)|Elimination Chamber]] and [[Royal Rumble (2020)|Royal Rumble]] respectively).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-raw-results-recap-grades-steve-austin-celebrates-new-wrestlemania-36-matches-made/live/|title=WWE Raw results, recap, grades: Steve Austin celebrates, new WrestleMania 36 matches made|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/coronavirus-wwe-smackdown-live-1203532469/ |title=WWE Moves 'SmackDown Live' to Orlando Performance Center With No Live Audience Due to Coronavirus |last=Otterson |first=Joe |date=March 12, 2020 |website=Variety|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-smackdown-results-recap-grades-john-cena-caps-surreal-empty-arena-showy-you-have-to-see/live/ |title=WWE SmackDown results, recap, grades: John Cena caps surreal empty arena show you have to see |website=CBSSports.com|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> The promotion also postponed some of its upcoming [[house show]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2020/03/13/22805585.html |title=WWE house shows cancelled, AEW alters plans |website=canoe.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the [[NXT TakeOver: Tampa Bay]] event and [[WWE Hall of Fame (2020)|2020 Hall of Fame ceremony]] were postponed to unannounced dates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/134766/wwe-hall-of-fame-nxt-takeover-off.html?p=1|title=WWE HALL OF FAME, NXT TAKEOVER OFF|publisher=PW Insider|website=pwinsider.com|first=Mike|last=Johnson|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[WrestleMania 36]] was originally scheduled to be held at [[Tampa, Florida]]'s [[Raymond James Stadium]]. On March 16, WWE announced that it would also be produced from the Performance Center, as well as a second, unannounced venue, and air across two nights (April 4 and 5).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/wrestlemania-canceled-coronavirus-wwe-tampa-1202881422/|title=WrestleMania To Stream Live Without Audience Due To Coronavirus Outbreak|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|date=2020-03-16|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/wwe-splits-audience-less-wrestlemania-36-into-two-nights/|title=WWE Splits Audience-Less WrestleMania 36 Into Two Nights|last=Maglio|first=Tony|date=2020-03-18|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/article/wrestlemania-36-two-night-wwe-network-rob-gronkowski-host|title=Unprecedented two-night WrestleMania to be hosted by Rob Gronkowski on WWE Network|date=March 17, 2020|work=WWE|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> It was then reported by ''[[PWInsider]]'' on March 21 that WWE would be filming all remaining episodes of ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' preceding WrestleMania, as well as the event itself\u2014in advance over the following days, rather than air them live.<ref name=\"taped\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/134908/wwe-scheduled-to-tape-everything-through-wrestlemania-this-week.html?p=1|title=WWE SCHEDULED TO TAPE EVERYTHING THROUGH WRESTLEMANIA THIS WEEK|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=March 21, 2020|publisher=PWInsider|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===All Elite Wrestling===\nOn March 12, [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW) announced the relocation of its two remaining live broadcasts of ''[[AEW Dynamite|Dynamite]]'' for the month of March, scheduled for [[Rochester, New York]] and [[Newark, New Jersey]] respectively, to an alternative location with no audience. AEW stated that it had re-booked the two cities for future episodes in July. Their [[AEW Blood and Guts|Blood and Guts]] show was also postponed.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbr.com/aew-dynamite-coronavirus-venue-changes/ |title=AEW Announces Venue Changes, Including Blood & Guts Show, Due to COVID-19 |date=2020-03-13 |website=CBR |language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> AEW has since originated programming from [[TIAA Bank Field]]'s [[Daily's Place]] amphitheater in [[Jacksonville, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news4jax.com/news/local/2020/03/13/aew-moves-show-from-rochester-to-jacksonville-due-to-coronavirus/|title=AEW moves show from Rochester to Jacksonville due to coronavirus|last=Mealey|first=Jason|date=2020-03-13|website=WJXT|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n===Impact Wrestling===\nOn March 16, [[Impact Wrestling]] announced that [[Lockdown (2020)|Lockdown]] scheduled for March 28 in [[Windsor, Ontario]], and March Breakdown scheduled for March 29 in [[Belleville, Michigan]] have been postponed. On March 17, Impact Wrestling announced that [[TNA: There's No Place Like Home]] has been cancelled along with the other events associated with WrestleCon. On March 24, it was announced that [[TNA Against All Odds|Against All Odds]] scheduled for April 17 in Toronto, [[Rebellion (2020)|Rebellion]] scheduled for April 19 in Columbus, and the TV tapings schedule for April 24 and 25 were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://impactwrestling.com/our-response-to-covid-19/ |title=An Update on Events |date=March 24, 2020 |website=Impact Wrestling |language=en|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ring of Honor===\nOn March 12, [[Ring of Honor]] announced the cancellations of its [[ROH 18th Anniversary Show]] scheduled for March 13 and its ''Past vs. Present'' event scheduled for March 14 at Sam's Town Live in [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rohwrestling.com/news/roh-18th-anniversary-and-past-vs-present-shows-cancellation |title=ROH 18TH ANNIVERSARY AND PAST VS PRESENT SHOWS CANCELLATION |date=March 12, 2020 |website=Ring of Honor |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 17, Ring of Honor announced the cancellation of all events through May 31.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rohwrestling.com/news/roh-cancels-all-live-events-through-may-31st-2020 |title=ROH 18TH ROH CANCELS ALL LIVE EVENTS THROUGH MAY 31ST, 2020 |date=March 17, 2020 |website=Ring of Honor |language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre===\nThe Mexican [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] company announced that they were cancelling their shows in Guadalajara, Jalisco to comply with the statewide recommendations. The promotion cancelled both their Tuesday ''Martes de Glamour'' shows and their Sunday ''Domingos Tapat\u00edos'' shows for the foreseeable future.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://superluchas.com/funciones-canceladas-por-coronavirus-en-mexico/ |title=Primeras funciones canceladas por Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |language=Spanish |work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] |first=Carlos |last=Acosta}}</ref>\n\n===Lucha Libre AAA Worldwide===\nOn March 13, [[Lucha Libre AAA Worldwide]] announced that they were cancelling their next major show, the 2020 ''[[Rey de Reyes (2020)|Rey de Reyes]]''  (\"King of Kings\") show originally scheduled for March 21 in Medida, Yucat\u00e1n. They announced that they would announce a future date for the event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://superluchas.com/aaa-se-cancela-rey-de-reyes-2020-por-coronavirus/ |title=AAA: Se cancela \"Rey de Reyes 2020\" por Coronavirus | trans-title= AAA: Cancelling \"Rey de Reyes 2020\" because of the Coronoavirus |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |language=Spanish |work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] |first=Carlos |last=Acosta}}</ref>\n\n=== National Wrestling Alliance ===\nOn March 16, [[National Wrestling Alliance]] announced the suspension of its operations until June, which included the [[Crockett Cup (2020)|2020 Crockett Cup]] on April 19 and [[NWA Power]] tapings on April 20 and April 21. NWA also cancelled an airing of Super Powerrr, scheduled for March 17, in order to not create confusion in the marketplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalwrestlingalliance.com/news/nwa-suspends-crockett-cup-amp-nwa-powerrr-live-events|title=NWA SUSPENDS CROCKETT CUP & NWA POWERRR LIVE EVENTS|website=NWA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n==Rodeo==\nThe 2020 [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] was cancelled after a festival attendee was diagnosed positive with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.click2houston.com/rodeo/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-amid-growing-concerns-over-coronavirus/|title=Houston Rodeo canceled; coronavirus patient attended Rodeo cookoff in February|last=Barker|first=Daniela Sternitzky-Di Napoli, Aaron|date=2020-03-12|website=KPRC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Rowing==\nFour [[Rowing at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|Olympic qualification regattas]] were cancelled, including the final qualification event scheduled to be held in [[Lucerne]], [[Switzerland]], from 17 to 19 May. All three events of the 2020 [[World Rowing Cup]] were also cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=Joint Decisions related to the impact of the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) on remaining Olympic and Paralympic qualification events |url=http://www.worldrowing.com/news/joint-decisions-related-the-impact-the-novel-coronavirus-covid-remaining-olympic-and-paralympic-qualification-events |website=World Rowing |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[The Boat Race 2020]], due to take place on the [[River Thames]] in [[London]] on 29 March, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2020-03-16/the-boat-race-has-been-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus/ | publisher = ITV| title = The Boat Race has been cancelled due to Coronavirus | date = 16 March 2020 | accessdate = 17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Rugby league==\nThe Australian/New Zealand [[National Rugby League]] was scheduled to continue with no spectators permitted in the stadiums however this was abandoned after round two.\n\nFor the first time in the competition's history, the entire season was suspended indefinitely on 23 March 2020,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2020/03/23/nrl-suspends-competition-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/|title=NRL suspends competition due to coronavirus pandemic|date=23 March 2020|work=National Rugby League|author=Dan Walsh}}</ref> and if the season cannot be restarted by 1 September, it will be abandoned with no premiership awarded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2020/03/24/nrl-tells-clubs-season-needs-to-start-by-september-to-be-salvaged/|title=NRL tells clubs season must restart by September to be salvaged|publisher=NRL.com|first=Dan|last=Walsh|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSuper League and the Rugby Football League suspended the season until 3 April as a result of the spread of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/51911290 |title=Coronavirus: Rugby Football League suspends season until 3 April |date=March 16, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 16, 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Rugby union==\nAt the end of February and start of March, the [[2020 Six Nations Championship]] saw all games against [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]] postponed due to the worsening situation in that country,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51749254 |title=Coronavirus: England's Six Nations games against Italy postponed |date=March 5, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 13, 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> with games against the [[Scotland women's national rugby union team|Scotland women's team]] also cancelled as one of the players tested positive and the team went into isolation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51777621 |title=Women's Six Nations: Scotland v France postponed after home player tests positive for coronavirus |date=March 6, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 13, 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> By March 13, the competition had been suspended.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907 |title=Six Nations: Wales v Scotland off because of coronavirus |date=March 13, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 13, 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> On March 12, the [[Pro14]] European rugby competition was suspended,.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51858815 |title=Coronavirus: Pro14 suspended indefinitely due to coronavirus |date=March 12, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 13, 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Super Rugby]], two fixtures of Japanese team [[Sunwolves]] had been moved to Australia from Japan, while Australia announced on 12 March that beginning in the next round of fixtures, all matches held in Australia would be played with no spectators, but otherwise continue as normal. However, on 14 March, New Zealand (who fields five teams in the competition) announced that it will require 14 days self-isolation for any person that arrives in the country from outside of the Pacific Islands, regardless of origin and including New Zealand citizens. League organizer [[SANZAAR]] stated that it was evaluating the impact of this restriction,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/rugby/super-rugby/super-rugby-coronavirus-news-2020-new-zealand-government/news-story/794c8a43de0a3806ea699a7503063461 |title=Super Rugby season on verge of shutdown after NZ restrictions |date=2020-03-14 |website=Fox Sports |language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rugby.com.au:443/news/2020/03/13/corona-virus-international-updates |title=Coronavirus: How rugby has been affected around the world |website=www.rugby.com.au |language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rugby.com.au:443/news/2020/03/12/super-rugby-waratahs-coronavirus |title=LOCKOUT: Coronavirus forces rugby behind closed doors next week but fans welcome at weekend |website=www.rugby.com.au |language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> and ultimately announced later in the day that the season would be suspended following the completion of the weekend's fixtures.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/rugby-union/all-super-rugby-matches-to-be-cancelled-after-sunday-s-fixtures-20200314-p54a4u.html |title=All Super Rugby matches to be cancelled after Sunday's fixtures |last=Decent |first=Tom |date=2020-03-14 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, [[Major League Rugby]] in the United States suspended its third season for 30 days,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.majorleague.rugby/news/major-league-rugby-suspends-2020-season-for-30-days/|title=MAJOR LEAGUE RUGBY SUSPENDS 2020 SEASON FOR 30 DAYS|website=Major League Rugby|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> but on March 18, organizers announced that it will suspend until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americasrugbynews.com/2020/03/18/major-league-rugby-to-suspend-until-2021/|title=Major League Rugby to suspend until 2021|date=2020-03-19|website=Americas Rugby News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Shooting==\nThe 2020 [[ISSF World Cup]], which was to commence on March 15 in New Delhi, was postponed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/virus-hits-indian-sports/articleshow/74519560.cms |title=Virus hits Indian sports |work=Economic Times |accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The Olympic Test Event in Tokyo, originally scheduled for April 2020, was also cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.issf-sports.org/news.ashx?newsid |title=Test Event \"READY STEADY TOKYO\" |publisher=International Shooting Sport Federation |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Short track speed skating==\nThe 2020 [[World Short Track Speed Skating Championships]] in Seoul, South Korea scheduled 13\u201315 March were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://speedskating.ca/news-and-info/news/isu-officially-cancels-world-short-track-championships-in-south-korea-due-to-coronavirus|title=ISU Officially Cancels World Short Track Championships in South Korea due to Coronavirus &#124; Speed Skating Canada|website=speedskating.ca|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Snooker==\n\nThe [[2020 Gibraltar Open]] and its qualifying rounds took place from 11 to 15 March.  For the first day, there was a limit of 100 spectators per session.  On the remaining days, there were no spectators.  A significant number of players withdrew, and there was a shortage of referees, with some early matches played without referees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bizarre times at Gibraltar Open as games played without referees and player brings wrong cue|publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|]]|first=Phil|last=Haigh|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/15/gibraltar-open-chaos-12400612/}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Tour Championship]], originally scheduled for 17 to 22 March, was postponed until 21 July.\n\nThe 2020 [[China Open (snooker)|China Open]], originally scheduled for 30 March to 5 April, was indefinitely postponed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: China Open in Beijing postponed|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/51325726|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=31 Jan 2020|accessdate=31 Mar 2020|}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 World Snooker Championship]], originally scheduled 18 April to 4 May, has been postponed,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/51964887 |title=Coronavirus: World Snooker Championship at Crucible postponed |date=2020-03-20 |accessdate=2020-03-20 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> tentatively until July or August.\n\nThe [[2020 World Women's Snooker Championship]], originally scheduled 22 to 27 June, has been postponed. \n<ref>{{cite web|title=World Women's Championship Postponed|url=https://wst.tv/world-womens-championship-postponed/|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|publisher=[[World Snooker Tour]]}}</ref>\n\n==Squash==\nThe 2020 [[European Squash Individual Championships]], scheduled to take place in [[Eindhoven]], the Netherlands from 29 April to 2 May are cancelled.<ref name=\"nu.nl\"/>\n\n==Surfing==\nThe 2020 [[World Surf League]], which was due to start in Australia on 26 March, is on hold until at least June. The first event of the season, the [[Quiksilver Pro Gold Coast|Corona Open Gold Coast]], was cancelled, while the second and third events, the [[Rip Curl Pro|Rip Curl Pro Bells Beach]] and [[Margaret River Pro]], were postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=WSL Cancels All Events In March |url=https://www.worldsurfleague.com/posts/449880/wsl-cancels-all-events-in-march |website=World Surf League |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=WSL Cancels Or Postpones Events Through May |url=https://www.worldsurfleague.com/posts/450379/wsl-cancels-or-postpones-events-through-may |website=World Surf League |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 ISA World Surfing Games]], scheduled to be held from 9 to 17 May in [[El Salvador]], will now take place from 6 to 14 June in the same location.<ref>{{cite web |title=ISA Postpones Surf City El Salvador ISA World Surfing Games |url=https://www.isasurf.org/isa-postpones-surf-city-el-salvador-isa-world-surfing-games/ |website=International Surfing Association |date=March 22, 2020 |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Swimming==\nThe [[YMCA]] [[Short course|Short Course]] Nationals swim meet is canceled in the United States for the first time since 1947.<ref>{{cite web |title=YMCA Short Course Nationals Canceled For First Time Since 1947 |url=https://swimswam.com/ymca-short-course-nationals-canceled-for-first-time-since-1947/ |website=Swim Swam |date=March 11, 2020 |publisher=Swim Swam |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Table tennis==\nThe [[2020 World Team Table Tennis Championships]] were scheduled to be held from 22 to 29 March in [[Busan]], [[South Korea]]. Provisionally, the event will now be held from 21 to 28 June.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 World Table Tennis Championships postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/02/25/2020-world-table-tennis-championships-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=February 25, 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 ITTF-ATTU Asian Cup]] was scheduled to be held from 28 February to 1 March in [[Hainan]], [[China]], but was postponed until later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Postponement of 2020 Asian Cup |url=http://www.attu.org/en/news/1057 |website=ATTU |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFive events on the [[2020 ITTF World Tour]] have also been postponed, including the [[China Open (table tennis)|China Open]] and the [[Japan Open (table tennis)|Japan Open]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 ITTF World Tour Japan Open postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/03/10/2020-ittf-world-tour-japan-open-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hong Kong and China Opens postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/03/20/hong-kong-china-opens-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Four [[Table tennis at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|Olympic qualifying events]], scheduled to be held in April, were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=ITTF consider Tokyo 2020 Olympic qualification measures after events postponed |url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1092033/ittf-tokyo-2020-qualification-plans |website=Inside The Games |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis==\nOn March 12, the [[2020 ATP Tour|ATP Tour]] and [[2020 ATP Challenger Tour|ATP Challenger Tour]] were initially suspended for six weeks due to the escalating health and safety issues caused by the coronavirus. Also, the [[2020 WTA Tour|WTA Tour]] were initially suspended for eight weeks. However, due to safety concerns, they extended to suspend until at least before June 8.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.atptour.com/en/news/atp-tour-2020-six-week-suspension-decision |title=ATP Suspends Tour For Six Weeks Due To Public Health & Safety Issues Over COVID-19|date=March 12, 2020 |website=ATP|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the [[2020 French Open]], originally scheduled for May 24\u2013June 7, was postponed to September 20\u2013October 4.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/sports/tennis/french-open-postponed.html|title=The French Open Is Postponed, to the Surprise of the Tours|last=Clarey|first=Christopher|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Volleyball==\nOn March 13, the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Volleyball|International Volleyball Federation]] (FIVB) decided to postpone the Nations League for [[2020 FIVB Volleyball Men's Nations League|men]] (finals scheduled for [[Turin]], Italy) and [[2020 FIVB Volleyball Women's Nations League|women]] until after the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] caused by the outbreak of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fivb.com/en/about/news/fivb-announces-changes-to-events-calendar?id=90648 |title=FIVB announces changes to events calendar |date=March 13, 2020 |website=FIVB|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Water polo==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2020 Women's Water Polo Olympic Qualification Tournament]] was scheduled to take place in [[Trieste]], [[Italy]], March 8\u201315, 2020. On February 28, 2020, [[FINA|International Swimming Federation]] (FINA) announced that the tournament would be postponed to May 17\u201324 due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fina.org/news/fina-announcement-fina-womens-water-polo-olympic-games-qualification-tournament |date=February 28, 2020 |title=FINA ANNOUNCEMENT: FINA Women's Water Polo Olympic Games Qualification Tournament |publisher=[[FINA]] |website=fina.org |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2020, FINA announced that several international water polo tournaments would be postponed due to the coronavirus pandemic. The [[2020 Men's Water Polo Olympic Qualification Tournament]] due to take place in [[Rotterdam]], [[Netherlands]], March 22\u201329, 2020, would be postponed to May 31 \u2013 June 7. The [[2020 FINA Men's Water Polo World League]] and [[2020 FINA Women's Water Polo World League]] would be postponed to September\u2013October 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fina.org/news/pr-16-first-meeting-fina-covid-19-taskforce |date=March 12, 2020 |title=PR 16 \u2013 First meeting of FINA COVID-19 taskforce |publisher=[[FINA]] |website=fina.org |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n[[2020 Asian Water Polo Championship]], the Asian continental qualification for the [[Water polo at the 2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Olympic water polo tournament]], was scheduled to take place in [[Nur-Sultan]], [[Kazakhstan]], February 12\u201316, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://astanatimes.com/2020/01/kazakh-capital-to-host-olympics-water-polo-asian-pre-qualification-tournament/ |first=Nurdana |last=Adylkhanova |date=January 31, 2020 |title=Kazakh capital to host Olympics water polo Asian pre-qualification tournament |publisher=Astana Times |website=astanatimes.com |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> In late January the event was cancelled as the Kazakh Government suspended all flights and visas from [[China]] due to concerns about the coronavirus outbreak in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/coronavirus-claims-first-tokyo-olympic-victim-2020-asian-water-polo-championships/ |first=Michael |last=Randazzo |date=13 February 2020 |title=Coronavirus Claims First Tokyo Olympic Victim: 2020 Asian Water Polo Championships |publisher=[[Swimming World]] |website=swimmingworldmagazine.com |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> In mid-February [[Asia Swimming Federation]] decided to use the final ranking of the [[Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games|2018 Asian Games]] to allocate its continental quotas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://total-waterpolo.com/asian-federation-decides-kazakhstan-and-china-goes-to-tokyo/ |first=Ivan |last=Curcic |date=February 14, 2020 |title=Asian Federation decides: Kazakhstan and China go to Tokyo |publisher=Total Waterpolo |website=total-waterpolo.com |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nOn February 28, 2020, [[LEN|European Swimming League]] (LEN) announced that the match of [[2019\u201320 LEN Champions League]] Day 10 between [[Ferencv\u00e1rosi TC (men's water polo)|Ferencv\u00e1ros]] (Hungary) and [[Pro Recco]] (Italy), and the match of [[2019\u201320 LEN Euro Cup]] semifinal between [[Egri VK]] (Hungary) and [[AN Brescia]] (Italy) would be postponed due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.len.eu/?p=16594 |date=February 28, 2020 |title=Two matches postponed \u2013 Euro Cup & Champions League |publisher=[[LEN]] |website=len.eu |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2020, LEN announced that all eight matches of 2019\u201320 LEN Champions League Day 11, the second leg of the [[2019\u201320 LEN Euro League Women]] quarter-finals, and the 2020 men's U19 European Championships qualification tournaments would be postponed to later dates due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.len.eu/?p=16631 |date=March 11, 2020 |title=LEN postpones upcoming water polo competitions |publisher=[[LEN]] |website=len.eu |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn March 11, 2020, the [[USA Water Polo]] (USAWP) announced that the 2020 ODP Girls National Water Polo Championship would be postponed, and the exhibition matches scheduled to be played on March 19\u201321, 2020 in [[California]] between [[United States men's national water polo team|United States]] and [[Spain men's national water polo team|Spain]] men's national water polo teams would be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://usawaterpolo.org/news/2020/3/11/general-2020-odp-girls-national-championship-postponed-usa-mens-national-team-series-with-spain-canceled.aspx |date=March 11, 2020 |title=2020 ODP Girls National Championship Postponed; USA Men's National Team Series With Spain Canceled |publisher=[[USA Water Polo]] |website=usawaterpolo.org |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2020, USAWP announced that the inaugural USA Water Polo Division III Women's National Championship scheduled for May 8\u201310, 2020 in [[Southern California]] would be rescheduled for May, 2021; and week three of the 2020 National Water Polo League and the 2020 National League Championship/Fisher Cup would be canceled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://usawaterpolo.org/news/2020/3/16/general-usa-water-polo-announces-the-cancellation-of-multiple-upcoming-events.aspx |date=March 16, 2020 |title=USA Water Polo Announces The Cancellation Of Multiple Upcoming Events |publisher=[[USA Water Polo]] |website=usawaterpolo.org |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Oceania===\nOn March 16, 2020, the [[Australian Water Polo]] (WPA) announced that the 2020 [[Australian National Water Polo League]] would be terminated, the 2020 WPA National Championships scheduled to take place in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]] in May would be cancelled, and the 2020 Open Championships (Country and Masters) scheduled to take place in the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Queensland]] in May would be postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.waterpoloaustralia.com.au/news/covid-19-virus-i-changes-to-national-calendar-/ |date=March 16, 2020 |title=COVID-19 virus I Changes to National Calendar |publisher=[[Australian Water Polo]] |website=waterpoloaustralia.com.au |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of major events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in sports]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|sports]]\n[[Category:Sports events cancelled due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n[[Category:Sports events postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{current related||2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Impact of coronavirus}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] has caused the most significant disruption to the [[2020 in sports|worldwide sporting calendar]] since [[World War II]]. [[Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Across the world]] and to varying degrees, sports events have been cancelled or postponed.<ref name=\"BBC overview\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: How the virus has impacted sporting events around the world |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/51605235 |website=BBC |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1= |first1= |title=How the coronavirus is affecting sports leagues and events |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-09/coronavirus-latest-news-sports-world |website=Los Angeles Times |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Multiple event competitions==\nThe [[2020 Arctic Winter Games]] were cancelled,<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/arctic-winter-games-cancelled-coronavirus-1.5490055 |title = 'Shocked and disappointed': Arctic Winter Games cancelled due to coronavirus concerns &#124; CBC News}}</ref> while the [[2020 ASEAN Para Games]] were postponed.<ref name=philippinencaa>{{cite news |last1=Villar |first1=Joey |title=NCAA succumbs to coronavirus scare, postpones all high school games |url=https://www.philstar.com/sports/2020/02/07/1991189/ncaa-succumbs-coronavirus-scare-postpones-all-high-school-games |accessdate=February 7, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> In the Philippines, the [[NCAA Season 95]] and [[UAAP Season 82]] were both indefinitely suspended.<ref name=philippinencaa/><ref name=pba/> NCAA Season 95 was terminated on 19 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/sports/university/ncaa/255125-season-95-terminated-coronavirus-luzon-lockdown|title=NCAA Season 95 terminated|last=Go|first=Beatrice|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Summer Olympics===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the 2020 Summer Olympics}}\nThe 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic itself has been a concern for the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] which were scheduled to take place in [[Tokyo]] starting at the end of July. Due to the Olympics, the [[Government of Japan|country's government]] has been taking extra precautions to help minimise the outbreak's worst impact.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/abe-brushes-worries-virus-impact-tokyo-olympics-68719487 |title=Abe brushes aside worries of virus impact on Tokyo Olympics |first=A. B. C. |last=News |publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/01/tokyo-2020-organisers-fight-false-rumours-olympics-cancelled-over-coronavirus-crisis |title=Tokyo 2020 organisers fight false rumours Olympics cancelled over coronavirus crisis |first=Justin |last=McCurry |date=February 1, 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> However, qualifying events are being canceled or postponed almost daily.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sltrib.com/sports/2020/03/10/coronavirus-already/ |title=Coronavirus already causing Olympic chaos at qualifying events |first=Ellingworth |last=Ellingworth |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Salt Lake Tribune}}</ref> There have been suggestions that the 2020 Olympics be moved to [[London]] in light of the situation. Governor of Tokyo [[Yuriko Koike]] indicated at the end of February 2020 that such a move was not under consideration at the moment.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Keh|first=Andrew|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/sports/olympics/tokyo-coronavirus.html|title=Grappling With Coronavirus, Tokyo Olympic Leaders Have No Good Options|date=2020-02-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-25|last2=Dooley|first2=Ben|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-02-21/tokyo-governor-2020-olympics-coronavirus|title=Tokyo governor: 'Inappropriate' to suggest moving 2020 Olympics because of coronavirus|date=2020-02-21|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nThe traditional [[Olympic flame]] lighting ceremony in [[Olympia, Greece]], to mark the start of the [[2020 Summer Olympics torch relay]] was held on March 12 without spectators.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-olympics-2020-flame/tokyo-2020-torch-lit-behind-closed-doors-in-ancient-olympia-idUSKBN20Z1EO |title=Tokyo 2020 torch lit behind closed doors in ancient Olympia |website=Reuters |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, it was announced that the Summer Olympics would be postponed to 2021, still to be held in Tokyo. Six days later, the Olympics made a reschedule date to twelve months from the original scheduled dates of 24 July to 9 August 2020, to 23 July to 8 August 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/fc044c3fa987a60534a804046215f3de|title=On hold: Tokyo Olympics postponed to 2021|date=2020-03-24|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=IOC_2021_Dates>{{cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/ioc-ipc-tokyo-2020-organising-committee-and-tokyo-metropolitan-government-announce-new-dates-for-the-olympic-and-paralympic-games-tokyo-2020 |title=IOC, IPC, Tokyo 2020 Organising Committee and Tokyo Metropolitan Government Announce New Dates for the Olympic and Paralympic Games Tokyo 2020 |date=2020-03-30 |website=olympic.org |access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Gaelic games===\nThe [[Gaelic games]] of [[Gaelic football|football]], [[hurling]], [[camogie]] and [[ladies' Gaelic football|ladies' football]] \u2013 mostly played in [[Ireland]] \u2013 saw all competitions suspended from 12 March 2020. The [[2020 National Hurling League|National Hurling League]], [[2020 National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]], [[2020 National Camogie League|National Camogie League]] and [[2020 Ladies' National Football League|Ladies' National Football League]] were suspended, with competitions not intended to resume until 29 March at the earliest.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaa.ie/news-archive/news/gaa-camogie-association-and-the-lgfa-suspend-all-activity/|title=GAA, Camogie Association, and the LGFA suspend all activity|website=www.gaa.ie}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.balls.ie/gaa/gaa-camogie-association-gaa-suspend-activities-march-29th-427885|title=GAA, Camogie Association And LGFA Suspend All Activity Until March 29th|first=P. J.|last=Browne|website=Balls.ie}}</ref> On 17 March, the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) confirmed that [[2020 Connacht Senior Football Championship|the opening fixture]] of the [[2020 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] \u2013 due to have taken place at [[Gaelic Park]] in [[Riverdale, Bronx|The Bronx]] on 3 May \u2013 had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/sport/gaa/galway-and-new-york-clash-first-major-casualty-of-pandemic-988773.html|title=Galway and New York clash first major casualty of pandemic|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|first=Eoghan|last=Cormican|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NCAA===\nOn March 11, 2020, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) \u2014 the main U.S. sanctioning body for [[College athletics in the United States|college athletics]] \u2014 initially announced that its winter-semester championships and tournaments, including its popular [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men's basketball tournament]] (widely known as \"March Madness\"), would be conducted with \"only essential staff and limited family attendance\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2020/03/11/ncaa-tournament-fans-banned-due-to-coronavirus-concerns/5024027002/ |title=NCAA men's and women's basketball tournaments will not include fans due to coronavirus concerns |first=Tom |last=Schad |newspaper=USA Today |date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> However, the following day, the NCAA announced that all remaining championship events for the 2019\u201320 academic year would be cancelled entirely. This marked the first cancellation in the 81-year history of the NCAA basketball tournament.<ref name=\"NCAA cancellations\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |title=NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships |publisher=NCAA |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===BUCS===\nOn 16 March 2020, [[British Universities and Colleges Sport]], the UK organisation for university sport, announced that all fixtures from 17 March to 1 April would not take place. Some individual events, like the [[orienteering]] and [[windsurfing]] championships were cancelled entirely, while others were postponed indefinitely.<ref name=\"BUCS Cancellations\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bucs.org.uk/update-covid-19-coronavirus.html|title=BUCS Statement regarding CoVid-19|publisher=BUCS|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Alpine skiing ==\nThe [[2019\u201320 FIS Alpine Ski World Cup]] ended two weeks earlier after World Cup races in Sweden, Slovenia, and Italy scheduled for March were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/international-ski-federation/news-multimedia/news/fis-alpine-ski-world-cup-finals-cortina-ita-cancelled |title=FIS Alpine Ski World Cup Finals in Cortina Cancelled |date=6 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/alpine-skiing/alpine-news-multimedia/news-multimedia/news/test2/audi-fis-women-s-world-cup-races-in-are-swe-cancelled |title=Audi FIS Women's World Cup races in Are (SWE) Cancelled |date=11 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fis-ski.com/en/alpine-skiing/alpine-news-multimedia/news-multimedia/news/test2/audi-fis-men-s-world-cup-races-in-kranjska-gora-slo-cancelled |title=Audi FIS Men's World Cup races in Kranjska Gora (SLO) Cancelled |date=12 March 2020 |publisher=[[International Ski Federation]] |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref> An earlier February World Cup race was moved from China to Austria.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.espn.com/olympics/skiing/story/_/id/28600579/world-cup-ski-races-canceled-china-move-austria |title=World Cup ski races canceled in China move to Austria |date=30 January 2020 |website=[[ESPN]] |agency=Associated Press |access-date=29 March 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Archery==\nThe opening stage of the [[2020 Archery World Cup]], scheduled to be held in [[Guatemala City]], [[Guatemala]] from 20 to 26 April, was postponed. Other events postponed include the [[Pan American Archery Championships]], which were scheduled to be held in [[Monterrey]], [[Mexico]], from 23 to 29 March, and the [[European Para-Archery Championships]], which were scheduled to be held in [[Olbia]], [[Italy]], from 18 to 26 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=International Archery Suspended Until 30 April due to COVID-19 Outbreak |url=https://worldarchery.org/news/178285/international-archery-suspended-until-30-april-due-covid-19-outbreak-1 |website=World Archery |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Association football==\nOn 13 March 2020, FIFA announced that clubs did not have to release players to their national teams during the international windows of March and April 2020, while players also had the option to decline a call-up without any consequences. FIFA also recommended that all international matches during these windows be postponed, though the final decision was left to the competition organisers or member associations for [[Exhibition game#International football|friendly]] matches.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/who-we-are/news/fifa-statement-x8681 |title=FIFA statement |work=[[FIFA]] |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy 28 March, [[2020 Belarusian Premier League|Belarusian Premier League]] and [[2019\u201320 Liga Primera de Nicaragua|Liga Primera de Nicaragua]] were the only two top flight national football leagues not suspended.<ref>[http://www.la-razon.com/marcas/futbol-covid-19-nicaragua-bielorrusia_0_3338666136.html En el planeta f\u00fatbol, solo Nicaragua y Bielorrusia contin\u00faan con sus torneos] la-razon.com {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n===Africa===\nOn 17 March 2020, [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] announced that the [[2020 African Nations Championship]] had been postponed to a later date due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cafonline.com/news-center/news/statement-on-total-chan-cameroon-2020|title=Statement on Total CHAN Cameroon 2020|publisher=CAF|date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nIn China, the [[2020 Chinese Super League]] was postponed as a result of the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecfa.cn/lstz/20200130/28537.html |title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u8db3\u534f\u5173\u4e8e2020\u8d5b\u5b63\u56fd\u5185\u8db3\u7403\u8d5b\u4e8b\u5ef6\u671f\u5f00\u59cb\u7684\u516c\u544a |work=Chinese Football Association |date=January 30, 2020 |accessdate=January 30, 2020 |language=zh}}</ref> In Hong Kong, the [[2020 Lunar New Year Cup]] was cancelled on January 23.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chan |first1=Kin-wa |title=Wuhan coronavirus: Lunar New Year Cup cancelled by government just hours after HKFA promotes the event |url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/hong-kong/article/3047415/wuhan-virus-lunar-new-year-cup-go-ahead-hong-kong-despite |website=South China Morning Post |date=January 23, 2020 |accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> Other leagues in Asia were affected, including South Korea's [[2020 K League 1|K League 1]] and Japan's [[2020 J1 League|J1 League]].<ref>{{cite news |title=K-League season postponed as COVID-19 spreads in South Korea |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/24/soccer/k-league-season-postponed-covid-19-spreads-south-korea/#.Xms5EqgzaUk |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Japan Times |agency=Associated Press |date=February 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Orlowitz |first1=Dan |title=Amid COVID-19 outbreak, J. League postpones all matches until March 15 |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/25/soccer/j-league/jleague-cancels-levain-cup-coronavirus/#.Xms5FagzaUk |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Japan Times |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 AFC Champions League|AFC Champions League]] and [[2020 AFC Cup|AFC Cup]] was also impacted, a number of group stage and play-off matches being postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-champions-league/latest/news/afc-competitions-update |title=AFC Competitions update |publisher=Asian Football Confederation |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, 2020, FIFA and AFC announced that [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] matches due to take place in March and June 2020 were postponed to later dates due to the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-afc.com/competitions/afc-asian-cup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers |publisher=AFC |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Play-off matches between South Korea and China in the [[2020 AFC Women's Olympic Qualifying Tournament]] were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers |publisher=FIFA.com |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn India, the remaining [[2019\u201320 I-League|I-League]] matches were postponed and the [[2020 Indian Super League Final|Indian Super League final]] was played behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-aiff.com/article/aiff-statement-10 |title=AIFF Statement |publisher=All India Football Federation|date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nThe championships of all [[Central Asian Football Association]] members were suspended.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Europe===\nIn Europe, various knockout matches in the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] and [[2019\u201320 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] were played [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] in February and March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2639297.html |title=Update on UEFA competition matches being played this week |work=UEFA |date=February 26, 2020 |access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2640496.html |title=Update on UEFA competition matches |work=UEFA |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> On March 12, 2020, [[UEFA]] announced that the elite qualification round of the men and women's under-17 and under-19 youth international tournaments had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=2640886.html |title=Postponement of Youth tournaments |publisher=UEFA.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The following day, UEFA postponed all fixtures for the following week in the Champions League, Europa League and [[2019\u201320 UEFA Youth League|Youth League]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/about-uefa/news/newsid=2641054.html |title=All of next week's UEFA matches postponed |work=UEFA |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany of the domestic European leagues were impacted in February and March 2020. After various fixtures were rescheduled or played behind closed doors, [[2019\u201320 Serie A|Serie A]] was postponed on March 9, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/51808683 |title=Coronavirus: All sport in Italy to be suspended because of outbreak |date=March 9, 2020 |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> On March 12, [[2019\u201320 La Liga|La Liga]] and the [[2019\u201320 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] were suspended for at least two weeks after a [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] basketball player tested positive for the virus, which resulted in Real Madrid's footballers being put in quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |title=Real Madrid players in quarantine and La Liga suspended due to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/12/real-madrid-players-in-quarantine-and-la-liga-suspended-due-to-coronavirus |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The [[2019\u201320 Eredivisie|Eredivisie]] was also suspended,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraaf.nl/sport/246406552/streep-door-eredivisie-en-interlands-van-oranje-in-maart|title=Streep door Eredivisie \u00e9n interlands van Oranje in maart|date=March 12, 2020|website=Telegraaf}}</ref> while [[2019\u201320 Ligue 1|Ligue 1]] and the [[2019\u201320 Bundesliga|Bundesliga]] followed suit shortly afterwards.<ref name=\"BBC overview\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lfp.fr/Articles/COMMUNIQU\u00c9S/2020/03/13/communique-de-la-lfp |title=Communiqu\u00e9 de la LFP |publisher=lfp.fr |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/coronavirus-what-games-are-cancelled-postponed-behind-closed-doors-overview-10410 |title=Coronavirus: Bundesliga suspended until 2 April |publisher=Bundesliga |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, the [[2019\u201320 Premier League|Premier League]] match between Manchester City and Arsenal, due to be played the next day, was postponed after a number of Arsenal players made close contact with Olympiacos owner [[Evangelos Marinakis]], who had tested positive for [[coronavirus]], when the two teams had met in the Europa League 13 days earlier.<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester City vs. Arsenal postponed after players exposed to Olympiakos owner Evangelos Marinakis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/english-premier-league/story/4071980/arsenal-vs-manchester-city-postponed-after-players-exposed-to-olympiakos-owner-evangelos-marinakis |website=ESPN |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Arsenal manager [[Mikel Arteta]] tested positive for the disease, prompting the team's Premier League match against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] for that weekend to also be postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arsenal boss Mikel Arteta tests positive for coronavirus, match against Brighton postponed |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/arsenal/story/4073648/arsenal-boss-mikel-arteta-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-squad-set-to-self-isolate |website=ESPN |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> As of March 13, there has been at least one recorded case of the disease affecting a player in the aforementioned leagues; Serie A footballers [[Daniele Rugani]] and [[Manolo Gabbiadini]], [[2. Bundesliga]] footballer [[Timo H\u00fcbers]], and Premier League footballer [[Callum Hudson-Odoi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/151101/official-gabbiadini-has-coronavirus |title=Official: Gabbiadini has Coronavirus |publisher=Football Italia |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/2020/03/13/chelsea-fc-training-facility-will-undergo-partial-closure-after- |title=CHELSEA FC TRAINING FACILITY WILL UNDERGO PARTIAL CLOSURE AFTER MEN'S TEAM PLAYER TESTED POSITIVE FOR COVID-19 |publisher=Chelsea Football Club |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Rugani tested positive while being [[Asymptomatic carrier|asymptomatic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51844945 |title=Coronavirus: Juventus centre-back Daniele Rugani tests positive for virus |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, English elite football was suspended until early April, including the [[Premier League]], [[English Football League]], [[FA Women's Super League]] and [[FA Women's Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Premier League and EFL suspended until 3 April at earliest |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51867989 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nBy 19 March, the [[2020 Belarusian Premier League|Belarusian Premier League]] was the only active top flight in all 55 UEFA member associations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.as.com/en/2020/03/19/football/1584633269_267045.html |title=Amid global coronavirus pandemic, new Belarus season starts |work=AS |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nConcerns were raised regarding [[UEFA Euro 2020]], being held in twelve host cities across Europe, and the potential impact of the coronavirus on players, staff and tournament visitors.<ref>{{cite news |last=Homewood |first=Brian |location=Rome |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy-soccer/uefa-says-monitoring-coronavirus-not-yet-clear-if-any-impact-on-euro-2020-idUSKBN20J1XS |title=UEFA says monitoring coronavirus, not yet clear if any impact on Euro 2020 |agency=Associated Press |date=February 25, 2020 |access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> UEFA president [[Aleksander \u010ceferin]] said the organisation was confident that the situation could be dealt with, while general secretary [[Theodore Theodoridis]] stated that UEFA was maintaining contact with the [[World Health Organization]] and national governments regarding the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last=MacInnes |first=Paul |location=Amsterdam |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/mar/03/uefa-congress-ceferin-coronavirus-dark-scenarios |title=Uefa's Ceferin warns against fixating on 'dark scenarios' over coronavirus threat |work=The Guardian |date=March 3, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> UEFA announced that a [[videoconference]] would be held on March 17 with representatives of its 55 member associations, along with a [[FIFPro]] representative and the boards of the [[European Club Association]] and [[European Leagues]], to discuss the response to the outbreak for domestic and European competitions, including Euro 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/about-uefa/news/newsid=2640887.html |title=UEFA calls meeting of European Football Stakeholders |work=UEFA |date=March 12, 2020 |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The tournament was moved by 12 months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/mediaservices/mediareleases/newsid=2641071.html |title=UEFA postpones EURO 2020 by 12 months |work=UEFA |date=17 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn March 12, 2020, the [[2020 CONCACAF Champions League|CONCACAF Champions League]] was suspended with immediate effect.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.concacafchampionsleague.com/en/article/concacaf-suspends-scotiabank-concacaf-champions-league-with-immediate-effect |title=Concacaf suspends Scotiabank Concacaf Champions League with immediate effect |publisher=CONCACAF Champions League |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The same day, [[2020 Major League Soccer season|Major League Soccer]] was suspended for 30 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/03/12/major-league-soccer-suspends-season-30-days-impact-coronavirus |title=MLS suspends 2020 season for 30 days due to coronavirus |publisher=mlssoccer.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Women's Soccer League]] (NWSL), whose [[2020 National Women's Soccer League season|season]] was not scheduled to start until April 18, canceled its preseason matches,<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.nwslsoccer.com/news/article/statement-from-nwsl-commissioner-lisa-baird-regarding-the-2020-season |title=Statement from NWSL Commissioner Lisa Baird regarding the 2020 season |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> and also imposed a moratorium on team training that initially ran through March 22.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.nwslsoccer.com/news/article/covid-19-resources-and-updates-for-nwsl-fans |title=COVID-19 resources and updates for NWSL fans |publisher=National Women's Soccer League |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> On March 19, Major League Soccer's suspension was extended to a target return date of May 10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/03/19/mls-extends-season-suspension-accordance-cdc-guidance-covid-19 |title=MLS extends season suspension in accordance with CDC guidance on COVID-19 |publisher=mlssoccer.com |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe day after MLS was initially postponed, all [[CONCACAF]] competitions scheduled for the next month were suspended. Match week 10 of Mexican [[Liga MX]] was played but as of March 15, league executives have now taken the decision to postpone Liga MX activity until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.concacaf.com/en/article/concacaf-suspends-all-its-competitions-scheduled-to-take-place-over-the-next-30-days |title=CONCACAF Champions League |publisher=CONCACAF |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 Major Arena Soccer League season]] was terminated early, effective March 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.maslsoccer.com/news/major-arena-soccer-league-to-end-regular-season-ef|title=MAJOR ARENA SOCCER LEAGUE TO END REGULAR SEASON EFFECTIVE IMMEDIATELY|publisher=Major Arena Soccer League|website=maslsoccer.com|first=Jeff|last=Husted|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[USL Championship]] suspended the [[2020 USL Championship season|2020 season]] on March 12, for at least 30 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uslchampionship.com/news_article/show/1094891|title=USL Championship Temporarily Suspends Play|publisher=uslchampionship.com|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Cricket in the West Indies|West Indies cricket championship]] was suspended due to the pandemic and [[Barbados]] was declared the champion on March 24.<ref>[https://apnews.com/435405d82ed4d043a7998c2a32fc8e87 Barbados declared winners of West Indies championship] AP, 24 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n===Oceania===\nOn March 9, 2020, the [[Oceania Football Confederation]] announced that all tournaments were postponed until May 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=OFC tournaments, workshops, training and courses postponed until 6 May |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc-tournaments-workshops-training-and-courses-postponed-until-6-may/ |publisher=OFC |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===South America===\nOn March 12, 2020, FIFA announced that the first two rounds of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|South American qualification for the 2022 World Cup]] due to take place in March 2020 were postponed to later dates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/update-on-upcoming-fifa-world-cup-qualifiers-in-south-america |title=Update on upcoming FIFA World Cup qualifiers in South America |publisher=FIFA.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The same day, CONMEBOL announced that the [[2020 Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores]] would be temporarily suspended.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-conmebol-libertadores-queda-suspendida-temporalmente |title=La CONMEBOL Libertadores queda suspendida temporalmente |publisher=CONMEBOL.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15 all top-tier football in Brazil was suspended until April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/eb6fe061d42f1c68f151697dfe25f1d8|title=The Latest: T-Wolves' Towns donating $100K to Mayo Clinic|date=March 15, 2020|website=AP NEWS}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March CONMEBOL announced that the 2020 edition of [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]] was postponed to 2021.<ref>{{cite news |title=Euro 2020 and Copa Am\u00e9rica Are Postponed for a Year |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/sports/euro-2020-postponed.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020|last1=Panja |first1=Tariq }}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n\nThe [[2021 World Athletics Indoor Championships|2020 World Athletics Indoor Championships]] were scheduled to be held from 13 to 15 March in [[Nanjing]], [[China]], but were postponed until March 2021.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Athletics to postpone World Athletics Indoor Championships Nanjing 2020 |url=https://www.worldathletics.org/news/press-releases/indoor-championships-nanjing-2020-postponed |website=World Athletics |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 World Athletics Half Marathon Championships]] was scheduled to be held on 29 March in [[Gdynia]], [[Poland]], but was postponed until October 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=World Half Marathon Championships in Gdynia to be postponed |url=https://www.worldathletics.org/competitions/world-athletics-half-marathon-championships/news/world-half-marathon-championships-gdynia-post |website=World Athletics |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first three events of the [[2020 Diamond League]], scheduled to be held in [[Qatar]] in April, followed by two events in [[China]] in May, were postponed until later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wanda Diamond League suspends early-season events |url=https://www.diamondleague.com/news/single-news/news/detail/News/wanda-diamond-league-suspends-early-season-events/ |website=Diamond League |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Boston Marathon]], originally scheduled for 20 April, was postponed until 14 September.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-marathon/2020/03/15/2020-boston-marathon-monday-september |title=Marathon Monday in September? Here's what we know so far about the 2020 Boston Marathon's new date |work=Boston.com |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 London Marathon]], scheduled to take place on 26 April, was postponed until 4 October.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/athletics/51878234 |title=Coronavirus: London Marathon postponed until October |newspaper=BBC Sport |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The 2020 [[Rome Marathon]] was cancelled.<ref name=\"cancellation.1\">{{cite web |author=user |url=https://www.runromethemarathon.com/en/2020/03/05/acea-run-rome-the-marathon-of-29-march-2020-cancelled/ |title=Acea Run Rome The Marathon of 29 March 2020 cancelled \u2013 ACEA RUN ROME THE MARATHON |publisher=Runromethemarathon.com |date= March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Two Oceans Marathon]], scheduled for 8\u201311 April has been cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twooceansmarathon.org.za/2020-two-oceans-marathon-cancelled-amid-covid-19-pandemic/|title=2020 Two Oceans Marathon cancelled amid COVID-19 Pandemic|website=Two Oceans Marathon|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Three Peaks Race]] originally scheduled for April 25 has been postponed to September 26.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.grough.co.uk/magazine/2020/03/12/coronavirus-claims-second-dales-event-as-three-peaks-race-put-back-to-September |title=Coronavirus claims second Dales event as Three Peaks Race put back to September |date=2020-03-12 |accessdate=2020-03-18 |publisher=Grough |first=Bob |last=Smith}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Grandma's Marathon]], scheduled for June 20, was canceled by the organizers more than 50 days before it was to begin. They announced on March 31 that the marathon, the half-marathon and the 5K would all be canceled. <ref>{{cite web |author1=Grandma's Marathon staff |title=COVID-19 Update/Cancellation |url=https://grandmasmarathon.com/covid19/ |website=grandmasmarathon.com |accessdate=31 March 2020 |location=Duluth, Minnesota |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Australian rules football==\nAt the conclusion of its first round of games, the [[2020 AFL season]] was suspended until May 31 at the earliest,<ref name=\"aussierules\">{{cite web|url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/389109/watch-from-4-30pm-aedt-afl-postpones-season|title=WATCH from 4.30pm AEDT: AFL postpones season|publisher=AFL.com.au|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> while the Finals series of the [[2020 AFL Women's season]] was cancelled after its semi-finals were played with no premiership awarded.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Badminton==\nAll scheduled [[Badminton World Federation]] tournaments were suspended until April 12 due to coronavirus concerns.<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Suspends International Badminton |url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/03/14/bwf-suspends-international-badminton/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=14 March 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> The affected tournaments are [[2020 Swiss Open (badminton)|Swiss Open]], [[2020 India Open|India Open]], [[2020 Orl\u00e9ans Masters|Orl\u00e9ans Masters]], [[2020 Malaysia Open|Malaysia Open]], and [[2020 Singapore Open|Singapore Open]]. Previously the body had suspended the [[2020 German Open (badminton)|German Open]]<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Media Statement on Yonex German Open 2020 |url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/02/26/bwf-media-statement-on-yonex-german-open-2020-2/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=2 March 2020 |date=26 February 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> and pushed the [[2020 Lingshui China Masters|Lingshui China Masters]] from February to May 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Statement on Postponement of Lingshui China Masters |url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/02/01/bwf-statement-on-postponement-of-lingshui-china-masters/ |publisher=Badminton World Federation |accessdate=2 February 2020 |date=1 February 2020 |work=bwfbadminton.com}}</ref> The [[2020 Thomas & Uber Cup]] had also been postponed to 15\u201323 August.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Baseball==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2021 World Baseball Classic \u2013 Qualification|qualifying round]] of the [[World Baseball Softball Confederation]]-sanctioned [[2021 World Baseball Classic]], scheduled in [[Tucson, Arizona]], United States in March 2020 was postponed on March 12, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harrigan |first1=Thomas |title=World Baseball Classic qualifier games postponed |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/world-baseball-classic-qualifier-games-postponed |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=MLB.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n\n====Japan====\nOn February 26, 2020, [[Nippon Professional Baseball]] announced that spring training would continue without fans in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japanese baseball to play remainder of preseason without spectators due to virus fears |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/02/26/baseball/japanese-baseball/japanese-baseball-play-remainder-preseason-without-spectators-due-virus-fears/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Japan Times |agency=Kyodo News |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, the league announced that the start of its [[2020 Nippon Professional Baseball season|2020 season]] would be postponed until April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's pro baseball league delays season start over coronavirus |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/6cba442bcfa8-breaking-news-japan-pro-baseball-to-delay-start-of-season-over-virus-source.html |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |agency=Kyodo News |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Coskrey |first1=Jason |title=BayStars, Tigers managers react to NPB's decision to push back start of season |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/?post_type=sports&p=2526679 |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Japan Times |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2020, the [[Japan High School Baseball Federation]] announced that the [[National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament]], scheduled to begin on March 19, would take place without fans in attendance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's Senbatsu spring HS baseball tourney to be held with no spectators due to virus |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200304/p2a/00m/0na/025000c |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Mainichi |date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> However, on March 11, the governing body of [[high school baseball in Japan]] declared that the tournament had been cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |title=Organizers cancel Spring Koshien due to COVID-19 crisis |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2020/03/11/baseball/cancel-spring-koshien-coronavirus/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=Japan Times |agency=Kyodo News |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Japan's Senbatsu spring HS baseball tournament canceled over coronavirus fears |url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20200311/p2a/00m/0sp/017000c |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=The Manichi |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The cancellation of the 2020 tournament marked the first time the contest had been cancelled since its establishment in 1924. The tournaments were not formally scheduled between 1942 and 1946, due to [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Koshien cancelation stuns players |url=https://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0006415873 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Japan News |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Spring high school baseball tourney cancelled over coronavirus |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2020/03/c9ea2971def3-breaking-news-national-invitational-hs-baseball-tournament-cancelled-due-to-virus.html |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |agency=Kyodo News |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====South Korea====\nOpening Day of the [[2020 KBO League season]] was originally scheduled for March 28, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baseball league announces 2020 regular season schedule |archiveurl=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20191216000870 |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=The Korea Herald |agency=Yonhap News Agency |archivedate=December 16, 2019 |date=December 16, 2019 |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20191216007100315}}</ref> The [[Korea Baseball Organization]] announced in March that all ten exhibition games would be cancelled, and the start of the regular season would be delayed until April.<ref>{{cite news |title=(LEAD) Pro baseball league postpones start of regular season over coronavirus |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200310005251315?input=tw |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |agency=Yonhap News Agency |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Latest: South Korean baseball season postponed |url=https://wtmj.com/national/2020/03/12/the-latest-south-korean-baseball-season-postponed/ |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=WTMJ-TV |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn March 12, 2020, [[Major League Baseball]] suspended all spring training activities. [[Opening Day]] of the [[2020 Major League Baseball season]], scheduled for March 26, was postponed, as was the start of the regular season for [[Minor League Baseball]], which was to begin on April 9.<ref>{{cite news |title=MLB suspends spring training, delays Opening Day at least two weeks |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/28892315/sources-mlb-expected-suspend-spring-training |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |website=[[ESPN.com]] |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/mlb-2020-season-delayed |title=Opening Day delayed at least 2 weeks; Spring Training games cancelled |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAlso on March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] announced the suspension of its baseball season and cancellation of the [[2020 College World Series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.omaha.com/sports/cws/college-baseball-stunned-after-ncaa-decision-to-cancel-college-world/article_ba4b22b5-7cbd-52a7-b0a0-edb0eba8f079.html|title=College baseball stunned after NCAA decision to cancel College World Series, end season in March|newspaper=Omaha World-Herald|last=Bland|first=Evan|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Basketball==\n\n===Africa===\nThe launch of the [[2020 BAL season|inaugural season]] of the [[Basketball Africa League]] set for March 2020 was delayed due to the coronavirus pandemic. No new date has been announced.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Solomon |first1=Salem |title=Basketball Africa League Delays Inaugural Season Because of Coronavirus |url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/basketball-africa-league-delays-inaugural-season-because |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |agency=Voice of America |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nThe [[2019\u201320 Chinese Basketball Association season]] was suspended on 1 February 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Prewitt|first=Alex|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2020/03/13/cba-coronavirus-nba-allerik-freeman|title=While the NBA Pauses, China Is Ready to Play Again. For Better or Worse|date=March 13, 2020|work=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February, [[FIBA]] ordered two [[2021 FIBA Asia Cup qualification|qualifying games for the 2021 FIBA Asia Cup]], [[Philippines men's national basketball team|Philippines]] vs [[Thailand national basketball team|Thailand]] in [[Quezon City]], and [[Japan national basketball team|Japan]] vs. [[China men's national basketball team|China]] in [[Chiba (city)|Chiba]] to be postponed to a later date. This brought the postponed games to three, after FIBA earlier ordered the China vs. [[Malaysia national basketball team|Malaysia]] game in [[Foshan]] to be postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/asiacup/2021/qualifiers/news/three-fiba-asia-cup-2021-qualifier-games-postponed|title=Three FIBA Asia Cup 2021 Qualifier games postponed|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Later that week, the [[Guam national basketball team|Guam]] vs. [[Hong Kong basketball team|Hong Kong]] game in [[Hag\u00e5t\u00f1a, Guam|Hag\u00e5t\u00f1a]] was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/asiacup/2021/qualifiers/news/fiba-asia-cup-2021-qualifier-between-guam-and-hong-kong-postponed|title=FIBA Asia Cup 2021 Qualifier game between Guam and Hong Kong postponed|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Korean Basketball League]] canceled its [[2019\u201320 KBL season|2019\u201320 season]] on 24 March, after playing its last game on 29 February. This comes as the [[Women's Korean Basketball League]] canceled its season a week before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200324000415|title=Men's basketball league cancels season due to coronavirus|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=2020-03-24|website=www.koreaherald.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March, FIBA announced the cancellation of the [[2019 FIBA Under-16 Asian Championship]] in [[Beirut]] and the 2019 FIBA Under-16 Asian Championship for Women in [[Canberra]]. It also postponed the [[Basketball at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's 3x3 qualification|3x3 Olympic qualification tournament]] in [[Bangalore]], and rescheduled the 2020 [[FIBA Asia 3x3 Cup]]s in [[Changsha]] and the 2020 FIBA 3x3 Under-17 Asian Cup in [[Cyberjaya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/news/changes-made-to-several-fiba-events-due-to-covid-19-virus|title=Changes made to several FIBA events due to COVID-19 virus|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n====ASEAN Basketball League====\nSeveral fixtures of the [[ASEAN Basketball League]] [[2019\u201320 ABL season|2019\u201320 season]] scheduled on February onwards were rescheduled due to the coronavirus pandemic. In early March 2020, four participating teams, [[Alab Pilipinas]], [[Hong Kong Eastern Basketball Team|Hong Kong Eastern]], [[Macau Black Bears]] and [[Formosa Dreamers]] has released statements urging the suspension of the whole season due to logistical issues posed by COVID-19-related travel measures in Southeast Asia, mainland China and Taiwan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alab Pilipinas, three other teams want ABL to suspend season due to COVID-19 |url=https://sports.mb.com.ph/2020/03/12/alab-pilipinas-three-other-teams-want-abl-to-suspend-season-due-to-covid-19/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, 2020, the league's 2019\u201320 season was postponed indefinitely.<ref name=\"pbateams\">{{cite news |last1=Dalupang |first1=Denison Rey |title=PBA: Teams can't hold practices, scrimmages |url=https://sports.inquirer.net/389302/pba-teams-cant-hold-practices-scrimmages |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Philippines====\nThe [[2020 PBA season|2020 season]] of the [[Philippine Basketball Association]] (PBA) and the [[PBA D-League]] was suspended indefinitely on March 10, 2020. The inaugural of the PBA's 3x3 tournament was also likewise delayed.<ref name=pba>{{cite news |title=PBA suspends games indefinitely due to COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/sports/basketball/729223/pba-suspends-games-indefinitely-due-to-covid-19/story/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The PBA management also imposed a two-week prohibition on team \"practices, scrimmages and other related activities\" which took effect on March 14, 2020.<ref name=\"pbateams\"/>\n\n=== Europe ===\n[[Jordi Bertomeu]], CEO of the [[Euroleague]], suspended the games from 14 March to 11 April. The Euroleague previously suspended the [[EuroCup Basketball|Eurocup]]. FIBA also suspended the [[Basketball Champions League]] and the [[FIBA Europe Cup]] starting on 14 March. [[Lietuvos krep\u0161inio lyga|Lithuania]], [[Swedish Basketball League|Sweden]], [[Swiss Basketball League|Switzerland]], [[Slovak Basketball League|Slovakia]] and [[Ukrainian Basketball SuperLeague|Ukraine]] canceled outright their respective first division leagues, naming the teams in the top of the standings as champions. Top flight divisions in [[Liga ACB|Spain]], [[LNB Pro A|France]], [[Basketball Bundesliga|Germany]], [[Lega Basket Serie A|Italy]], [[Israeli Basketball Premier League|Israel]], [[Pro Basketball League|Belgium]], [[Korisliiga|Finland]], [[HT Premijer liga|Croatia]], [[Greek Basket League|Greece]], [[Polish Basketball League|Poland]], [[Cyprus Basketball Division A|Cyprus]] and [[National Basketball League (Czech Republic)|Czech Republic]] suspended its games as of 14 March. The [[ABA League|Adriatic League]] and the [[VTB United League]] suspended its competitions until April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28898393/international-basketball-virtually-shut-coronavirus-concerns|title=International basketball virtually shut down|date=2020-03-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The government of Turkey suspended the [[Basketball Super League]] on 19 March, the last major European league to do so.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2020/03/19/turkey-basketball-soccer-suspended-coronavirus|title=Turkey Suspends Soccer, Basketball Seasons|last=West|first=Jenna|website=Sports Illustrated|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn March 11, 2020, the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) [[Suspension of the 2019\u201320 NBA season|suspended its season]] after [[Utah Jazz]] player [[Rudy Gobert]] tested positive for coronavirus prior to tip-off for a scheduled game against the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref name=\"nba-suspension-of-season\">{{cite web |title=NBA to suspend season following Wednesday's games |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2020/03/11/nba-suspend-season-following-wednesdays-games |website=NBA.com |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Commissioner [[Adam Silver]] stated the next day that this suspension \"will be most likely at least 30 days, and we don't know enough to be more specific than that\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, all [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] conferences in [[NCAA]] [[college basketball]] cancelled their respective tournaments in-progress. The [[Ivy League]] had already called off its tournament prior to the decision, while some conferences, as well as the NCAA for its [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men's]] and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women's]] tournaments, had previously announced that they would conduct their games behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/12/coronavirus-ncaa-conference-tournaments-cancellations.html |title=Big Ten, SEC, ACC scrap conference tournaments, adding to wave of coronavirus-related sports cancellations |last=Eudaily |first=Chris |date=March 12, 2020 |publisher=CNBC|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/pac-12-mens-basketball-tournament-canceled-over-coronavirus-pandemic |title=Pac-12 cancels all sports competitions 'until further notice' because of coronavirus |date=March 12, 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28891602/big-ten-sec-american-cancel-conference-tournaments |title=Conference tournaments shut down over virus |date=March 12, 2020 |publisher=ESPN|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The NCAA subsequently cancelled its tournaments outright.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/story/2020-03-12/march-madness-ncaa-tournament-canceled-coronavirus |title=No shining moments: NCAA basketball tournaments are canceled for the first time |date=March 13, 2020 |website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/coronavirus-updates-ncaa-cancels-championship-competition-for-all-winter-and-spring-sports/ |title=Coronavirus updates: NCAA cancels championship competition for all winter and spring sports |website=CBSSports.com|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Baloncesto Superior Nacional]] of Puerto Rico suspended its season on 14 March.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe [[National Basketball League of Canada]] suspended the remainder of the [[2019\u201320 NBL Canada season|2019-20 season]] on March 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nblcanada.ca/sports/mbkb/2019-20/releases/20200312nqi4na|title=NBLC Suspends Remainder of 2019-20 Season Until Further Notice|website=National Basketball League of Canada|language=en|date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Oceania ===\nIn Australia's [[National Basketball League (Australia)|National Basketball League]], the [[Sydney Kings]] announced 17 March that they would pull out of the [[2020 NBL Finals]] after three games, due to \"a critical mass of relevant and actual concerns related to player welfare and the club's social responsibility\". The NBL had been considering playing Game 4 of the series on 18 March instead of 20 March as originally scheduled to accelerate its completion.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/basketball/nbl/perth-wildcats-disappointed-with-sydney-kings-nbl-grand-final-decision/news-story/2426c7f70f33f5a06e963a4c971365c4|title=NBL Grand Final 2020: Perth Wildcats 'disappointed' with Sydney Kings' NBL Grand Final decision|date=2020-03-17|website=Fox Sports|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/basketball/nbl/breaking-nbl-season-called-off-midfinals-due-to-coronavirus-crisis/news-story/7f707f71310056816e01d8d99e7748cf|title=NBL Grand Final 2020: NBL season called off mid-finals due to coronavirus crisis, Sydney Kings vs Perth Wildcats|date=2020-03-17|website=Fox Sports|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> The decision effectively [[Forfeit (sport)|forfeited]] the series to the [[Perth Wildcats]]\u2014who were leading the best-of-five series 2-1 after Game 3, and were officially announced as NBL champions on 18 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thewest.com.au/sport/perth-wildcats/nbl-grand-final-title-win-the-last-piece-of-the-puzzle-for-stoked-perth-wildcats-ng-b881494184z|title=Title win the last piece of the puzzle for stoked Cats|date=2020-03-19|website=The West Australian|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The series was played behind closed doors beginning with Game 2, and the NBL stated that it would be suspended immediately if any player was diagnosed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/basketball/nbl-grand-final-series-to-be-completed-behind-closed-doors-20200313-p549xx.html|title=NBL grand final series to be completed behind closed doors|last=Ward|first=Roy|date=2020-03-13|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Biathlon ==\nThe [[2019\u201320 Biathlon World Cup]] ended a week and a day earlier than previously scheduled. The World Cup final in Norway was cancelled as was the last day of the penultimate World Cup in Finland.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.biathlonworld.com/news/detail/ibu-statement-on-world-cup-in-oslo |title=Update: IBU Statement on World Cup in Oslo, Kontiolahti and Junior OECH |date=13 March 2020 |website=Biathlon World |access-date=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bodybuilding==\nSeveral competitive events in international [[Bodybuilding|competitive bodybuilding]] on the amateur and [[Professional bodybuilding|professional]] levels have seen limitations, postponements, or even cancellations due to concerns about the spread of COVID-19.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nDue to these concerns the 2020 [[Arnold Sports Festival]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]] cancelled its Fitness Expo and, under orders from the state government, held the bodybuilding and physique competitions, including the Arnold Classic, without spectators with exceptions for parents and guardians of minors participating in the competitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arnoldsportsfestival.com/visitor-info/media/update-March-3/ |title=UPDATED EVENTS SCHEDULE |work=Arnold Sports Festival |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Similar Arnold Sports Festivals planned to be held in Africa, Australia, and South America were postponed for later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arnoldsportsfestival.com/ |title= ARNOLD SPORTS FESTIVALS IN AUSTRALIA, SOUTH AMERICA & AFRICA HAVE BEEN POSTPONED. NEW DATES TBD |work=Arnolds Sports Festival |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2020, Jim Manion, president of the [[IFBB Professional League]] and the [[National Physique Committee]] announced that competitions planned through to May 10, 2020 in the United States would be postponed for later in the year or cancelled until the 2021 season.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ifbbpro.com/npc-news/npc-ifbb-professional-league-president-jim-manion-addresses-coronavirus-concerns-for-contests-in-the-united-states/ |title= NPC & IFBB Professional League President Jim Manion Addresses Coronavirus Concerns For Contests In The United States |work=IFBB Professional League \u2013 NPC News Online |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Bowls==\nThe [[2020 World Outdoor Bowls Championship]] scheduled to be held on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] from 23 May to 7 June 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bowls.com.au/events-page/international-events/world-bowls-championships/|title=2020 World Bowls Championship|publisher=Bowls Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bowlsmalaysia.com/world-events-calendar/|title=WORLD EVENTS CALENDAR|publisher=Bowls Malaysia}}</ref> has been postponed until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bowls.com.au/2020-world-bowls-championships-to-be-postponed-indefinitely/|title=2020 World Bowls Championships to be postponed indefinitely|date=2020-03-17|website=Bowls Australia|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==Castells==\n\nIn response to the shutdown of extracurricular activities for children in [[Catalonia]], the Coordinadora de Colles Castelleres de Catalunya (CCCC), the governing body for [[castell]]s (Catalan human towers), issued a statement on March 10, 2020, recommending the suspension of all castells practices and performances.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mu\u00f1oz |first1=Silvia |title=Primers assajos i diades castelleres suspeses en prevenci\u00f3 pel coronavirus |url=https://www.elmoncasteller.cat/primers-assajos-i-diades-castelleres-suspeses-en-prevencio-pel-coronavirus/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=M\u00f3n Casteller |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> Subsequently, the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain|lockdown imposed throughout Spain]] shut down all castells activities throughout Catalonia as of March 15.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prats |first1=David |title=Segon cap de setmana de confinament casteller |url=http://revistacastells.cat/2020/03/segon-cap-de-setmana-de-confinament-casteller/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Revista Castells |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> As of March 25, 2020, there was no word about the potential impact of the pandemic on the biennial [[:ca:XXVIII Concurs de castells de Tarragona|Tarragona Castells Contest]], scheduled for October 3 and 4, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prats |first1=David |title=Madrid, una ciutat en hores baixes |url=http://revistacastells.cat/2020/03/madrid-una-ciutat-en-hores-baixes/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Revista Castells |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Chess ==\nThe [[44th Chess Olympiad]] scheduled to take place in [[Moscow]], [[Russia]] from 5\u201317 August 2020 was postponed and rescheduled for the summer of 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fide.com/news/460 |title=Statement by the FIDE Council regarding the Chess Olympiad |date=24 March 2020 |website=fide.com |publisher=FIDE |access-date=24 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"postponed\">{{cite web |url=https://www.chess.com/news/view/fide-postpones-chess-olympiad-to-2021 |title=FIDE Postpones Chess Olympiad To 2021 |author=Peter Doggers |date=24 March 2020 |publisher=[[Chess.com]] |access-date=24 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nThe FIDE [[Candidates Tournament 2020]], held in [[Yekaterinburg]], [[Russia]], was suspended at the mid-point of the tournament on 26 March. FIDE decided to postpone the second half of the tournament after Russia announced it would be interrupting air traffic with other countries starting on 27 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.chessbase.com/post/breaking-news-fide-stops-the-candidates-tournament |title=Breaking News: FIDE stops the Candidates Tournament! |date=2020-03-26 |website=Chess News |language=en |access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Cricket==\nThe coronavirus pandemic impacted on several international cricket fixtures and tournaments. The [[2020 ACA Africa T20 Cup Finals]] was scheduled to take place in Kenya in March 2020, before it was postponed in line with the Kenyan government's 30-day ban on international gatherings.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africacricket.com/read_more_news.php?id=145 |title=ACA T20 Africa Cup Kenya 2020 postponed |work=Africa Cricket Association |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.busybuddiesng.com/ncf-closes-lagos-camp-as-coronavirus-forces-postponement-of-africa-cricket-championship/ |title=NCF closes Lagos camp as coronavirus forces postponement of Africa Cricket Championship |work=Busy Buddies |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref> A women's [[2020 Thailand Women's Quadrangular Series|quadrangular series]] was scheduled to take place in Thailand in April 2020,<ref name=\"CV1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cricketireland.ie/news/article/quadrangular-tournament-ahead-for-ireland-women |title=Quadrangular tournament ahead for Ireland Women |work=Cricket Ireland |accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref> but was cancelled a month before it was due to start.<ref name=\"CV2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kncb.nl/en/news/womens-quadrangular-series-in-thailand-called-off/ |title=Women's Quadrangular Series in Thailand called off |work=Royal Dutch Cricket Association |accessdate=March 2, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Malaysia Cricket World Cup Challenge League A]], scheduled to take place in March 2020, was postponed,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/1636508 |title=Men's Cricket World Cup Challenge League A postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref> along with two T20I matches [[Mujib 100 T20 Cup Bangladesh 2020|between a World XI and Asia XI side]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28882792/world-xi-v-asia-xi-matches-postponed-amid-coronavirus-fears |title=World XI v Asia XI matches postponed amid coronavirus fears |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2020, English teams [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] and [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] both cancelled their pre-season warm-up tours to the United Arab Emirates.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/51835256 |title=Worcestershire & Surrey cancel pre-season trips to United Arab Emirates over coronavirus fear |newspaper=BBC Sport |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The following day, Australia Women's [[Australia women's cricket team in South Africa in 2019\u201320|tour to South Africa]] in March 2020 became the first major international series not to go ahead as planned due to coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1219220.html |title=Australia Women won't tour South Africa as scheduled because of coronavirus |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, 2020, the [[2020 United States Tri-Nation Series]] was postponed due to the pandemic and travel restrictions to the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/1645150 |title=Series six of Men's CWC League 2 in USA postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usacricket.org/media-release/mens-cricket-world-cup-league-2-in-usa-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |title=Men's Cricket World Cup League 2 in USA Postponed due to Coronavirus outbreak |work=USA Cricket |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 12, the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]] announced that all remaining matches of the [[Pakistan Super League]]'s ongoing [[2020 Pakistan Super League|fifth season]] being played in [[Karachi]] (where the majority of cases in Pakistan had been concentrated) would be closed to spectators.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/2174849/1-coronavirus-fears-psl-matches-karachi-played-empty-stadium/ |title=Covid-19: PSL matches in Karachi to be played in empty stadium |work=The Express Tribune |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/psl-matches-in-karachi-to-be-held-closed-door-without-crowd-coronavirus-outbreak-pandemic-1654922-2020-03-12 |title=Coronavirus pandemic: Pakistan Super League matches in Karachi to be played in front of empty stands |work=India Today |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Everest Premier League]] was also postponed on 12 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Everest Premier League 2020 postponed due to coronavirus threat |url=https://www.emergingcricket.com/events/everest-premier-league/everest-premier-league-2020-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-threat/ |website=Emerging Cricket |date=March 5, 2020 |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI) announced that the start of [[2020 Indian Premier League]] will be postponed from March 29 to April 15.<ref>{{cite news |title=It's official: IPL 2020 postponed to April 15 due to coronavirus |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/top-stories/its-official-ipl-2020-postponed-to-mid-april-due-to-coronavirus/articleshow/74609776.cms |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Times of India}}</ref> Later that day, it cancelled the [[South African cricket team in India in 2019\u201320|ODI matches between India and South Africa on March 15 and 18]], which were originally announced to be played without spectators.<ref>{{cite news |title=India-South Africa series called off due to COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.thehindu.com/sport/cricket/coronavirus-india-south-africa-series-called-off-due-to-covid-19-threat/article31061061.ece |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=The Hindu}}</ref> On the same day, the two-match Test series between [[English cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2019\u201320|Sri Lanka and England]], scheduled to be played in March 2020, was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28896266/england-tour-sri-lanka-cancelled-amid-covid-19-spread |title=England tour of Sri Lanka cancelled amid COVID-19 spread |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The remaining seven matches of the [[2020 Road Safety World Series]] were rescheduled to a later date.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldseriest20.com/news/in-the-interest-of-public-safety-security-and-support-to-the-government-road-safety-world-series-rescheduled |title=In the interest of public safety & security and support to the Government, Road Safety World Series rescheduled, new dates to be announced later |date=March 13, 2020 |website=Road Safety World Series |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> It was earlier decided that the remaining seven matches of the tournament would be played behind the closed doors in [[DY Patil Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldseriest20.com/news/unacademy-road-safety-world-series-to-be-played-behind-closed-doors-in-dy-patil-stadium |title=Unacademy Road Safety World Series to be played behind closed doors in DY Patil Stadium |date=March 12, 2020 |website=Road Safety World Series |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2020, the [[New Zealand cricket team in Australia in 2019\u201320|remaining two One Day International (ODI) matches]] of the [[Chappell-Hadlee Trophy]] along with the three-match [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) series [[Australian cricket team in New Zealand in 2019\u201320|between Australia and New Zealand]] were cancelled due to new border restrictions imposed by the New Zealand government.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://es.pn/2U7Ngt5 |title=Australia v NZ cancelled amid travel restrictions |work=ESPNcricinfo |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |date=14 March 2020 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> The first ODI match of the series had been played on 13 March behind closed doors in Sydney.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1645137 |title=COVID-19 outbreak: Chappell-Hadlee series to be held behind closed doors |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> The following day, [[Cricket Australia]] confirmed that the final round of matches in the [[2019\u201320 Sheffield Shield season]] had been cancelled, with [[New South Wales cricket team|New South Wales]] being named as the winners of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28913589/new-south-wales-named-sheffield-shield-winners-final-cancelled |title=New South Wales named Sheffield Shield winners as final cancelled |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> [[New Zealand Cricket]] cancelled the final two rounds of matches in the [[2019\u201320 Plunket Shield season]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28909068/plunket-shield-cancelled-due-coronavirus-measures,-wellington-named-champions |title=Plunket Shield cancelled due to coronavirus measures, Wellington named champions |work=ESPN Cricinfo |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref> with [[Wellington cricket team|Wellington]] being named the winners of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/coronavirus/120318144/coronavirus-plunket-shield-cancelled-wellington-firebirds-declared-champions |title=Coronavirus: Plunket Shield cancelled, Wellington Firebirds declared champions |work=Stuff |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2020, the remaining play-offs in the [[2020 Pakistan Super League]] were postponed due to a huge spike in the number of coronavirus cases around the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geosuper.tv/latest/4433-pcb-decides-to-call-off-psl-2020-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-report|title=PCB 'postpones' PSL 2020 amid coronavirus outbreak|website=www.geosuper.tv}}</ref> The [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]] tour of Pakistan for a single [[One Day International|ODI]] and a [[Test cricket|Test]] match was also postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1645763|title=Bangladesh's Karachi leg of Pakistan tour postponed|work=[[International Cricket Council]]|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Curling==\nThe [[2019\u201320 curling season|curling season]] typically ends in May but was cut short by the pandemic, effectively ending in early March. The [[World Curling Federation]] cancelled the last five championships scheduled for the 2019\u201320 curling season, most importantly the [[2020 World Women's Curling Championship]], [[2020 World Men's Curling Championship]], and [[2020 World Mixed Doubles Curling Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2019-2020 season ends with event cancellations |url=https://worldcurling.org/2020/03/2019-2020-season-ends/ |website=World Curling Federation |accessdate=24 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cycling==\n===Road cycling===\nThe [[2020 UAE Tour]] was scheduled to run until February 29, but was abandoned following stage five after two support staff tested positive for coronavirus. Of the following nineteen [[2020 UCI World Tour]] races scheduled to take place up to 31 May, only [[2020 Omloop Het Nieuwsblad|Omloop Het Nieuwsblad]] and [[2020 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]], which also had the final day of racing removed, took place at the intended time, some with the stated hope of taking place at a later date.  The postponed races in this block include the [[2020 Giro d'Italia]] and four of the five annual [[Cycling monument|monuments]], and many lower category races were also cancelled or postponed. Also races of the [[2020 UCI Women's World Tour]] were cancelled or postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uci.org/news/2020/novel-coronavirus-important-information|title=Novel coronavirus: important information|website=UCI|language=en|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Farrand|first=Stephen|title=RCS Sport cancels Strade Bianche in light of coronavirus measures|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/rcs-sport-cancels-strade-bianche-in-light-of-coronavirus-measures/|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=5 March 2020|date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Frattini|first=Kirsten|title=Coronavirus: Women's WorldTour Trofeo Alfredo Binda postponed until June 2|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/coronavirus-womens-worldtour-trofeo-alfredo-binda-postponed-until-june-2/|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=5 March 2020|date=5 March 2020|quote=They are still awaiting the authorisation of the new date from the UCI.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/coronavirus-womens-worldtour-ronde-van-drenthe-cancelled/|title=Coronavirus: Women's WorldTour Ronde van Drenthe cancelled|first=Lukas|last=Kn\u00f6fler|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=12 March 2020|date=12 March 2020|quote=Sadly, this means that our races will not go ahead [...] We hope to be back next year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Geen koers tot en met drie april, Ronde van Vlaanderen maakt nog een waterkansje maar houdt rekening met annulering|language=Dutch|trans-title=No race until April 3, Tour of Flanders still has a remote chance but takes cancellation into account|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20200312_04887671|work=[[Het Nieuwsblad]]|publisher=[[Mediahuis]]|accessdate=12 March 2020|date=12 March 2020|quote=We besluiten bij deze om onze wedstrijd Driedaagse Brugge De Panne ook uit te stellen naar een later tijdstip. We hopen dat we een plaatsje krijgen op de kalender in het najaar. [We hereby decide to postpone our match Three Days Bruges De Panne to a later date. We hope that we will have a place on the calendar in the autumn].}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://sporza.be/nl/2020/03/12/alle-sportactiviteiten-in-belgie-tot-en-met-3-april-worden-gean~1584050395120/|title=Alle sportactiviteiten in Belgi\u00eb tot en met 3 april worden geannuleerd|language=Dutch|trans-title=All sports activities in Belgium until April 3 will be canceled|work=[[Sporza]]|publisher=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie]]|date=12 March 2020|accessdate=12 March 2020|quote=In het wielrennen worden Nokere Koerse (18 maart), de Bredene Koksijde Classic (20 maart), de Driedaagse Brugge-De Panne (25 maart), de E3 Harelbeke (27 maart), Gent-Wevelgem (29 maart) en Dwars door Vlaanderen (1 april) geschrapt. [In cycling Nokere Koerse (March 18), the Bredene Koksijde Classic (March 20), the Driedaagse Brugge-De Panne (March 25), the E3 Harelbeke (March 27), Ghent-Wevelgem (March 29) and Dwars door Vlaanderen (April 1) are scrapped.]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://womenstour.co.uk/womens-tour-2020-postponed|title=Women's Tour 2020 postponed|first=Nick|last=Bull|work=[[The Women's Tour]]|publisher=SweetSpot Group|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/paris-roubaix-fleche-wallonne-and-liege-bastogne-liege-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/|title=Paris-Roubaix, Fl\u00e8che Wallonne and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge postponed due to coronavirus pandemic|first=Barry|last=Ryan|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|quote=As part of the fight against the spread of Coronavirus (COVID19), Amaury Sport Organisation, with the agreement of the Union Cycliste Internationale (UCI), has decided to not organise Paris-Roubaix (12th April), the Fl\u00e8che Wallonne and the Fl\u00e8che Wallonne Women (22nd April) and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge and Li\u00e8ge-Bastogne-Li\u00e8ge Women (26th April) races on their scheduled dates.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cyclingnews.com/news/tour-of-flanders-cancelled-over-coronavirus-concerns/|title=Tour of Flanders cancelled over coronavirus concerns|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020|quote=Organisers of the Tour of Flanders made the long-anticipated decision to cancel their April 5 race, saying they will work with the UCI and representatives of the teams and riders to look at the potential for scheduling a new date later this year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.velonews.com/2020/03/news/rolling-report-impact-of-coronavirus-on-pro-racing_505843|title=Rolling report: Impact of coronavirus on pro racing|work=[[VeloNews]]|publisher=Pocket Outdoor Media, LLC|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|quote=March 18, 5:15 a.m. (MT): Amstel Gold race postponed}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, [[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]] requested to suspend all UCI-sanctioned events in affected territories until April 3, and the qualification for the Tokyo 2020 Olympic Games and Paralympic Games to stop retroactively as of March 3.<ref name=\"uci20200315\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uci.org/inside-uci/press-releases/the-uci-takes-strong-measures-faced-with-the-development-of-the-coronavirus |title=The UCI takes strong measures faced with the development of the coronavirus |date=15 March 2020 |publisher=Union Cycliste Internationale |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> On March 18, the suspension of events were extended at least until the end of April.<ref name=\"uci20200318\">{{cite web |url=\nhttps://www.uci.org/inside-uci/press-releases/the-uci-and-its-partners-unite-to-face-the-consequences-of-the-coronavirus-for-road-cycling |title=The UCI and its partners unite to face the consequences of the coronavirus for road cycling |date=18 March 2020 |publisher=Union Cycliste Internationale |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===BMX===\nRace days of the 2020 [[UCI BMX Supercross World Cup]] were cancelled including 2 to 3 May in Papendal, the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myprivacy.dpgmedia.net/?siteKey=Oom2kBLTny5zJUeO&callbackUrl=https%3a%2f%2fwww.gelderlander.nl%2fprivacy-gate%2faccept%3fredirectUri%3d%252fsport-arnhem%252fwereldbeker-bmx-papendal-ook-van-de-agenda-geld-terug-voor-deelnemers-en-fans%257ea71539c9%252f%253freferrer%253dhttps%253a%252f%252fwww.google.nl%252f|title=Privacy settings|website=myprivacy.dpgmedia.net|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[UCI BMX World Championships]], scheduled to take place in [[Houston]], United States on 26\u201331 May, are postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nos.nl/l/2328063|title=Ook wereldkampioenschappen BMX uitgesteld wegens coronavirus|website=nos.nl|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nThe annual [[Cape Epic]] endurance race scheduled from 15 to 22 March was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cape-epic.com/riders/the-2020-race/official-statement-2020-absa-cape-epic-cancellation|title=The Official Statement regarding the cancellation of the 2020 Absa Cape Epic {{!}} Absa Cape Epic|website=cape-epic.com|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Darts==\nThe [[Professional Darts Corporation]]'s [[PDC European Tour|European Tour]] was impacted by the coronavirus; with the [[2020 European Darts Grand Prix]], the [[2020 European Darts Open]] and the [[2020 German Darts Grand Prix]] all being postponed following restrictions on gatherings implemented by federal governments in [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] and [[Bavaria]], respectively. The two [[2020 Premier League Darts]] rounds to be held in [[Rotterdam]] at the end of March were postponed to September following restrictions on gatherings in the Netherlands; and the round to be held in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] a week earlier was subsequently postponed to October; meaning the Newcastle date would serve as the Premier League's play-off round. The next five rounds, in [[Belfast]], [[Sheffield]], [[Manchester]], [[Berlin]] and [[Birmingham]] were also postponed to later dates. All ProTour events from March 16 to the end of April were postponed. The [[2020 Nordic Darts Masters]] was postponed from June to October. The PDC's North American affiliate, the Championship Darts Corporation, cancelled the first weekend of its season in [[Ontario]], and the New Zealand affiliate DartPlayers tour was ended for 2019/20 following the cancellation of events in [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus \u2013 Latest re PDC events |url=https://www.pdc.tv/Coronavirus |publisher=[[Professional Darts Corporation]] |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Esports==\n=== Leagues and tournaments ===\nImpact of the pandemic on [[esports]] have primarily affected events and leagues that host competitions in-person at venues with spectators, which have led to cancellations, postponements, and competitions being held behind closed doors\u2014either in the traditional sense, or with competition being conducted entirely [[Multiplayer video game|over the internet]] (although [[Latency (engineering)|latency]] between players can be a factor).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21167652/coronavirus-esports-impact-league-of-legends-pubg-csgo-iem-katowice|title=The coronavirus' human impact on esports|last=Garst|first=Aron|date=2020-03-06|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video-games/esports/2020/03/17/esports-streamers-coronavirus-sports-canceled/|title=While the sports world falls silent, esports and streamers fill the void|last=Smith|first=Noah|date=2020-03-17|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Overwatch League]] cancelled homestand events (matches held on-location at home venues akin to traditional sports leagues, as opposed to a centralized studio) in Asia at the onset of the pandemic, and subsequently cancelled all homestands through to April following its spread in North America in mid-March. The league planned a shift to online play, and competition of the [[2020 Overwatch League season|2020 season]] to resume March 21. The mid-season tournament was also removed from the schedule, and its all-star festivities were moved to the off-season due to not all players having played an equal number of games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28885048/coronavirus-leads-overwatch-league-suspend-play-march-april|title=Coronavirus leads OWL to cancel events for March, April|date=2020-03-11|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\"/> Due to [[stay-at-home orders]] imposed by the state of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in California|California]] (where [[Blizzard Entertainment|Blizzard]]'s headquarters and several other teams are located), the resumption of play was postponed (although exhibition matches showcasing the game's newly-unveiled character Echo were still held). Play resumed on March 28, with teams realigned into three regional conferences. Due to various factors, including several teams suspending their operations (including the [[New York Excelsior]], in compliance with a [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|local]] stay-at-home order, and the [[London Spitfire]] and [[Vancouver Titans]] re-locating their staff to South Korea), six of the 16 matches scheduled for the weekend were dropped from the schedule.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28928919/overwatch-league-postpones-first-weekend-online-matches|title=Overwatch League postpones first weekend of online matches|date=2020-03-20|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video-games/esports/2020/03/27/overwatch-league-schedule-coronavirus-online/|title=Overwatch League teams face a reset after pandemic spoils its grand plans|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=Launcher (Washington Post)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/multiple-overwatch-league-matches-canceled-on-march-28-and-29|title=Multiple Overwatch League matches canceled on March 28 and 29|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=Dot eSports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n[[Riot Games]] announced that the [[League of Legends Championship Series]] would temporarily suspend its season and switch to online play. In addition, the Spring Finals event in Frisco, Texas was called off and moved back to Riot's Los Angeles studio. [[Electronic Arts]] has suspended all competitive gaming that cannot be produced remotely.<ref name=\"espn-cancelled-esports\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28852881/how-coronavirus-affecting-esports-gaming-events|title=How coronavirus is affecting esports and gaming events|last=|first=|date=2020-03-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/3/14/21179779/league-of-legends-lcs-spring-finals-canceled-moved-ea-sports-fifa-global-series-apex-legends|title=League of Legends, EA suspend all esports due to coronavirus|last=Good|first=Owen S.|date=2020-03-14|website=Polygon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n=== Crossover with traditional sports ===\nSportcal suggested that the esports industry had an opportunity to attract mainstream sports fans as a \"viable alternative\" to traditional sporting events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://advanced-television.com/2020/03/18/analyst-coronavirus-a-significant-opportunity-for-esports/|title=Analyst: \"Coronavirus a significant opportunity for eSports\"|last=|first=|date=|website=advanced-television.com|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>  Roundhill Investments CEO Will Hershey predicted that games that are straightforward for casual viewers to understand (such as [[sports game]]s) could see particular interest among this new audience.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWith the suspension of nearly all sporting events, some professional athletes began to increase their involvement in video game streaming as a means to engage with fans.<ref name=\":2\" /> Some teams have taken advantage of sports games in a similar manner, such as the [[Phoenix Suns]] holding ''[[NBA 2K20]]'' streams with guest players, between the teams the Suns were scheduled to play that night if the season had continued.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28900417/luka-doncic-50-leads-mavs-suns-twitch|title=Luka's 50 lead Mavericks past Suns -- on Twitch|date=2020-03-14|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/28964373/bridges-leads-suns-victory-first-nba-2k-game-broadcast-radio|title=Bridges leads Suns to victory in first NBA 2K game broadcast on radio|date=2020-03-28|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> This culminated with a game actually being commentated by the team's radio broadcasters on team flagship [[KMVP-FM]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nEsports organisations have also invited professional athletes to compete in specific competitions (often alongside, or in competition with professional players); [[FaZe Clan]] organized a charity ''[[Call of Duty: Warzone]]'' pro-am entitled \"Fight 2 Fund\" in support of coronavirus-related charities, where professional players were partnered with celebrity participants (such as [[Ben Simmons]], [[Chad Johnson]], and [[JuJu Smith-Schuster]]),<ref name=\":2\" /> and several [[sim racing]] competitions similarly invited professional race drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/cars/2020/03/esports-fills-the-gap-as-coronavirus-cancels-in-person-sporting-events/|title=F1 drivers and other pros switch to esports in the age of the coronavirus|last=Gitlin|first=Jonathan M.|date=2020-03-16|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/22/21184192/sim-racing-coronavirus-f1-nascar-iracing-veloce-esports-max-verstappen-lando-norris|title=Pro drivers are competing with gamers after F1 and NASCAR canceled races|last=O'Kane|first=Sean|date=2020-03-22|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> In turn, both the [[IndyCar Series]] and [[NASCAR]] announced partnerships with sim racing platform [[iRacing]] to hold online invitational events featuring series regulars, with the latter employing television broadcasts by NASCAR television partner [[Fox NASCAR|Fox Sports]] (styled after and still featuring personalities associated with their traditional broadcasts, such as lead commentator [[Mike Joy]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nascar/2020/03/22/nascar-iracing-pro-invitational-series-fox-sports-1-high-marks/2894874001/|title=FS1 broadcast of NASCAR iRacing comes extremely close to the real thing|last=Gardner|first=Steve|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"espn.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/racing/nascar/story/_/id/28919500/with-nascar-season-postponed-drivers-compete-esports-series|title=NASCAR greats set to compete in esports series|date=2020-03-18|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"espn.com\" />\n\n==Field hockey==\nMany field hockey leagues in Europe have been suspended, including in Spain,<ref>{{cite web |title=Comunicado Oficial RFEH |url=https://www.rfeh.es/comunicado-oficial-rfeh-7/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=es}}</ref> England,<ref>{{cite web |title=England Hockey suspends national hockey activity |url=https://www.englandhockey.co.uk/news.asp?itemid=49019&itemTitle=England+Hockey+suspends+national+hockey+activity&section=22 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> Germany,<ref>{{cite web |title=Feldhockey-Bundesligen: Spielverkehr bis Ende April ausgesetzt |url=https://web.hockey.de/news/lgtz22.html |accessdate=20 March 2020 |language=de}}</ref> and the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web |title=Geen competitie en hockeyactiviteiten tot 1 april |url=https://www.knhb.nl/nieuws/geen-competitie-en-hockeyactiviteiten-tot-1-april |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 Euro Hockey League]] Final 8 and [[2020 Euro Hockey League Women]] seasons were suspended on 12 March.<ref name=\"EHL\">{{cite web |title=EHL Final8 Put on Hold |url=https://ehlhockey.tv/2020/03/12/ehl-final8-put-on-hold/ |website=ehlhockey.tv |publisher=[[Euro Hockey League]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Men's EuroHockey Club Trophy I]], [[2020 Men's EuroHockey Club Trophy II]], [[2020 Boys' EuroHockey Youth Championships]] and [[2020 Girls' EuroHockey Youth Championships]] were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=EHF cancels all EuroHockey Club Trophy and Challenge events, 2020 |url=https://eurohockey.org/2020/03/24/ehf-cancels-all-eurohockey-club-trophy-and-challenge-events-2020/ |website=eurohockey.org |publisher=[[European Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=EuroHockey U18 Championships boys and girls 2020 are cancelled |url=https://eurohockey.org/2020/03/31/eurohockey-u18-championships-boys-and-girls-2020-are-cancelled/ |website=eurohockey.org |publisher=[[European Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Asia, the [[2020 Men's Hockey Junior Asia Cup]], [[2020 Women's Asian Champions Trophy]], and [[2020 Women's Hockey Junior Asia Cup]] were postponed.<ref name=\"AHF2020\">{{cite web |title=Announcement: Postponement of the Bangabandhu Al-Arafah Islami Bank Junior Asia Cup Dhaka 2020 & the Women's Asian Champions Trophy Donghae 2020 |url=http://www.asiahockey.org/news/announcement-postponement-of-the-bangabandhu-al-arafah-islami-bank-junior-asia-cup-dhaka-2020-the-womens-asian-champions-trophy-donghae-2020/ |website=asiahockey.org |publisher=[[Asian Hockey Federation]] |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Junior Asia Cup Gifu Kakamigahara 2020 \u2013 Formal Announcement of Postponement |url=http://www.asiahockey.org/news/womens-junior-asia-cup-gifu-kakamigahara-2020-formal-announcement-of-postponement/ |website=asiahockey.org}}</ref> The [[2020 Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] has been postponed to 24 September.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Azlan Shah Cup Hockey Tournament Postponed |url=https://sports.ndtv.com/hockey/coronavirus-azlan-shah-cup-hockey-tournament-postponed-2188516 |website=ndtv.com |publisher=[[NDTV]]}}</ref>\n\n==Futsal==\nThe [[2020 AFC Futsal Championship]] in [[Ashgabat]] had been postponed following consultation with all relevant stakeholders. On 9 March 2020, FIFA and AFC announced that the tournament were postponed to 5\u201316 August 2020.\n\n==Golf==\nMany elite golf tournaments, both professional and amateur, have either been postponed or cancelled in response to the pandemic, including the [[Men's major golf championships|major championships]]. On March 13, it was announced that the [[2020 Masters Tournament|Masters Tournament]] (scheduled for April 9\u201312) had been postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Masters Tournament Postponed |url=https://www.masters.com/en_US/news/articles/2020-03-13/2020_masters_tournament_postponed.html |publisher=Masters.com |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=Augusta National announces Masters will be postponed |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28897249/augusta-national-announces-masters-postponed-played |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 PGA Championship]] (scheduled for May 11\u201317) was postponed the following week.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/sports/golf/pga-championship-postponed.html|title=P.G.A. Championship Is Postponed|newspaper=The New York Times|last=Pennington|first=Bill|date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> It is also widely expected that the [[2020 U.S. Open (golf)|2020 U.S. Open]] (scheduled for June 18\u201321) will also be postponed, but there has been no official announcement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/26/us-open-wont-be-played-in-june-but-will-stay-at-winged-foot/|title=US Open won't be played in June, but will stay at Winged Foot|newspaper=New York Post|last=Cannizzaro|first=Mark|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The [[R&A]] continue to plan for the [[2020 Open Championship]] to proceed as scheduled, but are investigating options should that not be possible.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theopen.com/latest/2020/03/covid19statement |title=Statement from the R&A on the COVID-19 pandemic |website=TheOpen.com |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> The ladies majors have been similarly affected, with the [[LPGA Tour]] postponing the [[ANA Inspiration]] until September.<ref name=lpga/>\n\nOn March 12, 2020, midway through the first round of the [[2020 Players Championship]], the [[PGA Tour]] announced that the remainder of the tournament and the next three events, the [[Valspar Championship]], [[WGC Match Play]], and the [[Valero Texas Open]], would continue without fan attendance. Subsequently, after completion of the days play, the tour decided to cancel the remainder of tournament and the three following events.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=Players Championship, other events won't have fans in attendance |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28890609/players-starts-autograph-ban-place |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Harig |first1=Bob |title=PGA Tour cancels Players Championship after first round |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28894497/pga-tour-cancels-players-championship-first-round |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 17, the tour announced the cancellation of all scheduled tournaments through May 10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pgatour.com/company/2020/03/17/pga-tour-news-tournament-cancellations-rbc-heritage-zurich-classic-new-orleans-wells-fargo-championship-att-byron-nelson-pga-championship.html |title=PGA Tour statement regarding additional tournament cancellations |publisher=PGA Tour |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> The [[European Tour]] have also cancelled or postponed many tournaments, mostly those scheduled from mid-March through to the end of May,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/news/articles/detail/update-on-european-tour-events/ |title=Update on European Tour events |website=European Tour |date=March 27, 2020 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> including the [[Irish Open (golf)|Irish Open]], a [[Rolex Series]] event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/golf/52092416 |title=Irish Open: Mount Juliet European Tour event postponed because of coronavirus |website=BBC Sport |date=March 30, 2020 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther leading professional tours have announced similar measures, as have the bodies responsible for organising leading amateur events. The LPGA Tour have postponed four tournaments including the ANA Inspiration,<ref name=lpga>{{cite news |title=LPGA to reschedule 3 events, including first major, the ANA Inspiration |url=https://www.espn.com/golf/story/_/id/28893923/lpga-reschedule-3-events-including-first-major-ana-inspiration |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> and the [[Japan LPGA Tour]] cancelled five tournaments scheduled form March into April.<ref name=sched>{{cite web |url=https://www.lpga.or.jp/tournament/jlpgatour/2020 |title=2020\u5e74\u5ea6 JLPGA\u30c4\u30a2\u30fc\u30b9\u30b1\u30b8\u30e5\u30fc\u30eb |trans-title=2020 JLPGA Tour Schedule |publisher=JLPGA |language=ja}}</ref>\n\n==Greyhound racing==\nThe [[2020 English Greyhound Derby]] was postponed on 16 March with no replacement dates set at present.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/derby-postponed-statement/|title=DERBY POSTPONED \u2013 ARC STATEMENT|website=Greyhound Star}}</ref> The [[Arena Racing Company]] tracks announced a behind closed doors policy from 24 March <ref>{{cite web|url=http://greyhoundstar.co.uk/arc-meetings-staged-behind-closed-doors/|title=ALL ARC MEETINGS TO BE STAGED BEHIND CLOSED DOORS|website=Greyhound Star}}</ref> and [[Greyhound racing in Ireland|racing in Ireland]] continues with a behind closed doors policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.igb.ie/talking-dogs/covid-19-update-racing-behind-closed-doors/|title=COVID 19 UPDATE: RACING BEHIND CLOSED DOORS|publisher=Irish Greyhound Board}}</ref>\n\n==Gridiron football==\n===CFL===\nOn March 12, the [[Canadian Football League]] announced the cancellation or modification of several pre-season events in response to the pandemic. Several scouting combines across Canada and the United States were cancelled, while other events such as rules committee meetings will now be held remotely. The League continues to plan to hold both its International and National Drafts in April.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cfl.ca/2020/03/12/statement-cfl-coronavirus-situation/ |title=A statement from the CFL on the Coronavirus situation |website=cfl.ca|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL===\nThe [[National Football League]] has been in its off-season since [[Super Bowl LIV|February 2, 2020]], but the [[2020 NFL Draft]] is scheduled to be held in [[Las Vegas]] from April 23\u201325, 2020. On March 12, various NFL teams began to suspend travel by their coaches and [[Scout (sport)|player scout]]s, while the league itself had advised its non-critical staff to work from home. On March 13, 2020, the NFL announced that it had temporarily prohibited draft-eligible players from travelling to meet team personnel, and vice versa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/nfl-coronavirus-updates-league-prohibits-pre-draft-visits-mulls-draft-changes-xfl-player-tests-positive/ |title=NFL coronavirus updates: League prohibits pre-draft visits, mulls draft changes, XFL player tests positive |website=CBSSports.com |language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the NFL announced that it had cancelled public festivities associated with the draft; the draft itself will still be held, but the league stated that it was exploring \"innovative options for how the process will be conducted\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Belson|first=Ken|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/sports/football/nfl-draft-coronavirus.html|title=How the N.F.L. Draft Process Works From Home|date=2020-03-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001106351/article/nfl-draft-to-proceed-april-2325-sans-public-events-in-las-vegas|title=NFL draft to proceed April 23\u201325 sans public events in Las Vegas|website=NFL.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nLabor negotiations with the [[National Football League Players Association]] continued through the pandemic, resulting in ratification of a new, ten-year [[collective bargaining agreement]] in March 2020.\n\n===XFL===\nOn March 12, the [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] announced the suspension of the 2020 season, with all players to be paid their base pay and benefits for the full 2020 regular season; the season was officially cancelled on March 20, with half of its ten-week regular season schedule played.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/xfl-officially-cancels-inaugural-season-reveals-when-players-can-sign-with-nfl-or-cfl-teams/|title=XFL officially cancels inaugural season, reveals when players can sign with NFL or CFL teams|last=Dajani|first=Jordan|date=20 March 2020|publisher=[[CBSSports.com]]|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> The XFL, which is the revival of [[XFL (2001)|a league]] that played only one season in 2001, stated that they were committed to playing a full season in 2021 and future years.\n\n==Gymnastics==\nMultiple international artistic gymnastics competitions, many of which were [[Gymnastics at the 2020 Summer Olympics|Olympic]] qualifying events, were either canceled or postponed.  On March 13, after already having completed qualifications, the [[2020 FIG Artistic Gymnastics World Cup series|Baku World Cup]] canceled its event finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gymnastics.sport/site/news/displaynews.php?idNews=2836|title=Finals of Baku World Cup cancelled|work=[[International Gymnastics Federation]]|date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>  The Stuttgart, Birmingham, and Tokyo World Cups (scheduled to take place between March 21 \u2013 April 5) were all canceled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gymnastics.sport/site/news/displaynews.php?idNews=2827|title=Impact of the COVID-19 outbreak on the upcoming FIG events|work=[[International Gymnastics Federation]]|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.british-gymnastics.org/news-and-events/news/latest-news/9015-british-gymnastics-national-events-announcement-including-fig-world-cup|title=British Gymnastics national events announcement, including FIG World Cup|work=[[British Gymnastics]]|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=tokyowc>{{cite tweet|number=1239945252183703553|user=FIG_media|date=March 17, 2020|title=Japan Gymnastics Association has decided to cancel the #Tokyo All-Around World Cup that was scheduled on 4-5 April 2020}}</ref>  The [[European Women's Artistic Gymnastics Championships]] (scheduled to take place April 30 \u2013 May 3) and the [[European Men's Artistic Gymnastics Championships]] (scheduled to take place May 27\u201331) were both canceled.<ref name=euros2020>{{cite web|url=https://www.ueg.org/news/covid-19-update-event-cancellations|title=COVID-19 update - event cancellations|work=[[European Union of Gymnastics]]|date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>  The [[Pacific Rim Championships]] (scheduled to take place April 17\u201319) was postponed until 2021.<ref name=pacrim>{{cite web|url=https://www.gymnasticsnz.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/2020-Pacific-Rim-postponement-announcement-final-17Mar20.pdf|title=2020 Pacific Rim Championships Postponed|date=March 17, 2020|work=Gymnastics New Zealand}}</ref>\n\n==Handball==\nThe 25\u201329 March, [[2020 European Women's Handball Championship qualification]] matches in Rotterdam, the Netherlands were cancelled.<ref name=\"nu.nl\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nu.nl/sport-overig/6033687/deze-sportevenementen-zijn-afgelast-vanwege-het-coronavirus.html|title=Deze sportevenementen zijn afgelast vanwege het coronavirus|date=February 27, 2020|website=NU|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Horse racing==\nIn the early stages of the outbreak, most horse racing events remained scheduled as normal, but with restricted attendance at racecourses. This included Hong Kong, France,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leparisien.fr/sports/hippisme/coronavirus-les-courses-hippiques-et-les-turfistes-s-adaptent-10-03-2020-8276982.php|title=Coronavirus : Les courses hippiques et les turfistes s'adaptent|first1=Par St\u00e9phan FlourentLe 10 mars 2020|last1=\u00e0 19h56|first2=Modifi\u00e9 Le 10 Mars 2020|last2=\u00c0 19h57|date=March 10, 2020|website=leparisien.fr}}</ref> Japan,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/238823/coronavirus-forces-bettors-online-in-japan |title=Coronavirus Forces Bettors Online in Japan |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |first=Naohiro |last=Goda |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> United Arab Emirates,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/horse-racing/the-35-million-dubai-world-cup-show-must-go-on-1.70362919|title=The $35 million Dubai World Cup show must go on|website=gulfnews.com}}</ref> United States, Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racenet.com.au/news/all-star-mile-slated-to-go-ahead-yet-fans-banned-from-australian-grand-prix-20200313|title=LATEST BREAKING NEWS \u2013 All-Star Mile to go ahead but crowd lockout|website=www.racenet.com.au}}</ref> Ireland,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/latest/dundalk-to-race-behind-closed-doors-as-ireland-launches-coronavirus-restrictions/427842|title=Racing in Ireland to go ahead behind closed doors until March 29 &#124; Horse Racing News &#124; Racing Post|website=www.racingpost.com}}</ref> United Kingdom, Germany, New Zealand, and Singapore.\n\nThe [[Macau Jockey Club]] suspended racing events from 31 January to 15 February and resumed racing from 22 February. The [[Korea Racing Authority]] suspended horse racing from 8 March. [[Sunland Park Racetrack & Casino|Sunland Park Racetrack]] in the United States canceled its race meeting from 16 March, which included the [[Sunland Derby]], part of the [[2020 Road to the Kentucky Derby]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239094/maryland-new-mexico-close-tracks-simulcast-facilities |title=Maryland, New Mexico Close Tracks, Simulcast Facilities |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Many tracks in North America followed suit over the following weeks, although some remained open depending on state-by-state decisions. In Britain, although the [[Cheltenham Festival]] proceeded as normal in mid-March,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Oliphant |first1=Vickiie |title=Cheltenham coronavirus advice: How to avoid COVID-19 \u2013 Festival guidelines in FULL |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/horseracing/1252795/Cheltenham-coronavirus-advice-guidelines-in-full-cheltenham-festival-races |website=Express.co.uk |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=en |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> the [[Grand National]] meeting at Aintree in April was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/grand-national-meeting-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/428688|title=Grand National cancelled as Aintree card lost to spiralling coronavirus crisis &#124; Horse Racing News &#124; Racing Post|website=www.racingpost.com}}</ref> By mid-March [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] had become the only major horse racing country in Europe where the sport continued, albeit strictly regulated and behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2020/mar/18/talking-horses-racing-industry-left-to-contemplate-cost-of-suspension|title=Ireland goes it alone as racing continues behind closed doors|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Greg|last=Wood|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Ireland finally closed down racing on 25 March until at least 19 April.<ref name=IrelandCancelled />\n\n[[Churchill Downs]] announced that the [[2020 Kentucky Derby]], normally the first leg of the [[Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing|American Triple Crown]], would be delayed to September 5;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239121/the-146th-kentucky-derby-moved-to-sept-5 |title=The 146th Kentucky Derby Moved to Sept. 5 |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first1=Eric |last1=Mitchell |first2=Byron |last2=King |title=Owners, Trainers React to Kentucky Derby Postponement |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239123/owners-trainers-react-to-kentucky-derby-postponement |website=[[The Blood-Horse]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |date=17 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> this also cascaded to the [[Preakness Stakes]], with the [[Maryland Jockey Club]] also delaying their second leg race to a date to be determined, likely in September as well.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://baltimore.cbslocal.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-latest-will-the-preakness-be-postponed-jockey-club-discussing/|title=Coronavirus Latest: Preakness To Be Postponed, Likely To September|date=17 March 2020|publisher=[[WJZ-TV]]|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> The [[New York Racing Association]] has not announced plans to reschedule the third leg, the [[Belmont Stakes]].\n\nOn 22 March, it was announced that the [[Dubai World Cup]], due to celebrate its 25th anniversary running on 28 March, had been cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Dubai World Cup night is called off at Meydan |url=https://gulfnews.com/sport/2020-dubai-world-cup-night-is-called-off-at-meydan-1.1584882198359 |website=Gulf News |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome horsemans are limited from travelling to other racecouses or horse racing facilities. Hong Kong-based jockey [[Keith Yeung]] felt unwell on 22 March night, but his test for COVID-19 PCR was negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/racing/article/3076478/hong-kong-jockey-keith-yeungs-covid-19-test-comes-back-negative|title=Hong Kong jockey Keith Yeung's Covid-19 test comes back negative|website=South China Morning Post|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> On 26 March, it was announced that American-based jockey [[Javier Castellano]] had tested positive.<ref>{{cite web |last1=King |first1=Byron |title=Jockey Castellano Tests Positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/239301/jockey-castellano-tests-positive-for-covid-19 |website=BloodHorse.com |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n;Cancelled race meetings<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Updates/Announcements |url=https://www.bloodhorse.com/horse-racing/articles/section/covid-19-updates-announcements |website=www.bloodhorse.com |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Macau Jockey Club]] \u2013 31 January to 15 February, 28 March to 11 April<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mjc.mo/race_en/info/news_detail.php?newsid=32256|title=Macau Jockey Club - Company News|website=Macau Jockey Club|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Korea Racing Authority]] \u2013 from 8 March\n*Selangor Turf Club, Malaysia \u2013 from 14 March\n*[[Sunland Park Racetrack & Casino|Sunland Park Racetrack]], New Mexico \u2013 March meeting\n*[[Keeneland]], Kentucky \u2013 April meeting. [[Kentucky Downs]] and [[Ellis Parks]] closed down in mid-March, while [[Turfway Park]] curtailed its meeting from 29 March to 26 March. Churchill Downs deferred the Kentucky Derby and Kentucky Oaks, normally scheduled for early May, to September\n* [[Woodbine Racetrack]], Toronto \u2013 harness racing from March 14 for at least two weeks. Status of Thoroughbred meeting, scheduled to begin in April, is to be determined\n* [[Aqueduct Racetrack]], New York \u2013 indefinitely from 19 March after a backstretch worker tested positive\n* [[Laurel Park (race track)|Laurel Park]], Maryland \u2013 indefinitely from 20 March\n* [[Fair Grounds Race Course|Fair Grounds]], Louisiana \u2013 cancelled last week of its winter meeting, 22 March to 29 March\n* [[Santa Anita Park]], California - indefinitely from 27 March\n*All United Kingdom racecourses \u2013 18 March to 30 April (excluding [[Downpatrick Racecourse|Downpatrick]] and [[Down Royal Racecourse|Down Royal]] in Northern Ireland, which come under Irish racing rules)\n*All Ireland racecourses \u2013 25 March to 19 April<ref name=IrelandCancelled>{{cite web |title=Racing off in Ireland from Wednesday after all sporting events are cancelled |url=https://www.racingpost.com/news/coronavirus/racing-off-after-all-sporting-events-are-cancelled-in-ireland/429939 |website=Racing Post |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*All German racecourses \u2013 17 March to 18 April<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.turf-times.de/tt-artikel/wegen-des-coronavirus-renn-stopp-bis-zum-18-april-deutschland|title=Wegen des Coronavirus: Renn-Stopp bis zum 18. April in Deutschland! &#124; Turf-Times Deutschland|website=www.turf-times.de|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n*All French racecourses [[France Galop]] and [[LeTrot]] \u2013 17 March to 15 April\n*All United Arab Emirates race meetings \u2013 Including [[Dubai World Cup Night]] and four April meetings.\n*All New Zealand racecourses - From 24 March\n*All South African racecourses - 27 March to 16 April<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportingpost.co.za/2020/03/sa-horseracing/|title=Newsflash: It's Official - No SA Racing|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n;Remaining racing meetings\n*[[Hong Kong Jockey Club]] - no meeting canceled and rescheduled.\n*[[Macau Jockey Club]] \u2013 resumed racing from 22 February to 21 March\n*[[Japan Racing Association]] and [[National Association of Racing]] - no meeting canceled and rescheduled under coronavirus.\n*[[Singapore Turf Club]] - Weekly one meeting from April.\n*[[Solvalla]], Sweden\n*Most Australian racecourses - Some County and Picnic meetings are canceled. \n*Some American racecources, including [[Gulfstream Park]] in Florida and [[Oaklawn Park]] in Arkansas\n\n==Ice hockey==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship|IIHF Women's World Championship]], [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division IV|IIHF World Championship Division IV]] and [[2020 Women's Ice Hockey World Championships|Women's Ice Hockey World Championships]] were all cancelled by the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] due to the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://iihf.com/en/events/2020/ww/news/18296/women%E2%80%99s-worlds-cancelled |title=Women's Worlds cancelled |date=March 7, 2020 |work=iihf.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iihf.com/en/news/18277/iihf-cancels-march-tournaments |title=IIHF cancels March tournaments |date=March 2, 2020 |work=iihf.com}}</ref> The federation also cancelled the [[2020 IIHF World U18 Championships|2020 event]] of one of its two official junior world championship tournaments, the [[IIHF World U18 Championship]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=IIHF cancels U18 Worlds |url=https://www.iihf.com/en/events/2020/wm18/news/18313/iihf-cancels-u18-world-chhmpionship |location=[[Plymouth Charter Township, Michigan]] & [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]], [[United States]] |publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]] |first=Adam |last=Steiss |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 21, IIHF publicly announced that the senior men's world championships had also been cancelled.<ref>{{cite press release | title=2020 IIHF Ice Hockey World Championship cancelled | url=https://www.iihf.com/en/events/2020/wm/news/18344/2020-iihf-ice-hockey-world-championship-cancelled | location=[[Switzerland]] | publisher=[[International Ice Hockey Federation]] | website=iihf.com | first=Adam | last=Steiss | date=March 21, 2020 | access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Cancelled tournaments:'''\n\n* [[2020 IIHF World U18 Championships]]\n*[[2020 IIHF World Championship]]s\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division I]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division II]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division III]]\n* [[2020 IIHF World Championship Division IV]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship Division I]]\n* [[2020 IIHF Women's World Championship Division II]] Group A\n\n===Europe===\n\nAs a result of the German government's ban on large events, the [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] announced on March 10 that it would cancel the remainder of its season, marking the first time in the league's history a champion would not be crowned. The top four teams at the time of the cancellation \u2014 [[EHC Red Bull M\u00fcnchen]], [[Adler Mannheim]], [[Straubing Tigers]], and [[Eisbaren Berlin]] \u2014 would advance to the [[Champions Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite press release | title=German League cancels season, won't crown champion as a result of coronavirus outbreak | url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/german-league-cancels-season-wont-crown-champion-as-a-result-of-coronavirus-outbreak | first=Jared | last=Clinton | publisher=[[The Hockey News]] | website=thehockeynews.com | date=March 10, 2020 | access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Swedish Ice Hockey Association]] suspended all remaining hockey, the playoffs and qualification rounds, in the Swedish elite leagues on March 15; no awarding of the [[Le Mat Trophy]] for the 2019/20 season nor transference of teams from the leagues' qualification plays for the 2020/21 season will happen as a result.<ref>{{cite news | title=Hockeys\u00e4songen 2019/20 st\u00e4lls in | url=https://www.hockeyallsvenskan.se/artikel/2ittak7t7-1el1/hockeysasongen-2019-20-stalls-in | publisher=[[HockeyAllsvenskan]] | language=Swedish | website=hockeyallsvenskan.se |date=March 10, 2020 | access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Cancelled or ended leagues:'''\n\n* [[2019\u201320 Czech Extraliga season]]\n* [[2019\u201320 Slovak Extraliga season]]\n* [[2019-20 Austrian Hockey League season]]\n* [[2019-20 DEL season]]\n* [[2019-20 SHL season]]\n* [[2019-20 EIHL season]]\n\n===North America===\nIn early March 2020, the [[National Hockey League]] suspended media access to the locker rooms, saying that only official personnel would be allowed in after the games to limit person-to-person contact. On March 12, the NHL, [[American Hockey League]], the leagues of the [[Canadian Hockey League]] ([[Ontario Hockey League]], [[Quebec Major Junior Hockey League]], and [[Western Hockey League]]), the [[United States Hockey League|USHL]], and [[ECHL]] announced that their [[2019\u201320 NHL season|2019\u201320 seasons]] would be indefinitely suspended.<ref>{{cite web |title=NHL pauses regular season because of coronavirus |url=https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gaydos |first1=Ryan |title=NHL suspends 2019\u201320 season over coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.foxnews.com/sports/nhl-suspends-season-over-coronavirus-outbreak |website=Fox News |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaplan |first1=Emily |title=NHL suspending play immediately due to virus |url=https://www.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/28891430/sources-nhl-suspending-play-immediately-due-virus |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wearegreenbay.com/community/health/coronavirus/green-bay-gamblers-season-suspended-due-to-covid-19/|title=Green Bay Gamblers season suspended due to COVID-19|last=Rose|first=Joshua|date=12 March 202|work=[[WFRV-TV|WeAreGreenBay.com]]|publisher=[[Nexstar Media Group]]|accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe ECHL announced on March 14 that the remainder of the season would be scrapped.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/28904194/prudent-decision |title=ECHL cancels season amid concerns over virus |date=2020-03-15 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The leagues of the CHL announced on March 18 that they would scrap the remainder of their regular seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/qmjhl-becomes-first-chl-league-to-cancel-remainder-of-regular-season|title=CHL leagues cancel remainder of regular season campaigns; playoff status still undetermined|last=EllisMarch 18|first=Steven|last2=2020|date=2020-03-18|website=The Hockey News|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> On March 23, the CHL confirmed that all playoffs and the [[2020 Memorial Cup]] were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprovince.com/sports/hockey/junior-hockey/covid-19-forces-cancellation-of-chl-playoffs-and-2020-memorial-cup|title=COVID-19 forces cancellation of CHL playoffs and 2020 Memorial Cup|date=2020-03-23|website=The Province|language=en-CA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n[[Hockey Canada]], the governing body for amateur hockey in the country, cancelled the remainder of its season on March 13. This included national championships such as the [[Telus Cup]] and [[Esso Cup]], as well as all regional and provincial playoffs.  It also included the [[Canadian Junior Hockey League]] playoffs and the [[2020 Centennial Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hockeycanada.ca/en-ca/news/2020-news-hockey-canada-ends-season|title=Hockey Canada statement in response to coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=2020-03-12|publisher=Hockey Canada}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/hockey-canada-ends-season-cancels-championships-1.4851343|title=Hockey Canada ends season, cancels championships|last=Hunt|first=Stephen|date=2020-03-12|website=Calgary|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\n==Lacrosse==\nThe [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL) temporarily suspended the [[2020 NLL season|2020 season]] on March 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nll.com/news/nll-statement-on-game-play-march-12-2020/|title=NLL STATEMENT ON GAME PLAY (MARCH 12, 2020)|publisher=National Lacrosse League|website=nll.com|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts==\nDue to [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], [[ONE Championship]]  will host all events closed door at least until May 29, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mmaweekly.com/one-championship-closes-door-on-all-events-until-at-least-may-29-because-of-coronavirus |title=ONE Championship closes door on all events until at least May 29 because of coronavirus {{!}} MMAWeekly.com|date=March 12, 2020|language=en-US|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Bellator MMA in 2020#Bellator 241|Bellator MMA 241]] was scheduled to be a closed-door event,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mma/news/coronavirus-updates-bellator-241-fight-card-to-be-held-without-fans-in-attendance-in-connecticut/ |title=Coronavirus updates: Bellator 241 fight card to be held without fans in attendance in Connecticut |website=CBSSports.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> but was cancelled the day of the fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mmaweekly.com/bellator-makes-last-minute-decision-to-cancel-fridays-bellator-241-coronavirus-covid-19|title=Bellator makes last-minute decision to cancel Friday's Bellator 241|publisher=MMA Weekly|website=mmaweekly.com|first=Ken|last=Pishna|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Konfrontacja Sztuk Walki]] (KSW) cancelled KSW 53 in [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]], Poland for March 21, 2020 event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fightsports.tv/ksw-cancels-upcoming-event-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |title=KSW Cancels Upcoming Event Due To Coronavirus Outbreak |date=March 11, 2020 |website=FIGHT SPORTS |language=en-US|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) hosted its event [[UFC Fight Night: Lee vs. Oliveira]] [[Behind closed doors (sport)|behind closed doors]] in [[Bras\u00edlia]], Brazil.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/news/UFC-Brasilia-to-be-Held-in-Empty-Arena-Following-Governors-Order-Media-Day-Cancelled-171435 |title=UFC Brasilia to be held in empty arena following Governor's order, Media Day cancelled |website=Sherdog.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[UFC Fight Night: Overeem vs. Harris]], [[UFC on ESPN: Ngannou vs. Rozenstruik]], and [[UFC Fight Night: Woodley vs. Edwards]] were postponed to future dates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/ufc-postpones-three-events-coronavirus-pandemic|title=UFC postpones three events amid growing coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-16|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Motorsport==\n===Australian Supercars===\nThe [[Supercars Championship]] had planned to hold an event, the [[Melbourne 400]] supporting the Australian Grand Prix. The event was cancelled the same time the Grand Prix was also cancelled. The Championship is currently seeking to hold a replacement event later in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/13/supercars-confirms-albert-park-cancellation-seeking-replacement-event/|title=Supercars confirms Albert Park cancellation, seeking replacement event|date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The Supercars' [[Tasmania Super400]] at [[Symmons Plains Raceway]] (originally scheduled for 4\u20135 April), the [[Auckland Super400]] at Hampton Downs (25\u201326 April), and the [[Perth SuperNight]] at [[Wanneroo Raceway]] (16\u201317 May) rounds were also postponed beyond June.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chapman|first=Simon|url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/18/breaking-supercars-postpones-tasmania-auckland-and-perth/|title=Supercars postpones Tasmania, Auckland and Perth|publisher=[[Speedcafe]]|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref> The Supercars' support series like the [[Boost Mobile Super Trucks]] were also affected, though the trucks intend to commit to their support schedule once new dates are finalised.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nguyen|first=Justin|url=https://www.thecheckeredflag.co.uk/2020/03/tasmania-auckland-perth-races-postponed-sst-to-follow-reschedules/|title=Tasmania, Auckland, Perth races postponed, SST to follow reschedules|publisher=The Checkered Flag|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSupercars formed the All Stars Eseries to allow its drivers to compete against each other.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bartolomaeus|first=Stefan|url=https://www.supercars.com/news/championship/what-you-need-to-know-supercars-goes-virtual/|title=What you need to know: Supercars goes virtual|publisher=[[Supercars Championship]]|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters===\nThe [[2020 Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters|Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters]] series postponed the start of its championship until July 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/dtm/news/148790/dtm-issues-revised-2020-calendar-set-for-july-start|title=The DTM has issued a revised 2020 calendar set to start in July|first=Rachit|last=Thukral|website=Autosport.com|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Formula One===\nThe early [[2020 Formula One World Championship|Formula One season]] was disrupted by the coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"CHN postponed\">{{cite web |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.chinese-grand-prix-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak.3g2y5Ngyrk1MbNxQB9hj4s.html |title=2020 F1 Chinese Grand Prix postponed due to novel coronavirus outbreak |date=February 12, 2020 |website=Formula1.com |publisher=Formula One World Championship Limited|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200212184109/https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.chinese-grand-prix-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak.3g2y5Ngyrk1MbNxQB9hj4s.html|archive-date=February 12, 2020|access-date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> Prior to the start of the season, [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] and [[Scuderia AlphaTauri|AlphaTauri]] expressed concern about the spread of the virus and its effect on the championship. Both teams are based in Italy, which has suffered [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|one of the worst outbreaks of the virus]] outside China,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148478/ferrari-wants-assurances-over-coronavirus-from-f1 |title=Ferrari wants assurances over coronavirus from F1 before travel |last=Noble |first=Jonathan |date=February 28, 2020 |website=[[Autosport|Autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229014941/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148478/ferrari-wants-assurances-over-coronavirus-from-f1|archive-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148508/tost-unfair-if-australia-goes-ahead-without-all-teams |title=Tost: Unfair if Australia goes ahead without all F1 teams |last=Noble |first=Jonathan |date=March 2, 2020 |website=[[Autosport|Autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303042841/https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/148508/tost-unfair-if-australia-goes-ahead-without-all-teams|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> and so both Ferrari and AlphaTauri were therefore concerned over the ability of their staff to leave a quarantine zone that was established in northern Italy. [[Ross Brawn]], the managing director of the sport, announced that Grands Prix would not go ahead if a team were blocked from entering a host nation, but that events could go ahead if a team voluntarily chose not to enter a host nation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51727401 |title=Coronavirus: F1 will not hold race in country preventing teams entering |last=Benson |first=Andrew |date=March 4, 2020 |website=[[BBC Sport]] |publisher=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305134810/https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51727401|archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> The [[Australian Grand Prix|Australian]] and [[Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Grands Prix]] were cancelled.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/51849163 |title=Coronavirus: Australian Grand Prix called off |date=March 13, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 13, 2020 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"NEDMONESP\"/> The cancellation of the Monaco Grand Prix meant that 2020 would mark the first time since {{F1|1954}} that the race has not been held. The [[Azerbaijan Grand Prix|Azerbaijan]], [[Bahrain Grand Prix|Bahrain]], [[Chinese Grand Prix|Chinese]], [[Dutch Grand Prix|Dutch]], [[Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish]] and [[Vietnam Grand Prix|Vietnam Grands Prix]] were postponed.<ref name=\"NEDMONESP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.dutch-spanish-and-monaco-grands-prix-postponed.5CggooJeHoDchKkFehkrkY.html|title=Dutch, Spanish and Monaco Grands Prix postponed|website=formula1.com|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"spectators\">{{cite web |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/08/no-spectators-for-bahrain-grand-prix/ |title=No spectators for Bahrain Grand Prix |last=Chapman |first=Simon |date=March 8, 2020 |website=Speedcafe|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://mobile.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-13/f1-grand-prix-in-china-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-fears/11960614 |title=Coronavirus fears force the postponement of the F1 Grand Prix in China in April |work=abc.net.au |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=13 February 2020 |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> The summer break shut down period\u2014which includes mandatory factory closures as a cost-cutting measure\u2014was also brought forward from August to March and April and was extended to three weeks, allowing for postponed races to be held in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.f1-summer-shutdown-brought-forward-in-response-to-coronavirus-outbreak.5a4PM49x3Rs3WKMmxfUIO8.html|title=F1 summer shutdown brought forward in response to coronavirus outbreak|last=|first=|date=2020-03-18|website=Formula1.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nThe sport had planned to overhaul its technical regulations for the {{F1|2021}} championship in one of the largest changes in its seventy-year history. The pandemic prompted these changes to be postponed until {{F1|2022}}, with teams required to enter their {{F1|2020}} cars in the 2021 championship to minimise the financial stress placed on the teams.<ref name=\"19 chassis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/20/formula-1s-new-regulations-delayed-until-2022/|title=Formula 1's new regulations delayed until 2022|first=Daniel|last=Herrero|work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]]|publisher=[[Speedcafe]]|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRecently,{{when|date=March 2020}} some Formula One drivers have entered a virtual version of the [[Australian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DG1cFm3dsaU|title=Veloce Esports's NotAusGP|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> and the [[Bahrain Grand Prix]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vVLTdi4BtPE|title=Veloce Esports's NotTheBahGP|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QwcRDOjgfkE|title=F1 Bahrain Virtual Grand Prix|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The races are hosted by [[Jean-\u00c9ric Vergne]]'s Veloce Esports and F!. The online races are contested by current and former F1 drivers, like [[Lando Norris]], [[Nicholas Latifi]], [[Stoffel Vandoorne]], [[Esteban Guti\u00e9rrez]], [[Nico H\u00fclkenberg]], [[Johnny Herbert]] and [[Martin Brundle]], as well as celebrities and other sportsmen.\n\n====Formula 2 and Formula 3====\nThe [[Bahrain International Circuit|Bahrain]], [[Circuit Zandvoort|Zandvoort]] and [[Circuit de Barcelona|Barcelona]] rounds of the [[2020 FIA Formula 2 Championship|FIA Formula 2]] and [[2020 FIA Formula 3 Championship|Formula 3 Championships]]\u2014a series of races for junior drivers that run in support of Formula 1 events\u2014were postponed when the Bahrain, Dutch and Spanish Grands Prix were postponed.<ref name=\"BHR postponed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2020/03_March/FIA-Formula-2-and-FIA-Formula-3-Championships-Round-1-in-Bahrain-postponed/ |title=FIA Formula 2 and FIA Formula 3 Championships Round 1 in Bahrain postponed \u2013 Formula 2 |website=fiaformula2.com|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ZANBARMON\">{{cite news|url=https://www.fiaformula2.com/Latest/53FNxDGggZW5n65yl8aFpB/fia-formula-2-and-fia-formula-3-championships-may-races-and-tests-postponed|title=FIA Formula 2 and FIA Formula 3 Championships May races and tests postponed|work=fiaformula2.com|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Circuit de Monaco|Monaco]] Formula 2 round was cancelled when the Monaco Grand Prix was cancelled and the [[Baku City Circuit|Baku]] round postponed when the Azerbaijan Grand Prix was postponed;<ref name=\"ZANBARMON\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fiaformula2.com/Latest/3jBJqgLEiIY3w7fOsUwScE/fia-f2-round-in-baku-postponed-as-coronavirus-outbreak-continues|title=FIA Formula 2 round in Baku postponed as Coronavirus outbreak continues|work=fiaformula2.com|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> Formula 3 had not been scheduled to race in Monaco or Azerbaijan.\n\n===Formula E===\nThe [[Formula E]] championship for electric cars initially responded to the pandemic by postponing the [[Rome ePrix|Rome]] and [[Sanya ePrix]]. Planned races in [[Paris ePrix|Paris]], [[Jakarta ePrix|Jakarta]] and [[Seoul ePrix|Seoul]] were also postponed, prompting organisers to postpone the entire season by two months.<ref name=Sanya>{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/formula-e/news/fe-china-sanya-eprix-coronavirus/4679553/amp/ |title=Formula E postpones China race amid virus outbreak |first=Alex |last=Kalinauckas |date=February 2, 2020|access-date=February 2, 2020 |website=motorsport.com}}</ref><ref name=Rome>{{cite news |url=https://www.fiaformulae.com/NEWS/2020/March/rome-eprix-update-march-2020?utm_source=FormulaETwitter&utm_mediumSocialPost&utm_campaign=rome&utm_source=FormulaETwitter&utm_mediumSocialPost&utm_campaign=rome |date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020 |website=fiaformulae.com |title=Statement on the 2020 Rome E-Prix}}</ref><ref name=ParisAndSeoul>{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/formula-e/news/coronavirus-suspend-season-two-months/4740500/ |first1=Charles |last1=Bradley |title=Formula E set to suspend 2019\u201320 season for two months |website=motorsport.com |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===GT World Challenge Europe===\nThe 3 Hours of Monza round of the [[2020 GT World Challenge Europe Endurance Cup]], scheduled for 19 April, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/gt/news/148594/gtwce-opener-in-italy-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus|title=GT World Challenge Europe Monza opener cancelled due to coronavirus|first=Gary|last=Watkins|website=Autosport.com|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===IndyCar===\nThe [[IndyCar Series]] initially announced on March 12 that it would hold the [[Firestone Grand Prix of St. Petersburg|Grand Prix of St. Petersburg]] \u2014 the opening race of the [[2020 IndyCar Series|2020 season]] \u2014 behind closed doors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://racer.com/2020/03/12/indycar-st-pete-to-run-behind-closed-doors-condensed-schedule/ |title=IndyCar St Pete to run behind closed doors; condensed schedule |date=March 12, 2020 |website=RACER |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 13, the series announced that it would cancel all races through at least the end of April, including St. Petersburg, [[Honda Indy Grand Prix of Alabama|Alabama]], [[Grand Prix of Long Beach|Long Beach]], and [[AutoNation IndyCar Challenge|Austin]]. IndyCar intended to begin the season with the traditional \"Month of May\" races at [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]], including the [[GMR Grand Prix|road course race]], and the 104th running of the [[Indianapolis 500]] on its traditional [[Memorial Day]] weekend scheduling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://racer.com/2020/03/13/indycar-cancels-st-pete-first-four-races/ |title=IndyCar cancels St Pete, first four races |date=March 13, 2020 |website=RACER |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, IndyCar announced that it would tentatively delay the beginning of the season to the end of May (beginning with the [[Detroit Grand Prix (IndyCar)|Detroit Grand Prix]] on May 30 and 31) by postponing the two Indianapolis races to later in the season. The [[GMR Grand Prix]] was moved to [[Independence Day (United States)|July 4]], and the Indianapolis 500 to August 23\u2014marking the first time in history that it has not been held in May. The Grand Prix of St. Petersburg was reinstated as the planned season finale, with a date to be determined.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/motor/2020/03/26/indycar-calendar-undergoes-massive-overhaul/2918583001/|title=IndyCar calendar undergoes massive overhaul in response to coronavirus|website=Indianapolis Star|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nIndyCar eventually formed the IndyCar iRacing Challenge, with its drivers racing against one another on the ''[[iRacing]]'' [[racing simulation]] game.<ref>{{cite web|last=Eubanks|first=Michael|url=https://motorsports.nbcsports.com/2020/03/28/indycar-iracing-challenge-drivers-first-virtual-race-at-watkins-glen/|title=What drivers said after IndyCar's iRacing opener at Watkins Glen|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===MotoGP===\nThe [[MotoGP|MotoGP World Championship]] cancelled the opening round of the 2020 championship in [[2020 Qatar motorcycle Grand Prix|Qatar]]. The [[Moto2]] and [[Moto3]] support categories raced in the country. Planned events in the United States, Argentina and Thailand were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fim-live.com/en/article/motogp-class-cancelled-at-the-grand-prix-of-qatar/ |title=MOTOGP CLASS CANCELLED AT THE GRAND PRIX OF QATAR |last= |first= |date=March 1, 2020 |website=FIM-live.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NASCAR===\nPrior to the [[2020 Folds of Honor QuikTrip 500]], part of the [[2020 NASCAR Cup Series]], [[NASCAR]] announced that no fans would be permitted to attend the race; this event, along with the [[Dixie Vodka 400]] at [[Homestead-Miami Speedway]], were later postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/12/nascar-statement-atlanta-homestead-race-schedules/ |title=NASCAR statement on Atlanta and Homestead {{!}} NASCAR|date=March 12, 2020|website=Official Site Of NASCAR|language=en-US|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, NASCAR announced that all race events through May 3 were postponed, however they still intend to run all 36 races for the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nascar.com/news-media/2020/03/16/nascar-schedule-update-statement-race-coronavirus/ |title=NASCAR statement: All race events through May 3 postponed {{!}} NASCAR|date=March 16, 2020|website=NASCAR.com|language=en-US|access-date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNASCAR subsequently began to organize invitational [[eSports]] events on ''iRacing'', featuring current and past NASCAR drivers, officially known as the eNASCAR iRacing Pro Invitational Series. [[Fox NASCAR|Fox Sports]] also picked up broadcasts of these events to provide filler content for [[Fox Sports 1]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autoweek.com/racing/nascar/a31789600/fox-sports-to-air-iracing-event-featuring-full-field-of-nascar-drivers/|title=Fox Sports to air iRacing event featuring full field of NASCAR drivers|last=Weaver|first=Matt|date=2020-03-19|website=Autoweek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n===World Endurance Championship===\nThe [[1000 Miles of Sebring]] race was cancelled.<ref name=\"Sebring\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailysportscar.com/2020/03/12/wec-set-to-cancel-sebring-trip.html |title=WEC Cancels Sebring Race (Updated) |date=March 12, 2020 |work=Marshall Pruett |publisher=Dailysportscar.com |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The [[6 Hours of Spa-Francorchamps]] and the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] were both postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://racer.com/2020/03/16/wec-postpones-spa/|title=WEC postpones Spa|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/motorsport/51946353| title= Coronavirus: Le Mans 24 Hours postponed until September| work=[[BBC Sport]]| date=18 March 2020| accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===World Rally Championship===\nThe 2020 running of [[Rally Argentina]], [[Rally Italia Sardegna]] and [[Rally Portugal]] were postponed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.autosport.com/wrc/news/148648/coronavirus-forces-rally-argentina-to-be-postponed |title=Coronavirus forces WRC Rally Argentina to be postponed |first=Nick |last=Garton |work=[[Autosport|autosport.com]] |publisher=[[Motorsport Network]] |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.autosport.com/wrc/news/148778/wrc-season-hit-by-more-postponements|title=WRC 2020 season hit by more rally postponements due to coronavirus|first=Pablo|last=Elizalde|work=[[Autosport|autosport.com]]|publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 Rally Mexico]] was shortened to allow competitors time to pack their equipment up and return to their headquarters in Europe before a series of travel bans were implemented.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2020/03/15/rally-mexico-shortened-by-a-day-due-to-travel-restrictions/ |title=Rally Mexico shortened by a day due to travel restrictions |first=Daniel |last=Herrero |work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]] |publisher=[[Speedcafe]] |date=15 March 2020 |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 World Rally Championship-2|World Rally Championship-2]], [[2020 World Rally Championship-3|World Rally Championship-3]] and [[2020 Junior World Rally Championship|Junior World Rally Championship]] support categories were also affected by the postponements.\n\n===World Rallycross Championship===\nThe opening rounds of the [[2020 FIA World Rallycross Championship]] in [[World RX of Barcelona|Barcelona]] and [[World RX of Portugal|Portugal]] were postponed.<ref name=\"BarcelonaPostponed\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/world-rx/news/world-rallycross-opener-barcelona-coronavirus/4746950/ |title=World RX postpones Barcelona opener over coronavirus |date=13 March 2020 |last=Ridge |first=Hal |publisher=motorsport.com |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PortugalPostponed\">{{cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/world-rx/news/portugal-second-round-postponed-coronavirus/4771259/|title=World RX's second round also postponed due to coronavirus|date=20 March 2020|last=Ridge|first=Hal|publisher=motorsport.com|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===World Touring Car Cup===\nThe opening rounds of the [[2020 World Touring Car Cup]] in [[FIA WTCC Race of Hungary|Hungary]] and [[FIA WTCC Race of Germany|Germany]] were cancelled.<ref name=\"hun2020cancellation\">{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/wtcr/wtcr-race-of-hungary-statement_sto7702776/story.shtml |title=WTCR Race of Hungary statement |date=13 March 2020 |work=Eurosport |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/17/nurburgring-24-hours-race-weekend-postponed-september/|title=N\u00fcrburgring 24 Hours race weekend postponed to September|date=17 March 2020|work=TouringCarTimes|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fiawtcr.com/update-wtcr-race-of-germany/|title=Update: WTCR Race of Germany|date=17 March 2020|work=FIA WTCR {{!}} World Touring Car Cup|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> The four races that would have been held across the two rounds were rescheduled for other rounds.\n\n===Motorcycle road racing===\nThe 2020 [[Isle of Man TT]] was cancelled on 16 March.<ref>[http://web.archive.org/web/20200316235253/https://www.iomtt.com/news/2020/03/16/tt-2020-cancelled Isle of Mann Government announces cancellation of 2020 TT Races] Isle of Mann TT 16 March 2020</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[North West 200]] event was postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Statement Re the Postponement of the 2020 fonaCAB and Nicholl Oils North West 200 |url=https://www.northwest200.org/statement-re-the-postponement-of-the-2020-fonacab-and-nicholl-oils-north-west-200/ |website=northwest200.org |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 [[Scottish Six Days Trial]] event was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.obantimes.co.uk/2020/03/16/scottish-six-days-trial-and-pre-65-trial-cancelled-due-to-covid-19-outbreak-2/|title=Scottish Six Days Trial and Pre '65 Trial cancelled due to Covid-19 outbreak|date=16 March 2020|website=The Oban Times|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/highlands/2077336/coronavirus-lochabers-scottish-six-days-trial-event-cancelled/|title=Coronavirus: Lochaber's Scottish Six Days Trial event cancelled|first=Stuart|last=Findlay|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===British national-level championships===\nAll British motorsport, including the [[2020 British Touring Car Championship|British Touring Car Championship]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.touringcartimes.com/2020/03/17/btcc-postpones-opening-three-rounds-coronavirus-policy-change/|title=BTCC postpones opening three rounds after coronavirus policy change|date=17 March 2020|website=Touring Car Times|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> the [[2020 British GT Championship|British GT Championship]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.britishgt.com/news/590/british-gt-season-opener-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak|title=British GT season opener postponed due to coronavirus outbreak|date=17 March 2020|publisher=britishgt.com|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> and the [[Britcar]] [[2020 Britcar Endurance Championship|Endurance]] and [[2020 Britcar Trophy Championship|Trophy Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britcar-endurance.com/newsRead.php?link=317&page=0|title=Opening Rounds Postponed|website=Britcar Endurance|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> were postoned until July 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autosport.com/national/news/148772/uk-motorsport-on-hold-until-july-due-to-covid19|title=UK motorsport on hold until July to contain spread of coronavirus|first=Stefan Mackley, Paul|last=Lawrence|website=Autosport.com|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Monster trucks===\n[[Monster Jam]] events in multiple localities were affected. Shows in [[Austin, Texas]], [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], [[Columbia, South Carolina]], [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]], [[Columbus, Ohio]], [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], and [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]] were postponed; and a show in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]] was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.monsterjam.com/en-US/event-basic-page|title=Event basic page &#124; Monster Jam|website=www.monsterjam.com|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Hot Wheels|Hot Wheels Monster Trucks Live]] postponed a show in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whas11.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/hot-wheels-monster-trucks-postponed/417-fe68c6a7-fba6-46f3-b913-d4ab3ad5cc99|title=Hot Wheels Monster Trucks Live postpones shows this weekend|website=WHAS11|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMonster X Tour postponed it's World Finals event in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://alohastadium.hawaii.gov/main/monster-x-tour/|title=MONSTER X TOUR WORLD FINALS 2020 \u2013 RESCHEDULED JULY 25-26|website=alohastadium.hawaii.gov|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020, [[Monster Jam World Finals XXI|World Finals XXI]], scheduled to take place May 2\u20133, 2020, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|title=Monster Jam World Finals 2020 Cancelled|date=March 27, 2020|url=https://www.monsterjam.com/en-US/2020-worldfinals-cancelled|publisher=[[Monster Jam]]|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Radio-controlled racing===\nDespite taking place in the second half of the year, all 4 blocks (representing Asia ([[Far East Model Car Association|FEMCA]]), North America ([[Remotely Operated Auto Racers|ROAR]]), Europe ([[European Federation of Radio Operated Model Automobiles|EFRA]]) and the rest of the world ([[Fourth Association of Model Auto Racing|FAMAR]])) and the [[International Federation of Model Auto Racing|IFMAR committee]] have agreed to postpone all remaining [[IFMAR World Championships]] ([[2020 IFMAR ISTC World Championship|1:10 Electric Touring Car]] in Heemstede, Netherlands); [[2020 IFMAR 1:8 IC Off-Road World Championship|1:8 IC Off-Road]] in Cianorte, Brasil and [[2020 IFMAR 1:10 IC Touring Car World Championship|1:10 IC Touring Car]] in Brisbane, Australia) to an alternative date, possibly early 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverc.com/news/announcements/22360-All_2020_IFMAR_World_Championships_Postponed/ |title=All 2020 IFMAR World Championships Postponed |publisher=LiveRC.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redrc.net/2020/03/ifmar-call-off-2020-season/ |title=IFMAR call off 2020 season |publisher=Red RC |date= March 28, 2020|accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref> This was the first postponement since 2001 when the events of the [[September 11 attacks]] caused the [[IFMAR 1:10 Electric Off-Road World Championship|1:10 Electric Off-Road Worlds]] to be moved to May the following year.\n\n==Poker==\n\nAs of March 18, most casinos and other gaming venues worldwide have been closed indefinitely and many upcoming live [[poker tournament]]s have been either postponed, cancelled or (in jurisdictions where currently permitted) moved to an [[online poker|online platform]]. Tournaments originally scheduled to be played live and now being played online include the 2020 [[Irish Poker Open]].\n\nThe pandemic has resulted in a massive increase in online poker traffic. It is believed to have directed both professional and recreational players who normally prefer live poker to online platforms due the indefinite closure of most casinos and other live gaming venues worldwide, with even many [[Underground poker|unlicensed venues]] shutting down. In addition, the sudden dearth of live entertainment options due to the widespread disruption of the sports and entertainment schedules around the world is believed to have resulted in more than the usual number of casual players turning to online poker as an alternative. Many operators reported traffic of double or more the previous volume, depending on the time of day.\n\n==Professional wrestling==\n===New Japan Pro-Wrestling===\nIn accordance with recommendations from the Japanese Ministry of Health, [[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] (NJPW) decided to cancel all scheduled shows from March 1 through March 15.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-cancels-shows-march-1-15-due-coronavirus-outbreak-305026 |title=NJPW CANCELS SHOWS FROM MARCH 1\u201315 DUE TO CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK |first=Joseph |last=Currier |date=February 26, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> On March 10, NJPW announced that they were cancelling all shows through March 22, which meant that they either cancelled or postponed the [[New Japan Cup#2020|2020 New Japan Cup]] as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/new-japan-news/njpw-cancels-remainder-new-japan-cup-tour-due-coronavirus-306136 |title=NJPW CANCELS REMAINDER OF NEW JAPAN CUP TOUR DUE TO CORONAVIRUS |first=Brian |last=Rose |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref> The [[World Wonder Ring Stardom|Stardom]] promotion, sister company of NJPW also owned by [[Bushiroad]], also made adjustments to their scheduled, cancelling shows from February 19 to March 14. Their March 8 show in [[Korakuen Hall]] was held without any spectators in attendance, instead streaming live on their [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/stardom-makes-major-schedule-changes-due-coronavirus-outbreak-304441 |title=STARDOM MAKES MAJOR SCHEDULE CHANGES DUE TO CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK |first=Josh |last=Nason |date=February 18, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]}}</ref>\n\n===WWE===\nAmerican promotion [[WWE]] began to move the broadcasts of its weekly programs, including ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]]'' and ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' (which usually broadcast from arenas), and ''[[WWE NXT|NXT]]'' (which is usually filmed at [[Full Sail University]]; the school has suspended group activities through April)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2020/03/13/wwe-moves-smackdown-taping-to-orlandos-wwe-performance-center-at-full-sail-amid-coronavirus-concerns |title=WWE moves 'SmackDown' taping to Orlando's WWE Performance Center at Full Sail amid coronavirus concerns |last=Moyer |first=Matthew |website=Orlando Weekly |language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> to the [[WWE Performance Center]] in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], beginning with ''SmackDown'' on March 13, with no audience and only essential staff in attendance. The first ''SmackDown'' and ''Raw'' broadcasts under this arrangement included fewer live matches than usual episodes, with time filled by encores of matches from recent WWE [[pay-per-view]] events ([[Elimination Chamber (2020)|Elimination Chamber]] and [[Royal Rumble (2020)|Royal Rumble]] respectively).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-raw-results-recap-grades-steve-austin-celebrates-new-wrestlemania-36-matches-made/live/|title=WWE Raw results, recap, grades: Steve Austin celebrates, new WrestleMania 36 matches made|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/coronavirus-wwe-smackdown-live-1203532469/ |title=WWE Moves 'SmackDown Live' to Orlando Performance Center With No Live Audience Due to Coronavirus |last=Otterson |first=Joe |date=March 12, 2020 |website=Variety|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-smackdown-results-recap-grades-john-cena-caps-surreal-empty-arena-showy-you-have-to-see/live/ |title=WWE SmackDown results, recap, grades: John Cena caps surreal empty arena show you have to see |website=CBSSports.com|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> The promotion also postponed some of its upcoming [[house show]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2020/03/13/22805585.html |title=WWE house shows cancelled, AEW alters plans |website=canoe.com|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the [[NXT TakeOver: Tampa Bay]] event and [[WWE Hall of Fame (2020)|2020 Hall of Fame ceremony]] were postponed to unannounced dates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/134766/wwe-hall-of-fame-nxt-takeover-off.html?p=1|title=WWE HALL OF FAME, NXT TAKEOVER OFF|publisher=PW Insider|website=pwinsider.com|first=Mike|last=Johnson|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[WrestleMania 36]] was originally scheduled to be held at [[Tampa, Florida]]'s [[Raymond James Stadium]]. On March 16, WWE announced that it would also be produced from the Performance Center, as well as a second, unannounced venue, and air across two nights (April 4 and 5).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/wrestlemania-canceled-coronavirus-wwe-tampa-1202881422/|title=WrestleMania To Stream Live Without Audience Due To Coronavirus Outbreak|last=Ramos|first=Dino-Ray|date=2020-03-16|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/wwe-splits-audience-less-wrestlemania-36-into-two-nights/|title=WWE Splits Audience-Less WrestleMania 36 Into Two Nights|last=Maglio|first=Tony|date=2020-03-18|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/wrestlemania-36/article/wrestlemania-36-two-night-wwe-network-rob-gronkowski-host|title=Unprecedented two-night WrestleMania to be hosted by Rob Gronkowski on WWE Network|date=March 17, 2020|work=WWE|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> It was then reported by ''[[PWInsider]]'' on March 21 that WWE would be filming all remaining episodes of ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' preceding WrestleMania, as well as the event itself\u2014in advance over the following days, rather than air them live.<ref name=\"taped\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/134908/wwe-scheduled-to-tape-everything-through-wrestlemania-this-week.html?p=1|title=WWE SCHEDULED TO TAPE EVERYTHING THROUGH WRESTLEMANIA THIS WEEK|last=Johnson|first=Mike|date=March 21, 2020|publisher=PWInsider|accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===All Elite Wrestling===\nOn March 12, [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW) announced the relocation of its two remaining live broadcasts of ''[[AEW Dynamite|Dynamite]]'' for the month of March, scheduled for [[Rochester, New York]] and [[Newark, New Jersey]] respectively, to an alternative location with no audience. AEW stated that it had re-booked the two cities for future episodes in July. Their [[AEW Blood and Guts|Blood and Guts]] show was also postponed.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbr.com/aew-dynamite-coronavirus-venue-changes/ |title=AEW Announces Venue Changes, Including Blood & Guts Show, Due to COVID-19 |date=2020-03-13 |website=CBR |language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> AEW has since originated programming from [[TIAA Bank Field]]'s [[Daily's Place]] amphitheater in [[Jacksonville, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news4jax.com/news/local/2020/03/13/aew-moves-show-from-rochester-to-jacksonville-due-to-coronavirus/|title=AEW moves show from Rochester to Jacksonville due to coronavirus|last=Mealey|first=Jason|date=2020-03-13|website=WJXT|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n===Impact Wrestling===\nOn March 16, [[Impact Wrestling]] announced that [[Lockdown (2020)|Lockdown]] scheduled for March 28 in [[Windsor, Ontario]], and March Breakdown scheduled for March 29 in [[Belleville, Michigan]] have been postponed. On March 17, Impact Wrestling announced that [[TNA: There's No Place Like Home]] has been cancelled along with the other events associated with WrestleCon. On March 24, it was announced that [[TNA Against All Odds|Against All Odds]] scheduled for April 17 in Toronto, [[Rebellion (2020)|Rebellion]] scheduled for April 19 in Columbus, and the TV tapings schedule for April 24 and 25 were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://impactwrestling.com/our-response-to-covid-19/ |title=An Update on Events |date=March 24, 2020 |website=Impact Wrestling |language=en|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ring of Honor===\nOn March 12, [[Ring of Honor]] announced the cancellations of its [[ROH 18th Anniversary Show]] scheduled for March 13 and its ''Past vs. Present'' event scheduled for March 14 at Sam's Town Live in [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rohwrestling.com/news/roh-18th-anniversary-and-past-vs-present-shows-cancellation |title=ROH 18TH ANNIVERSARY AND PAST VS PRESENT SHOWS CANCELLATION |date=March 12, 2020 |website=Ring of Honor |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 17, Ring of Honor announced the cancellation of all events through May 31.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rohwrestling.com/news/roh-cancels-all-live-events-through-may-31st-2020 |title=ROH 18TH ROH CANCELS ALL LIVE EVENTS THROUGH MAY 31ST, 2020 |date=March 17, 2020 |website=Ring of Honor |language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre===\nThe Mexican [[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]] company announced that they were cancelling their shows in Guadalajara, Jalisco to comply with the statewide recommendations. The promotion cancelled both their Tuesday ''Martes de Glamour'' shows and their Sunday ''Domingos Tapat\u00edos'' shows for the foreseeable future.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://superluchas.com/funciones-canceladas-por-coronavirus-en-mexico/ |title=Primeras funciones canceladas por Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |language=Spanish |work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] |first=Carlos |last=Acosta}}</ref>\n\n===Lucha Libre AAA Worldwide===\nOn March 13, [[Lucha Libre AAA Worldwide]] announced that they were cancelling their next major show, the 2020 ''[[Rey de Reyes (2020)|Rey de Reyes]]''  (\"King of Kings\") show originally scheduled for March 21 in Medida, Yucat\u00e1n. They announced that they would announce a future date for the event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://superluchas.com/aaa-se-cancela-rey-de-reyes-2020-por-coronavirus/ |title=AAA: Se cancela \"Rey de Reyes 2020\" por Coronavirus | trans-title= AAA: Cancelling \"Rey de Reyes 2020\" because of the Coronoavirus |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |language=Spanish |work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] |first=Carlos |last=Acosta}}</ref>\n\n=== National Wrestling Alliance ===\nOn March 16, [[National Wrestling Alliance]] announced the suspension of its operations until June, which included the [[Crockett Cup (2020)|2020 Crockett Cup]] on April 19 and [[NWA Power]] tapings on April 20 and April 21. NWA also cancelled an airing of Super Powerrr, scheduled for March 17, in order to not create confusion in the marketplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalwrestlingalliance.com/news/nwa-suspends-crockett-cup-amp-nwa-powerrr-live-events|title=NWA SUSPENDS CROCKETT CUP & NWA POWERRR LIVE EVENTS|website=NWA|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n==Rodeo==\nThe 2020 [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] was cancelled after a festival attendee was diagnosed positive with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.click2houston.com/rodeo/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-amid-growing-concerns-over-coronavirus/|title=Houston Rodeo canceled; coronavirus patient attended Rodeo cookoff in February|last=Barker|first=Daniela Sternitzky-Di Napoli, Aaron|date=2020-03-12|website=KPRC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Rowing==\nFour [[Rowing at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|Olympic qualification regattas]] were cancelled, including the final qualification event scheduled to be held in [[Lucerne]], [[Switzerland]], from 17 to 19 May. All three events of the 2020 [[World Rowing Cup]] were also cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |title=Joint Decisions related to the impact of the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) on remaining Olympic and Paralympic qualification events |url=http://www.worldrowing.com/news/joint-decisions-related-the-impact-the-novel-coronavirus-covid-remaining-olympic-and-paralympic-qualification-events |website=World Rowing |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[The Boat Race 2020]], due to take place on the [[River Thames]] in [[London]] on 29 March, was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2020-03-16/the-boat-race-has-been-cancelled-due-to-coronavirus/ | publisher = ITV| title = The Boat Race has been cancelled due to Coronavirus | date = 16 March 2020 | accessdate = 17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Rugby league==\nThe Australian/New Zealand [[National Rugby League]] was scheduled to continue with no spectators permitted in the stadiums however this was abandoned after round two.\n\nFor the first time in the competition's history, the entire season was suspended indefinitely on 23 March 2020,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2020/03/23/nrl-suspends-competition-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/|title=NRL suspends competition due to coronavirus pandemic|date=23 March 2020|work=National Rugby League|author=Dan Walsh}}</ref> and if the season cannot be restarted by 1 September, it will be abandoned with no premiership awarded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrl.com/news/2020/03/24/nrl-tells-clubs-season-needs-to-start-by-september-to-be-salvaged/|title=NRL tells clubs season must restart by September to be salvaged|publisher=NRL.com|first=Dan|last=Walsh|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSuper League and the Rugby Football League suspended the season until 3 April as a result of the spread of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/51911290 |title=Coronavirus: Rugby Football League suspends season until 3 April |date=March 16, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 16, 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Rugby union==\nAt the end of February and start of March, the [[2020 Six Nations Championship]] saw all games against [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]] postponed due to the worsening situation in that country,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51749254 |title=Coronavirus: England's Six Nations games against Italy postponed |date=March 5, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 13, 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> with games against the [[Scotland women's national rugby union team|Scotland women's team]] also cancelled as one of the players tested positive and the team went into isolation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51777621 |title=Women's Six Nations: Scotland v France postponed after home player tests positive for coronavirus |date=March 6, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 13, 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> By March 13, the competition had been suspended.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907 |title=Six Nations: Wales v Scotland off because of coronavirus |date=March 13, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 13, 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref> On March 12, the [[Pro14]] European rugby competition was suspended,.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51858815 |title=Coronavirus: Pro14 suspended indefinitely due to coronavirus |date=March 12, 2020 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=March 13, 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Super Rugby]], two fixtures of Japanese team [[Sunwolves]] had been moved to Australia from Japan, while Australia announced on 12 March that beginning in the next round of fixtures, all matches held in Australia would be played with no spectators, but otherwise continue as normal. However, on 14 March, New Zealand (who fields five teams in the competition) announced that it will require 14 days self-isolation for any person that arrives in the country from outside of the Pacific Islands, regardless of origin and including New Zealand citizens. League organizer [[SANZAAR]] stated that it was evaluating the impact of this restriction,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/rugby/super-rugby/super-rugby-coronavirus-news-2020-new-zealand-government/news-story/794c8a43de0a3806ea699a7503063461 |title=Super Rugby season on verge of shutdown after NZ restrictions |date=2020-03-14 |website=Fox Sports |language=en-AU|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rugby.com.au:443/news/2020/03/13/corona-virus-international-updates |title=Coronavirus: How rugby has been affected around the world |website=www.rugby.com.au |language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rugby.com.au:443/news/2020/03/12/super-rugby-waratahs-coronavirus |title=LOCKOUT: Coronavirus forces rugby behind closed doors next week but fans welcome at weekend |website=www.rugby.com.au |language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> and ultimately announced later in the day that the season would be suspended following the completion of the weekend's fixtures.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/sport/rugby-union/all-super-rugby-matches-to-be-cancelled-after-sunday-s-fixtures-20200314-p54a4u.html |title=All Super Rugby matches to be cancelled after Sunday's fixtures |last=Decent |first=Tom |date=2020-03-14 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, [[Major League Rugby]] in the United States suspended its third season for 30 days,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.majorleague.rugby/news/major-league-rugby-suspends-2020-season-for-30-days/|title=MAJOR LEAGUE RUGBY SUSPENDS 2020 SEASON FOR 30 DAYS|website=Major League Rugby|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> but on March 18, organizers announced that it will suspend until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americasrugbynews.com/2020/03/18/major-league-rugby-to-suspend-until-2021/|title=Major League Rugby to suspend until 2021|date=2020-03-19|website=Americas Rugby News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Shooting==\nThe 2020 [[ISSF World Cup]], which was to commence on March 15 in New Delhi, was postponed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/sports/virus-hits-indian-sports/articleshow/74519560.cms |title=Virus hits Indian sports |work=Economic Times |accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The Olympic Test Event in Tokyo, originally scheduled for April 2020, was also cancelled.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.issf-sports.org/news.ashx?newsid |title=Test Event \"READY STEADY TOKYO\" |publisher=International Shooting Sport Federation |accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Short track speed skating==\nThe 2020 [[World Short Track Speed Skating Championships]] in Seoul, South Korea scheduled 13\u201315 March were cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://speedskating.ca/news-and-info/news/isu-officially-cancels-world-short-track-championships-in-south-korea-due-to-coronavirus|title=ISU Officially Cancels World Short Track Championships in South Korea due to Coronavirus &#124; Speed Skating Canada|website=speedskating.ca|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Snooker==\n\nThe [[2020 Gibraltar Open]] and its qualifying rounds took place from 11 to 15 March.  For the first day, there was a limit of 100 spectators per session.  On the remaining days, there were no spectators.  A significant number of players withdrew, and there was a shortage of referees, with some early matches played without referees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bizarre times at Gibraltar Open as games played without referees and player brings wrong cue|publisher=[[Metro (British newspaper)|]]|first=Phil|last=Haigh|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/15/gibraltar-open-chaos-12400612/}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 Tour Championship]], originally scheduled for 17 to 22 March, was postponed until 21 July.\n\nThe 2020 [[China Open (snooker)|China Open]], originally scheduled for 30 March to 5 April, was indefinitely postponed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: China Open in Beijing postponed|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/51325726|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=31 Jan 2020|accessdate=31 Mar 2020|}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 World Snooker Championship]], originally scheduled 18 April to 4 May, has been postponed,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/51964887 |title=Coronavirus: World Snooker Championship at Crucible postponed |date=2020-03-20 |accessdate=2020-03-20 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> tentatively until July or August.\n\nThe [[2020 World Women's Snooker Championship]], originally scheduled 22 to 27 June, has been postponed. \n<ref>{{cite web|title=World Women's Championship Postponed|url=https://wst.tv/world-womens-championship-postponed/|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|publisher=[[World Snooker Tour]]}}</ref>\n\n==Squash==\nThe 2020 [[European Squash Individual Championships]], scheduled to take place in [[Eindhoven]], the Netherlands from 29 April to 2 May are cancelled.<ref name=\"nu.nl\"/>\n\n==Surfing==\nThe 2020 [[World Surf League]], which was due to start in Australia on 26 March, is on hold until at least June. The first event of the season, the [[Quiksilver Pro Gold Coast|Corona Open Gold Coast]], was cancelled, while the second and third events, the [[Rip Curl Pro|Rip Curl Pro Bells Beach]] and [[Margaret River Pro]], were postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=WSL Cancels All Events In March |url=https://www.worldsurfleague.com/posts/449880/wsl-cancels-all-events-in-march |website=World Surf League |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=WSL Cancels Or Postpones Events Through May |url=https://www.worldsurfleague.com/posts/450379/wsl-cancels-or-postpones-events-through-may |website=World Surf League |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 ISA World Surfing Games]], scheduled to be held from 9 to 17 May in [[El Salvador]], will now take place from 6 to 14 June in the same location.<ref>{{cite web |title=ISA Postpones Surf City El Salvador ISA World Surfing Games |url=https://www.isasurf.org/isa-postpones-surf-city-el-salvador-isa-world-surfing-games/ |website=International Surfing Association |date=March 22, 2020 |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Swimming==\nThe [[YMCA]] [[Short course|Short Course]] Nationals swim meet is canceled in the United States for the first time since 1947.<ref>{{cite web |title=YMCA Short Course Nationals Canceled For First Time Since 1947 |url=https://swimswam.com/ymca-short-course-nationals-canceled-for-first-time-since-1947/ |website=Swim Swam |date=March 11, 2020 |publisher=Swim Swam |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Table tennis==\nThe [[2020 World Team Table Tennis Championships]] were scheduled to be held from 22 to 29 March in [[Busan]], [[South Korea]]. Provisionally, the event will now be held from 21 to 28 June.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 World Table Tennis Championships postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/02/25/2020-world-table-tennis-championships-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=February 25, 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2020 ITTF-ATTU Asian Cup]] was scheduled to be held from 28 February to 1 March in [[Hainan]], [[China]], but was postponed until later in the year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Postponement of 2020 Asian Cup |url=http://www.attu.org/en/news/1057 |website=ATTU |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFive events on the [[2020 ITTF World Tour]] have also been postponed, including the [[China Open (table tennis)|China Open]] and the [[Japan Open (table tennis)|Japan Open]].<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 ITTF World Tour Japan Open postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/03/10/2020-ittf-world-tour-japan-open-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hong Kong and China Opens postponed due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.ittf.com/2020/03/20/hong-kong-china-opens-postponed-due-covid-19/ |website=ITTF |date=March 20, 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> Four [[Table tennis at the 2020 Summer Olympics \u2013 Qualification|Olympic qualifying events]], scheduled to be held in April, were also postponed.<ref>{{cite web |title=ITTF consider Tokyo 2020 Olympic qualification measures after events postponed |url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1092033/ittf-tokyo-2020-qualification-plans |website=Inside The Games |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis==\nOn March 12, the [[2020 ATP Tour|ATP Tour]] and [[2020 ATP Challenger Tour|ATP Challenger Tour]] were initially suspended for six weeks due to the escalating health and safety issues caused by the coronavirus. Also, the [[2020 WTA Tour|WTA Tour]] were initially suspended for eight weeks. However, due to safety concerns, they extended to suspend until at least before June 8.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.atptour.com/en/news/atp-tour-2020-six-week-suspension-decision |title=ATP Suspends Tour For Six Weeks Due To Public Health & Safety Issues Over COVID-19|date=March 12, 2020 |website=ATP|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, the [[2020 French Open]], originally scheduled for May 24\u2013June 7, was postponed to September 20\u2013October 4.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/sports/tennis/french-open-postponed.html|title=The French Open Is Postponed, to the Surprise of the Tours|last=Clarey|first=Christopher|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Volleyball==\nOn March 13, the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Volleyball|International Volleyball Federation]] (FIVB) decided to postpone the Nations League for [[2020 FIVB Volleyball Men's Nations League|men]] (finals scheduled for [[Turin]], Italy) and [[2020 FIVB Volleyball Women's Nations League|women]] until after the [[2020 Summer Olympics]] caused by the outbreak of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fivb.com/en/about/news/fivb-announces-changes-to-events-calendar?id=90648 |title=FIVB announces changes to events calendar |date=March 13, 2020 |website=FIVB|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Water polo==\n\n===International===\nThe [[2020 Women's Water Polo Olympic Qualification Tournament]] was scheduled to take place in [[Trieste]], [[Italy]], March 8\u201315, 2020. On February 28, 2020, [[FINA|International Swimming Federation]] (FINA) announced that the tournament would be postponed to May 17\u201324 due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fina.org/news/fina-announcement-fina-womens-water-polo-olympic-games-qualification-tournament |date=February 28, 2020 |title=FINA ANNOUNCEMENT: FINA Women's Water Polo Olympic Games Qualification Tournament |publisher=[[FINA]] |website=fina.org |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2020, FINA announced that several international water polo tournaments would be postponed due to the coronavirus pandemic. The [[2020 Men's Water Polo Olympic Qualification Tournament]] due to take place in [[Rotterdam]], [[Netherlands]], March 22\u201329, 2020, would be postponed to May 31 \u2013 June 7. The [[2020 FINA Men's Water Polo World League]] and [[2020 FINA Women's Water Polo World League]] would be postponed to September\u2013October 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fina.org/news/pr-16-first-meeting-fina-covid-19-taskforce |date=March 12, 2020 |title=PR 16 \u2013 First meeting of FINA COVID-19 taskforce |publisher=[[FINA]] |website=fina.org |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\n[[2020 Asian Water Polo Championship]], the Asian continental qualification for the [[Water polo at the 2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Olympic water polo tournament]], was scheduled to take place in [[Nur-Sultan]], [[Kazakhstan]], February 12\u201316, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://astanatimes.com/2020/01/kazakh-capital-to-host-olympics-water-polo-asian-pre-qualification-tournament/ |first=Nurdana |last=Adylkhanova |date=January 31, 2020 |title=Kazakh capital to host Olympics water polo Asian pre-qualification tournament |publisher=Astana Times |website=astanatimes.com |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> In late January the event was cancelled as the Kazakh Government suspended all flights and visas from [[China]] due to concerns about the coronavirus outbreak in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/coronavirus-claims-first-tokyo-olympic-victim-2020-asian-water-polo-championships/ |first=Michael |last=Randazzo |date=13 February 2020 |title=Coronavirus Claims First Tokyo Olympic Victim: 2020 Asian Water Polo Championships |publisher=[[Swimming World]] |website=swimmingworldmagazine.com |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> In mid-February [[Asia Swimming Federation]] decided to use the final ranking of the [[Water polo at the 2018 Asian Games|2018 Asian Games]] to allocate its continental quotas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://total-waterpolo.com/asian-federation-decides-kazakhstan-and-china-goes-to-tokyo/ |first=Ivan |last=Curcic |date=February 14, 2020 |title=Asian Federation decides: Kazakhstan and China go to Tokyo |publisher=Total Waterpolo |website=total-waterpolo.com |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\nOn February 28, 2020, [[LEN|European Swimming League]] (LEN) announced that the match of [[2019\u201320 LEN Champions League]] Day 10 between [[Ferencv\u00e1rosi TC (men's water polo)|Ferencv\u00e1ros]] (Hungary) and [[Pro Recco]] (Italy), and the match of [[2019\u201320 LEN Euro Cup]] semifinal between [[Egri VK]] (Hungary) and [[AN Brescia]] (Italy) would be postponed due to the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.len.eu/?p=16594 |date=February 28, 2020 |title=Two matches postponed \u2013 Euro Cup & Champions League |publisher=[[LEN]] |website=len.eu |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2020, LEN announced that all eight matches of 2019\u201320 LEN Champions League Day 11, the second leg of the [[2019\u201320 LEN Euro League Women]] quarter-finals, and the 2020 men's U19 European Championships qualification tournaments would be postponed to later dates due to the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.len.eu/?p=16631 |date=March 11, 2020 |title=LEN postpones upcoming water polo competitions |publisher=[[LEN]] |website=len.eu |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===North America===\nOn March 11, 2020, the [[USA Water Polo]] (USAWP) announced that the 2020 ODP Girls National Water Polo Championship would be postponed, and the exhibition matches scheduled to be played on March 19\u201321, 2020 in [[California]] between [[United States men's national water polo team|United States]] and [[Spain men's national water polo team|Spain]] men's national water polo teams would be cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://usawaterpolo.org/news/2020/3/11/general-2020-odp-girls-national-championship-postponed-usa-mens-national-team-series-with-spain-canceled.aspx |date=March 11, 2020 |title=2020 ODP Girls National Championship Postponed; USA Men's National Team Series With Spain Canceled |publisher=[[USA Water Polo]] |website=usawaterpolo.org |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2020, USAWP announced that the inaugural USA Water Polo Division III Women's National Championship scheduled for May 8\u201310, 2020 in [[Southern California]] would be rescheduled for May, 2021; and week three of the 2020 National Water Polo League and the 2020 National League Championship/Fisher Cup would be canceled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://usawaterpolo.org/news/2020/3/16/general-usa-water-polo-announces-the-cancellation-of-multiple-upcoming-events.aspx |date=March 16, 2020 |title=USA Water Polo Announces The Cancellation Of Multiple Upcoming Events |publisher=[[USA Water Polo]] |website=usawaterpolo.org |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Oceania===\nOn March 16, 2020, the [[Australian Water Polo]] (WPA) announced that the 2020 [[Australian National Water Polo League]] would be terminated, the 2020 WPA National Championships scheduled to take place in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]] in May would be cancelled, and the 2020 Open Championships (Country and Masters) scheduled to take place in the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Queensland]] in May would be postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.waterpoloaustralia.com.au/news/covid-19-virus-i-changes-to-national-calendar-/ |date=March 16, 2020 |title=COVID-19 virus I Changes to National Calendar |publisher=[[Australian Water Polo]] |website=waterpoloaustralia.com.au |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of major events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Impact of the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in sports]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|sports]]\n[[Category:Sports events cancelled due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n[[Category:Sports events postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic| ]]\n", "name_user": "Wjemather", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGolf:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_on_sports"}
